<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Kuwait-F18s     05-11 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Kuwait-F18s,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Wants to Sell F-18 Fighter-Bombers to Kuwait</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration intends to sell
advanced F-18 fighter-bombers to Kuwait, a deal that would make the
tiny Persian Gulf state the first Arab country to have them, The
Washington Post reported Thursday.
   Citing unidentified sources in the Defense and State
departments, the Post said Kuwait wants to buy 40 of the aircraft
and the administration will notify Congress soon of its intention
to proceed with the sale.
   The deal could be worth $680 million to the manufacturer,
McDonnell Douglas Co., said company spokesman Robert J. O'Brien.
   Several State Department officials contacted by The Associated
Press on Wednesday night said they were unaware that any decision
had been made.
   One noted that Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy
had told a congessional panel Tuesday that ``there was a request
from Kuwait to look at the possibility of selling F-18s.''
   Another source, who also spoke on condition that he not be
named, said, ``I'm not aware that any decision is imminent.''
   ``There's no more than the possibility of a sale,'' he said,
adding that he was skeptical that such a decision would have been
made so quickly.
   ``I would doubt it very seriously,'' he said. ``There's
interest, but a lot of discussion needs to go on before any
decision like that would be considered. I think it's awful early. I
would be very surprised if it's true.''
   The source noted that Kuwait has talked to several countries,
including France, about the possibility of buying advanced aircraft.
   Murphy had told the congressional panel Tuesday that the
administration had alerted Congress that Kuwait was interested in
the F-18s and might prefer them to the less sophisticated F-16s.
   Congress could block the sale.
   The United States is selling F-16s to Bahrain, but it hasn't
sold F-18s to any Arab nation, the Post said.
   The United States and Kuwait have created an increasingly close
security relationship since last year, when the United States
committed naval forces to protect U.S.-flagged ships traveling
through the war-torn Persian Gulf.
   Initially, 11 Kuwaiti ships were re-flagged under this policy
and were given protection by the Navy. The United States recently
revised its policy in the gulf, announcing that it would offer help
to other ships that were attacked by combatants in the 7{-year-old
Iran-Iraq war.
</TEXT>
