<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Korea-Ships     05-11 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Korea-Ships,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea's Shipbuilding Orders Decrease 41.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's shipbuilding orders
decreased more than 40 percent so far this year from the same
period in 1987 because of a rapid appreciation in the country's
currency, industry officials said today.
   Orders received so far consist of 626,300 gross tons of export
ships and 800 gross tons of domestic ships, the officials said.
   But they added that despite the sluggish orders, local
shipmakers still have a combined outstanding order of 6 million
tons, enough to keep them busy until the first half of next year.
   The value of the South Korean won has risen 7.43 percent against
the U.S. dollar so far this year. A higher won makes South Korean
exports more expensive abroad while lowering the prices of foreign
imports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
