<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Argentina-US     05-11 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Argentina-US,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argentina To Take Part In U.S. Naval Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina will take part in naval
exercises with the United States for the first time since the 1982
Falklands War.
   Raul Alconada Sempe, secretary of foreign affairs, said on
Tuesday that Argentina will participate in ``Operation America,''
with United States and several of the Latin countries that once
took part in ``Operation Unitas.''
   Argentina quit the Unitas war games after the Falklands conflict
to protest what it said was U.S. assistance to Britain. The 74-day
war over the islands Argentina calls the Malvinas killed 712
Argentine and 256 British soldiers.
   Final details of the exercises next year are to be completed
this week in the United States while Navy commander Adm. Ramon
Arosa is visiting Washington and Norfolk, Va., Alconada Sempe said.
   Naval vessels from the United States, Brazil, Argentina, Chile
and Peru took part in the Unitas exercises.
</TEXT>
