<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Strike,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1,000 Workers Strike At Contruction Plant In Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 employees stopped
work at a construction plant in southern Yugoslavia and demanded
their March wages and a pay increase, the Tanjug news agency
reported.
   Three hours after the stoppage began Tuesday at the Ramiz Sadiku
plant in Pristina, its director, Nijazi Hoxha, and union leaders
told the workers that March wages would be paid but they would not
receive a pay increase.
   Tanjug said some workers were satisfied with that offer but that
others threatened to continue the strike.
   Officials said a record 365,000 workers took part in more than
1,570 strikes in Yugoslavia last year. The government is planning a
new economic program to make the centrally run economy more market
oriented.
</TEXT>
