<DOCNO> AP880511-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DeficitCommission     05-11 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deficit Commission,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Learns When A Spending Cut Is Not A Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national panel created to solve the
national budget problem is quickly learning that balancing the
government's checkbook first means decoding some artful accounting.
   ``If we did this in business, they'd lock us up,'' said
commission member Lee Iacocca, the Chrysler chairman, after the
National Economic Commission on Tuesday held its first public
hearing on federal budget practices.
   Experts told the commission the history of the convoluted budget
process and the scope of the deficit problem, which has already
saddled taxpayers with paying back principal and interest on more
than $2.5 trillion in debt.
   The tone among the commission members was often jocular in
reaction to testimony about federal budgeting oddities.
   Timothy Muris, a George Mason University professor who until
last year worked at the Office of Management and Budget, described
how a ``cut'' can really be an increase in spending.
   That's because budget writers work from projections of inflated
program costs instead of current spending levels.
   ``I thought I was pretty good when I was in government, but I
was a rank amateur,'' said Washington lawyer Robert Strauss, a
Democrat who is co-chairman of the commission.
   ``Think of it as a 20 percent cut from a 50 percent markup,''
quipped Lane Kirkland, president of the AFL-CIO.
   But former Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger made clear he
didn't think the concept was funny when it applied to Pentagon
spending. Cutting the military short of inflationary increases is
``a very real reduction,'' he said.
   ``There is nothing in the world situation which justifies that
kind of cutback,'' he said, referring to recent budget restraints.
``That is a reality and it is a very unhappy reality for the United
States.''
   Weinberger said the first task of the commission should be to
streamline the budget process, but the witnesses did not agree.
   Commission co-chairman Drew Lewis, President Reagan's former
Transportation secretary and currently the head of the Union
Pacific Railroad, announced that the group intended to produce its
recommendation by Dec. 21, more than two months ahead of its
statutory deadline.
   The revised schedule would give the 12-member commission a great
chance of influencing policies of the next president, who will get
to appoint two more commission members after November's election.
   ``We are not looking at this as a partisan mission,'' said Lewis.
   Carol Cox, executive director of the Committee for a Responsible
Federal Budget, told the commission that reducing the deficit will
be a difficult task and efforts so far have had mixed results.
   ``It seems like we're on a treadmill _ we're running to stay in
place,'' she said.
   But Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y., was optimistic. ``We're
talking about a situation that's within our capacity to solve.''
   Cox said the budget mechanisms have worked well when there's a
consensus to be carried out. Presidents Carter and Reagan both used
it to achieve their initial legislative successes when they took
office, she said.
   Stanley Collender, director of federal budget policy for the
firm of Touche Ross & Co., said procedures could be improved but
``the budget process is not the problem.''
   ``It will always be subservient to politics,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ProductLiability     05-11 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Product Liability,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Product Liability Lawsuit Bill Clears First Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation setting new ground rules for
filing damage suits against manufacturers of hazardous products
survived its initial test in a House committee, but its chances of
passing Congress this year are still considered minimal.
   Consumer activists suffered a setback Tuesday when the House
Energy and Commerce Committee rejected two proposals by Rep. Henry
A. Waxman, D-Calif., that would have expanded the product liability
bill's narrow list of legal grounds available to victims seeking to
recover damages.
   Then, after four hours of bickering, the committee postponed
until Thursday any further action on what Rep. James J. Florio,
D-N.J., called a ``complex and extremely controversial'' measure.
   The bill would establish a uniform federal standard of product
liability that would pre-empt conflicting state laws. Consumer
activists vigorously oppose the measure on the ground that it would
weaken the legal rights of victims of unsafe consumer products.
   It was the first time that the House bill, first introduced in
1979, had advanced to the full committee. Even if it reaches the
House floor, which is uncertain, the bill is virtually assured of a
hostile reception in the Senate, where it was filibustered to death
in late 1986.
   Two consumer groups called it ``a radical bill that would
immunize the manufacturers of defective goods, deprive victims of
compensation for their injuries and expose American consumers to
more hazardous products.''
   Business support for the bill has become increasingly lukewarm
with each revision aimed at meeting consumer demands. ``This is a
watered-down bill,'' said Rep. Norman Lent, R-N.Y., ``but it is
better than none.''
   Other committee Republicans said the bill represented an
important step toward discouraging ``frivolous'' damage suits,
reversing the escalating cost of liability insurance premiums and
bolstering the competitiveness of U.S. products on world markets.
   The committee's first day of debate focused on a compromise
plan, drafted by Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., at the request of Rep.
John Dingell, D-Mich., the panel's chairman, which was aimed at
making the bill more acceptable to consumer groups and moderate
committee Democrats.
   Charging that ``we are about to emasculate the product liability
system,'' Waxman tried unsuccessfully to restore some of the legal
grounds for damage suits in the states that would be pre-empted by
a uniform federal standard.
   Dingell voted with opponents in defeating Waxman's pair of
consumer-backed amendments by roll call votes of 29-12 and 30-12.
   Under the bill approved by Florio's commerce subcommittee last
December, a manufacturer could escape liability for damages if he
did not know _ or could not know _ of a design defect with
knowledge ``reasonably available'' to him, or if there were no
feasible alternative design.
   This restriction would not apply if the consumer could establish
that the product was egregiously unsafe, that an ordinary consumer
would not know of the product's risks and if the product had little
or no usefulness.
   The Synar plan would require only that the plaintiff prove that
the product was so unsafe compared with its usefulness that it
should not have been marketed. Synar also would put the burden of
proof on the manufacturer to show that a design defect could not be
discovered and that an alternative design was not feasible.
   Leaders of four consumer organizations complained to Dingell on
April 27 that Synar's plan ``still falls far short of protecting
the legal rights of individuals injured by unreasonably dangerous
and defective products.''
   Underscoring the bill's poor prospects, Rep. Jim Bates,
D-Calif., drew laughter at one point in the debate by referring to
Synar's plan as ``a killer amendment to a bill that's already
dead.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
