<HEAD>Henry Winker Tells Youths About Fulfilling Their Dreams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Henry Winkler told 120 outstanding Los
Angeles students that they can fulfill their dreams even if the
obstacles seem insurmountable.
   ``I wasn't very good in school,'' admitted Winkler, who gained
fame as the character ``Fonzie'' on television's ``Happy Days.''
   ``I have dyslexia,'' Winkler said referring to a learning
disorder that impairs reading ability. ``I was told that I was
never going to be able to live out my dream.''
   Instead, Winkler went on to graduate from college, and earned a
master's degree in drama at Yale University. The rest is TV history.
   ``I dreamed of doing what I do now,'' said Winkler, who works
primarily as a producer of the TV series ``MacGyver.''
   Winkler was among the hosts Tuesday at the Los Angeles Unified
School District's ``Youth Recognition Day'' for outstanding
students ranging from fifth to 12th grade.
