<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bennett     05-11 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bennett,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett Describes Self as Education Department's Savior</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William J. Bennett says
his department is now much less likely to be eliminated, and that
he deserves the credit.
   Bennett's boast came Tuesday during a typically contentious
appearance before a congressional committee, replete with the
taunts and tantrums that have marked almost every Capitol Hill
exchange between lawmakers and the education secretary.
   One day after Bennett announced plans to step down in
mid-September, Sen. Lowell Weicker accused him of having shirked
his responsibilities to poor and handicapped students aided by
federal programs.
   ``In the course of your tenure, you have chosen to go ahead and
ravage these programs,'' said Weicker, R-Conn., referring to budget
cuts sought on a nearly annual basis by the department.
   ``Why didn't you concentrate on what was your responsibility?''
Weicker asked. ``I have difficulty understanding your preoccupation
with everybody else's business. ... I find it incredible that
nothing has been achieved in your specific charges.''
   Bennett defended his interest in state and local education
efforts during what he termed probably his final appearance before
the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on education and other
agencies. ``The best federal program is the program that's deployed
well at the local level,'' he sid.
   President Reagan came into office pledging to dissolve the
Education Department and Bennett conceded under questioning that he
still does not see a real need for it, other than to spark debate.
   What, asked an irritated Weicker, would you think of teachers
who see no real need for their jobs?
   ``They shouldn't be in a classroom,'' Bennett replied.
   ``Well, you shouldn't be in the Department of Education,''
Weicker snapped. ``What kind of commitment does that show?''
   ``I made a hell of a commitment. You just didn't like the
direction,'' Bennett retorted. ``I was damn successful. You're mad
at me because we were a lot more successful than you thought we'd
be.''
   In fact, Bennett said, he has done such a good job that the
question of the department's future is probably moot.
   ``It's much less likely you'll see abolition of the Department
of Education in the future, largely because of me,'' he said. ``A
lot of people think the department's been transformed.''
   Bennett contended he had as much responsibility to lead ``an
intense national conversation about education'' as to oversee
federal programs.
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., the subcommittee chairman, has been
highly critical of Bennett but defended the secretary's conception
of his job. When he voted in favor of creating the department,
Chiles said, ``I hoped there would be a national spokesman ... I
quite agree with you that that is your role.''
   The administration has sought deep cuts in education spending
for every fiscal year except 1985 and 1989 _ the years for which
proposals were submitted during presidential election campaigns.
   Bennett repeatedly has lectured lawmakers about the need to
restrain spending and told them more money does not necessarily
produce better education. For their part, lawmakers have blasted
Bennett for consistently agreeing to cuts far deeper than those
proposed for any other department.
   The result has been a continuing series of stormy, sarcastic
sessions with various congressional panels, including the one
Tuesday.
   ``Mr. Secretary, I know you're going to miss these lovefests,''
said Chiles.
   Bennett indicated later that lawmakers may not have seen the
last of him. He said he wouldn't rule out returning to a Cabinet
post _ even possibly education secretary _ in a future Republican
administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
