<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContractFraud     05-11 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contract Fraud,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Tougher Penalties for Contract Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A unanimously passed House bill would raise
penalties against contractors convicted of defrauding the federal
government, and its chief sponsor predicts the measure will stop a
flood of such cases.
   ``Procurement fraud is robbing the government of hundreds of
millions of dollars a year, and in some instances costing peoples'
lives,'' chief sponsor William J. Hughes, D-N.J., said following
Tuesday's 419-0 vote.
   The measure, which now goes to the Senate, would apply to any
procurement contract of $1 million or more in which the government
was bilked out of at least $250,000. Procurement contracts are
those providing a product rather than a service.
   Hughes said the bill would apply to some 10,000 existing
contracts.
   The legislation would establish a maximum prison sentence of 10
years, and a minimum two-year sentence for cases involving a
foreseeable and substantial risk of personal injury.
   Hughes said the risk could result from substitution of inferior
products by contractors, especially in military parts.
   Current law permits fines based on the monetary gain to the
defendant or the loss to the federal government.
   The House bill would add a new fine of up to $10 million in
cases in which the risk of injury is involved.
   A reward system would permit payments of up to $250,000 from the
criminal fines for information leading to a conviction.
   The measure also contains protection for government
whistleblowers who provide information leading to convictions.
   Fraud in procurement contracts has involved overcharges,
malfunctioning equipment and product substitution, Hughes said.
   The General Accounting Office reported in January that based on
known cases, the estimated loss to the government in procurement
fraud was $387.4 million in a one-year period ending March 31, 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
