<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Postmaster     05-11 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Postmaster,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service Cuts Could End by Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Post office window service and collections
could be back to normal by the end of summer, but that won't mean
the end of the agency's financial struggles, according to
Postmaster General Anthony Frank.
   Frank said Tuesday that he is committed to restoring service
that was cut earlier this year in the face of congressionally
imposed budget restrictions.
   But reopening counters and restoring Sunday sorting and
collection means finding $9 million a month in savings somewhere
else, he said.
   With luck, he said, that can be accomplished by late summer. But
he added that services will be restored only when he is sure that
they can be kept open.
   Hundreds of construction projects for new postal facilities also
were canceled or delayed to save money.
   ``Long after people forget about the windows being closed,''
building projects will still be delayed, land will have been sold
to someone else and construction costs will be even higher, Frank
said.
   Frank, who took over as postmaster on March 1, said that
explaining the need for service cuts at the same time rates are
rising has been difficult.
   The rate increases imposed on April 3 don't help, he said,
because the accounting system mandated by Congress results in the
increased income being counted as a reduction in the national debt,
not as extra money for the agency.
   On other topics, Frank said:
   _A system may be considered in which notices would automatically
be sent out for people filing change or address forms.
   _The agency should help serve as a go-between for other federal
agencies and the public, such as by making catalogs of Government
Printing Office booklets available in lobbies. The current program
to deliver an AIDS booklet to every home is a good example, he said.
   _It is ``amazing'' how many suggestions for new stamps he
receives. He said he doesn't see anything wrong with issuing a
stamp to honor singer Elvis Presley, although so far the
independent committee that makes the final choices has turned down
that idea.
   The budget problems may be eased by a House bill that would
remove the Postal Service from the federal budget. The agency had
not been part of the budget until 1985.
   ``You really can't include us in the budget process, when we
don't use taxes,'' Frank said. Direct subsidies to the agency were
ended several years ago.
   In addition to restoring the services that were cut earlier,
Frank said he wants to find ways to add other services.
   For example, automated postal tellers now under development
could be placed in shopping malls, more markets and other stores
encouraged to sell stamps at their checkouts and automation
improved to speed post office lobby service.
   Frank said battling for renewed public confidence means both
improved service and improving perception of that service.
   He described a program in which postal carriers placed specific
items in home mailboxes and, later, asked the residents to fill out
forms indicating whether those items had been received.
   When the item was a large white envelope, only 0.3 percent
reported that it had not been delivered, he said. But when it was a
commercial catalog, 11 percent of the people who received it
reported that it had not arrived.
   ``We know the items were delivered'' but the perceived value of
the item makes a difference, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
