<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ColemanTrial     05-11 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coleman Trial,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``A Lot Of Broken Hearts'' Over Coleman Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The life sentences and possibility of parole
given a once-condemned killer for his role in killing six members
of the Alday family have left ``a lot of broken hearts'' in
southwest Georgia, said one family member.
   Wayne Carl Coleman was sentenced Tuesday to six life prison
terms after the jury that convicted him deliberated almost a week
without voting the death sentence prosecutors won in his trial 14
years ago.
   By law, the life sentences were automatic because the jury could
not agree. The 11 members of the Alday family present when the
sentence was announced broke into tears.
   ``We do know we had some friends on the jury and we certainly
appreciate them,'' said Bud Alday, brother of two victims, who
discovered their bodies. ``We had some enemies, too, and they're
going to have to live with it.''
   ``Everybody down here is just as sick as they can be. There are
a lot of broken hearts in Seminole County,'' Bobby Alday, nephew of
victims Ned and Aubrey Alday, said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
   Ned and his brother Aubrey, along with Ned's sons Jimmy, Jerry
and Chester, were shot to death in Jerry Alday's mobile home on May
14, 1973, after they walked in on a burglary.
   Jerry's wife, Mary Alday, was repeatedly raped, then driven to a
wooded area, where she was again raped, sodomized, shot and left to
die on an ant hill.
   Coleman, Carl Isaacs and George Dungee _ who had escaped from a
Maryland prison camp _ were convicted in Seminole County of the
murders and sentenced to death. The convictions were overturned in
1985 by a federal appeals panel that said pretrial publicity
influenced the original trial jury.
   ``It's been awful hard. We've been waiting for 15 years to see
justice,'' said Ernestine Alday, widow of Ned and mother of Jimmy,
Jerry and Chester. She said faith in God has sustained the family:
``He's going to be the judge.''
   Coleman was retried during the past several weeks in DeKalb
Superior Court. Isaacs was convicted in Perry in January and again
sentenced to die; Dungee faces a retrial later this year in
Columbus.
   Coleman is immediately eligible for parole review under a 1964
law requiring a review after seven years in prison, and will go
before the state Board of Pardons and Paroles next month, said
board spokesman Silas Moore.
   But State Attorney General Michael Bowers disagreed, saying
Coleman is covered by a 1983 law that would require him to serve 30
years before a parole hearing.
   Coleman's attorney Tom West said the life sentences were
justified. ``We can only assume that if Wayne had had a fair trial
15 years ago, he would have gotten a life sentence,'' he said.
   ``Wayne is satisfied that his life has been spared,'' West said.
   Faded ``Remember the Aldays'' bumper stickers still can be found
on a few cars in Seminole County, a sparsely populated area where
most people are farmers. They don't like that their tax dollars
have financed such a long judicial process, said Bobby Alday, who
was not in court Tuesday.
   ``I think Seminole County is tired of getting these people TVs
and tennis rackets,'' he said. ``Without a doubt, these people,
they don't deserve a second chance. They've not shown a bit of
remorse.''
   Alday said the numerous appeals and lengthy debate in the case
since the murders took place have placed a strain on the closeknit
family, whose ``big family reunions and such'' have now ``gone by
the wayside.''
   ``Most people down here would like to move on and put this
behind them, yet it'll be years to come before everybody down here
can move on with their lives,'' Alday said.
   ``When your family's been wiped out, it's not easy to put it
aside,'' he continued. ``It's been a long hard road for everybody
down here.''
</TEXT>
