<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Berlin, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0739,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Berlin Planning Quiet 100th Birthday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with 75 people serenading
Berlin, picking up 4th graf ``Any list...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 75 people gathered outside the home of
Irving Berlin early Wednesday, serenading the composer of dozens of
famous songs on his 100th birthday.
   Berlin planned a quiet day at home with relatives Wednesday
avoiding the limelight as he has for decades.
   The group assembled outside the five-story Manhattan townhouse
at midnight Tuesday to sing ``Happy Birthday,'' Berlin's ``Always''
and ``The Songs of Irving Berlin,'' an original composition by
neighbor, songwriter and fan John Wallowitch.
   ``Sing softly with great love,'' Wallowitch instructed, and the
group crooned:
   ``Over the years, through laughter and tears, while strolling
down memory lane, we sang all the songs of Irving Berlin and we'll
sing them all over, again and again.''
   ``It's one of the few songs he doesn't own the copyright to,''
Wallowitch, who organized the caroling, said earlier.
   Berlin did not appear.
   Any list of the 20th-century's most popular songs would be
filled with Berlin's contributions, including ``God Bless
America,'' ``White Christmas,'' ``Easter Parade,'' ``Alexander's
Ragtime Band,'' ``Russian Lullaby,'' ``There's No Business Like
Show Business,'' ``Puttin' on the Ritz,'' ``Blue Skies,'' ``Cheek
to Cheek,'' ``Always'' and ``What'll I Do?''
   Altogether, Berlin has written about 1,500 songs, some of which
will be heard again Wednesday night when the American Society of
Composers, Authors and Publishers holds a tribute at Carnegie Hall.
   Among performers scheduled to appear are Frank Sinatra, Willie
Nelson, Jerome Robbins, Isaac Stern, Ray Charles and Garrison
Keillor. Berlin is a charter member of ASCAP, founded in 1914.
   Nonetheless, ``He won't be at Carnegie Hall,'' his secretary,
Hilda Schneider, said. ``His birthdays are always spent very
quietly with family.''
</TEXT>
