Haun sted Hahn; EDITS next to last graf to conform.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of four members of a family
were discovered in their home Tuesday night, and authorities
believed the deaths were the result of murder-suicide.
   Police were called after a relative looked in a front window and
saw two bodies on the floor.
   Police identified the victims as Chester Duchow, 35; his wife,
Doris, 34; and their children, 7-year-old Tom and 9-year-old Frank.
The parents appeared to have died of gunshot wounds and the
children apparently were strangled with pieces of cord, police said.
   Lt. David Haun of the Springfield Police Department said
authorities believed the father, Chester Duchow, killed his wife
and children and then killed himself. A note outlining personal and
family problems was found in the house, Haun said.
   ``It is a reasonable assumption this is a case of triple
homicide and suicide,'' said Dr. Erwin Busiek, medical examiner for
Springfield and Greene County.
   Busiek said the children may have been dead 12 to 24 hours.
Police said they believed the children were killed first and Mrs.
Duchow was killed when she came home from shopping.
   The bodies of the parents were found in the living room of the
northwest Springfield home, Haun said. The children's bodies were
discovered in a loft in an upstairs bedroom. All were found shortly
before 9 p.m., police said.
   Police said a relative stopped by the house and saw the bodies
through a window.
   Donna Wagner, who lives across the street, said the husband had
been unemployed for some time.
