<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CatastrophicHealth     05-11 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Catastrophic Health,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prescriptions, Premiums Dominate Conferee Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate conferees are getting down to
the final rounds in their effort to resolve differences over a
measure to protect the 31 million Medicare recipients against
financial devastation from serious illness.
   After months of behind-the-scenes negotiations, the full
conference met for the first time publicly on Tuesday to discuss
the first major expansion of the program in its 23-year history.
   The House and Senate both passed legislation on catastrophic
health insurance by overwhelming margins last year. Although more
encompassing and expensive, the legislation is built on a basic
framework devised by Health and Human Services Secretary Otis R.
Bowen and embraced by President Reagan.
   While no formal timetable was set, the conference committee is
expected to shape a final bill for presentation to the two houses
later this month with an eye toward having the legislation ready
for President Reagan's signature next month.
   On Tuesday, both sides agreed on only two points: that major
disagreements still separate them and that the time has come to
resolve them.
   Sen. George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, head of the Senate Finance
subcommittee that did preliminary work on the Senate bill,
cautioned against adopting a final version too expensive for the
elderly to bear. He expressed particular concern about including
the more expansive House version of a new prescription drug benefit.
   ``We can always expand these programs, but it is very hard to
contract them,'' said Mitchell.
   But Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., suggested a prescription drug
program probably would be to the only additional benefit realized
by millions of Americans who will not face a lengthy hospital stay.
``They've got to see something out of this legislation,'' he said.
   The differences concern the level of additional protection the
legislation will provide and how the costs are to be spread among
the 31 million Medicare recipients who will have to pay for the
Although the measures are substantially more expansive, and
expensive, than proposed by the administration,
   The legislation does not provide long-term nursing home care
under Medicare _ a complicated and even more expensive issue put
off until next year _ but would shield Medicare beneficiaries
against annual out-of-pocket doctor and hospital bills.
   The cap would be $1,043 in the latest House suggested compromise
and $1,370 in the Senate compromise offer now on the bargaining
table.
   Medicare now covers only the first 60 days of a hospital stay in
a given year and pays only 80 percent of doctor bills, no matter
how high they range.
   The major disagreement on the benefit side is over prescription
drugs _ how much to pay and how soon to start paying.
   On the cost side, the major disagreement is how to distribute
the additional premium Medicare enrollees will have to pay _
particularly the so-called supplemental premium that is tantamount
to an income tax increase for the estimated 50 percent of retirees
who would be subject to it.
   The only other additional cost for the estimated 50 percent of
the elderly not now subject to income tax would be a flat monthly
premium of about $8 to $10 per month, depending on the shape of the
final legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0812EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ExitPolls     05-11 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exit Polls,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Supported Across Ideological Spectrum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis found broad
ideological backing along with support from one-time Reagan
Democrats in the West Virginia and Nebraska primaries, both of
which could provide important boosts in a general election campaign.
   Ideologically, ``Dukakis is a Rorschach test,'' said ABC News
poll analyst Doug Muzzio. ``Voters of different ideologies look at
Dukakis and are seeing what they want to see. In a sense he's all
ideologies to all voters.''
   ABC's exit polls of voters Tuesday found that a majority of
liberals, a majority of moderates and a plurality of conservatives
said Dukakis' views were ``just right'' as opposed to too liberal
or too conservative.
   ``Certainly he has not been painted among these two electorates
as a liberal,'' a likely Republican tactic, Muzzio said. Instead,
Dukakis seemed acceptable to voters across the spectrum of
ideologies in his party.
   One reason for pause in the Dukakis camp, Muzzio suggested, was
that about 30 percent of the voters said they were not sure of
Dukakis' ideology. But while that could suggest a lack of
self-definition, it also could be turned into an advantage in a
general election campaign, he said.
   Another good sign for November was Dukakis' support from
Democrats who voted for President Reagan in 1984. Twenty-three
percent of the Democratic voters in West Virginia and 22 percent in
Nebraska were Reagan Democrats; 73 percent of them in West Virginia
and 78 percent in Nebraska said they would vote for Dukakis over
George Bush, ABC found.
   ``Dukakis could bring home the Reagan Democrats,'' said Muzzio.
The finding has been consistent, he noted, since ABC started asking
the question in its Connecticut primary exit poll March 29.
   ABC's poll said Jackson in Nebraska on Tuesday scored one of his
best showings of the primary season with white voters, winning 24
percent. He has done better only in Vermont, where he ABC had him
winning 32 percent.
   Jackson, who appealed to distressed farmers in Nebraska for
their votes, won majorities there in two issue groups _ voters who
cited the poor and elderly as a key issue, and those who cited the
ability to bring changes.
   Still, Dukakis won all white subgroups in Nebraska and won
overwhelming majorities of voters of all groups other than blacks
in West Virginia. The key issue to the most voters in both states
was job protection, and Dukakis won a majority of that group.
   Dukakis made some inroads into the small bloc of black votes,
winning 32 percent of the black vote in West Virginia and 11
percent in Nebraska. Blacks made up 4 percent of the total in West
Virginia and 5 percent in Nebraska, and the margin of sampling
error is high for such a small group in a poll.
   Among all voters, the error margin was 5 percentage points in
the surveys.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
