<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hopes To Clinch Nomination In Next Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, with two
more primary wins, says he hopes to clinch the Democratic
presidential nomination in the final month of the primary season.
   ``I hope by the 8th of June we are at or closing in on the
nomination,'' Dukakis said. The last round of Democratic primaries
is June 7, and includes the big states of California and New Jersey.
   ``I'm working hard, vigorously and I hope successfully, to see
if we can wrap it up,'' the governor told reporters here Tuesday
night.
   Dukakis was spending most of today at the Statehouse in Boston
before heading to New Jersey for a fundraiser.
   Despite his successes in West Virginia and Nebraska, where he
scored landslide wins over Jesse Jackson, Dukakis was not writing
off his remaining Democratic rival.
   ``We're taking none of these primaries for granted,'' he said of
upcoming races. ``They're all very, very important.''
   With primaries set next Tuesday in Oregon and a week later in
Idaho, followed up by the primaries of June 7, ``It's going to be a
very lively month,'' Dukakis said.
   Montana and New Mexico also hold their primaries on the final
day of the Democratic season.
   Dukakis, looking toward the fall, predicted he could be the
``unifier'' who would enable Democrats to put one of their own in
the White House.
   ``I sense a greater desire on the part of rank and file
Democrats and party leaders across the country to unify and come
together,'' he said at a news conference at Marymount Manhattan
College.
   ``I think we sense that victory is out there to be won and we've
got one of the best chances we've had in years to win a
presidential victory. And I'm somebody who is a unifier.''
   Dukakis says his recent string of victories ``reflects a desire
on the part of the people of this country for ... very strong
economic leadership, leadership that's committed to uniting this
country and to building a very strong future of full employment and
real opportunity for all of our citizens.''
   ``That's what I stand for and I think that's why we're doing so
well,'' he said.
   Dukakis also took a dig at President Reagan even as he expressed
a bit of sympathy over the flap created by the book written by
former White House Chief of Staff Donald Regan.
   ``Like most people who've been in public life for a long time, I
abhor kiss-and-tell staff people,'' Dukakis said.
   Asked whether he believed the public had a right to know about
Nancy Reagan's reported reliance on astrology, the governor
answered: ``I can only speak for my own first lady ... she
appreciates the stars, but she doesn't consult them.''
</TEXT>
