<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSFiring     05-11 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Firing,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worker Says Dismissal Violates Government's Own Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Justice Department employee with AIDS
says he was fired despite a new federal policy touted as
``enlightened and compassionate'' that prohibits discrimination
against government workers with the disease, according to a
published report.
   The Washington Post reported today that Mark Gregory was fired
from the department's Community Relations Service on April 25,
several weeks after the Office of Personnel Management announced
employees with acquired immune deficiency syndrome would be treated
the same as those with other serious illnesses.
   ``The only reason they fired me is because I'm sick and because
I have AIDS,'' said Gregory, 30, who is undergoing experimental
treatment at the National Institutes of Health.
   Gregory, who lost his health insurance when he was fired, is
appealing the dismissal.
   Federal guidelines on workers with AIDS were issued in March,
when OPM Director Constance Horner said, ``The federal government,
as an enlightened and compassionate employer concerned with the
health and welfare of its employees, has an obligation to show the
way in addressing the realities of the AIDS epidemic.''
   The Justice Department says Gregory was fired not because of his
illness but because of the 30 days work he has missed since he was
hired as a clerk-typist last July. Gregory says most of the missed
days were spent participating in the experimental NIH program.
   ``He's not being singled out,'' said department spokesman Brad
Marman. ``He was discharged because he could not perform the job on
a full-time basis adequately.''
   Marman told the Post that Gregory was considered a probationary
employee when he was hired, although both he and Gregory's
supervisor would not talk in detail about his case.
   Diagnosed as having AIDS-related complex in October 1987,
Gregory said he took 10 days leave without pay on the advice of his
supervisor and another 14 days to participate in the NIH program.
He took another six days off after his lover died.
</TEXT>
