<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0408EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GeneBanks     05-11 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gene Banks,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to correct category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Breeding With Overseas Livestock Could Lower U.S. Meat Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELTSVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exotic livestock breeds including Soviet
sheep that reproduce much more quickly than American breeds could
lower U.S. meat prices if they were available here, an Agriculture
Department official says.
   The American public should therefore demand that the government
establish a program to gather and evaluate different breeds of
livestock from abroad, said the official, Keith Gregory of the U.S.
Meat Animal Research Service, part of the department's Agricultural
Research Service.
   ``It is in the public interest to have such a program,'' Gregory
said Tuesday.
   The Agriculture Department is spending $26 million this year in
an ongoing effort to gather, store and evaluate cultivated and wild
plants so that breeders will have a kind of library of genetic
traits to choose from in developing improved food crops, Gregory
said.
   Such a program has never been developed to provide what can be
thought of as ``gene banks'' for livestock breeders, Gregory said.
   The federal government should step in because commercial
breeders have neither the capital nor the expertise to collect and
evaluate exotic livestock species, Gregory said. He spoke at a
press conference held in conjunction with the Agricultural Research
Service's annual scientific symposium in Beltsville.
   The department's efforts to conserve plant ``germplasm'' _
genetic material that can be used to regenerate plants _ has been
criticized as inadequate.
   Department scientists agree that the plant germplasm collection
and storage system should be expanded, but they say it is difficult
to convince other government officials and the public of the need
for additional funds.
   The Office of Management and Budget recently acted to hold next
year's budget equal to the current $26 million, said Henry Shands,
coordinator of the National Plant Germplasm System. Officials had
hoped for an increase.
   ``USDA has not developed the clientele to insure that these
programs get the support they require,'' said Lawrence Busch, a
sociologist at the University of Kentucky who specializes in
agricultural issues.
   Of the various animals raised for meat in the United States, the
turkey is the only one native to this country, and it was bred in
Europe before becoming established here, Gregory said.
   He noted, for example, that Romanov sheep from the Soviet Union
and Finn sheep from Finland reproduce much more quickly than
traditional U.S. breeds.
   ``Those are two sources of genes that might enable us to
increase the breeding rate,'' Gregory said. A higher breeding rate
means lower production costs, and ultimately lower costs for the
consumer.
   The two breeds have their drawbacks _ they produce less wool and
it is of lower quality, he said. Nevertheless, their genes could be
useful in the development of improved breeds, he said.
   Bringing such animals into the country involves expensive
quarantining procedures that can last years, Gregory said.
   In the case of sheep, for example, the animals must be kept in
complete isolation for five years to be certain they don't carry
the scrapie virus, a potentially devastating disease. Only then can
breeding experiments begin.
   Recent advances in biotechnology now allow sperm and embryos to
be frozen, providing new means of storing genetic resources.
   Research also suggests that it might be possible to wash frozen
embryos so that they are free of viruses, thus eliminating costly
quarantines, Gregory said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AlaskaOil     05-11 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alaska Oil,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Accused of Withholding Critical Report on Alaskan Oil
Drilling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Interior Department report says there has
been environmental damage from oil drilling in Alaska but
apparently nothing to scuttle an administration request to open the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to petroleum development, a
congressional aide says.
   The report has been withheld from Congress, however, and the
copies of the report have been made available only through
unofficial channels, say aides to Rep. George Miller, D-Calif.
   Miller is chairman of the House Interior water and power
resources subcommittee considering the administration request to
allow oil rigs in the nation's largest wildlife refuge.
   In April 1987, Miller had requested a report from the Fish and
Wildlife Service on the environmental impact of drilling in
Alaska's North Slope.
   Miller's aides said Tuesday the report prepared by the service's
Fairbanks office was completed and sent to the Interior Department
last December but never sent to Miller.
   Philip Million, a spokesman for the Fish and Wildlife Service,
said Tuesday night he had not seen the report, but said he had been
told ``that it was a regional report prepared in Alaska and there
were disagreements within the regional office on the conclusions
reached in that report.''
   Million said the report either has been or is being modified,
but that he didn't know what conclusions the final version will
draw.
   The report deals with existing drilling activities at Prudhoe
Bay, about 70 miles west of the refuge, and the Trans-Alaska
pipeline.
   The information from the report did not represent any ``smoking
gun'' that could, by itself, torpedo the administration's request
for permission to drill in the refuge, the aide said.
   ``What makes this such a big deal is they sat on it,'' said the
aide, who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   Another aide commented: ``The real issue is whether Congress is
being told the whole story. They're not.''
   The new report by the Fairbanks office supports some testimony
given to Congress that populations of predators like bears and
wolves have diminished since Prudhoe opened. The decline has been
blamed on the arrival of an industrial complex and illegal hunting.
   But the document also said the caribou herd in the area has
grown during development of Prudhoe and that no major oil spills
had occurred.
   The report said air pollution has been a problem at Prudhoe, but
said that dust has been more of a problem than chemical pollutants,
the Miller aides said.
   They added that the report cited pollution of fresh water
because of drilling operations and alterations in natural fresh
water flows because of construction.
   In testimony before congressional committees considering the
future of the refuge, Interior Department witnesses have
acknowledged problems at Prudhoe with environmental protection and
enforcement but they said Prudhoe has improved in recent years and
those lessons would be applied to any drilling in the refuge.
   Miller's aides related that another section of the report said
22,500 birds were lost or displaced from Prudhoe.
   The aides noted, however, that the report did not tell another
side of the Prudhoe story: It has produced 5 billion barrels of oil
and brought about $100 billion worth of economic benefits to the
nation.
   Miller's subcommittee has tentatively scheduled another round of
hearings on the refuge question for early next month. Bills to open
the refuge have been approved by the House Merchant Marine and
Fisheries Committee and the Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee.
   The Reagan administration and the oil industry have been pushing
Congress since the start of 1987 to allow development on the
refuge, which they say may hold oil deposits to rival Prudhoe Bay's
and which could help alleviate the nation's growing dependence on
imported oil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Summit     05-11 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Summit,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Initiatives Unlikely At June Economic Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To Canadian Finance Minister Michael Wilson, the
Oct. 19 stock market crash was a bracing ``tap on the shoulder''
but there is no cause for alarm about the world economy.
   The Economic Summit of the Group of Seven major industrialized
countries, to be held in Toronto on June 19-21, is therefore likely
to reaffirm current policies rather than adopt sweeping new
initiatives, Wilson told a group of foreign correspondents Tuesday.
   ``I wouldn't look for major new statements, major new
decisions,'' he said.
   But in another pre-summit briefing, the government-funded
Economic Council of Canada took a much gloomier view of economic
realities.
   The council's deputy chairman, Harvey Lazar, said failure to
correct the ``fundamental disequilibrium in the world economy'' _
evidenced by continued huge U.S. deficits _ points toward another
economic shock. He feared a ``hard landing'' in which interest
rates will soar along with unemployment.
   ``We've gotten off relatively easy so far,'' Lazar said of the
surprising resilience of major economies following the market
crash. ``The question is whether between now and the election of a
new U.S. government, the world can somehow muddle through. There
remains a serious risk we may not.''
   He said the United States must either raise taxes or slash
spending to attack its deficits, but either course is unlikely in
the final months of Ronald Reagan's presidency.
   With that major problem untackled, Lazar said, the summit's
``scope is pretty limited.''
   Wilson maintained that since the October crash, the Group of
Seven countries _ the United States, Japan, West Germany, France,
Britain, Italy and Canada _ have patched up differences and
cooperated to stabilize markets.
   He also pointed to a clear shift in the U.S. economy from
consumption to exports, while Japan and West Germany have moved to
increase imports to shave their trade surpluses.
   ``Inflationary pressures on a worldwide basis aren't there,'' he
said, adding that the recent ``upward creep'' of interest rates
should not derail Group of Seven policies.
   But senior forecaster Ross Preston of the independently-run
Economic Council said: ``We're still lacking a true consensus about
how to manage international economic policy.''
   He said that since the mid-1970's, ``people have been resistant
to face up to the fact that real growth has declined.''
   With ``macroeconomic'' fiscal and monetary policies fixed,
Canadian officials said the summit will likely focus on
``microeconomic'' structural factors such as tax reform,
deregulation and privatization.
   Reform of land prices and the goods distribution system in
Japan, the extension of shopping hours in West Germany and tax
incentives to boost the level of bank savings in the United States
are examples of ``micro'' initiatives that could have a major
impact, Sylvia Ostry, Canada's ambassador for multilateral trade
negotiations, told reporters.
   She said summit leaders may discuss a proposal for the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which governs world trade, to
monitor microeconomic factors in the same way the International
Monetary Fund surveys macroeconomic policies.
   Wilson said he saw no need for changes in Canada's interest rate
or other economic policies, despite the latest figures showing
domestic growth stalled in January and February, after 3.9 percent
real growth in the gross domestic product last year.
   ``We're still nicely on track and I see no reason to change,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     05-11 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Reportedly Confident About U.S. Drug Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega met with
his American lawyers to discuss fighting U.S. drug trafficking
indictments against him. One said the general was encouraged at how
the case is going.
   Two Florida attorneys met on Tuesday with the general, who has
survived U.S. economic and other pressures aimed at forcing him to
resign as head of the nation's 15,000-strong Defense Forces and
leave Panama.
   The lawyers are Raymond Takiff and Frank Rubino, who were
contracted by Noriega after he was indicted in Florida in February.
   After the meeting, Rubino described Noriega, the power behind
the civilian government, as ``very encouraged'' by developments in
the case and ``very confident'' about having weathered U.S.
pressure to oust him.
   According to Noriega, the Reagan administration wants him out
because of his opposition to what he calls efforts in the United
States to retain control of the Panama Canal. Under the 1977 canal
treaties, the United States must relinquish control of the canal by
midnight Dec. 31, 1999.
   Noriega won his first legal battle last month when U.S. District
Judge William Hooveler ruled he did not have to appear in court in
Florida for hearings on his challenge of the indictments.
   The U.S. government has imposed economic sanctions on Panama and
encouraged domestic dissent in an effort to force the ouster of
Noriega.
   Washington still recognizes the presidency of Eric Arturo
Delvalle, who has been in hiding since his ouster Feb. 26, a day
after he tried to fire the general, who has led the Defense Forces
since 1983.
</TEXT>
