<DOCNO> AP880511-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Indians     05-11 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Indians,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Leaders Begin Talks With Sandinistas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan Indian rebel leaders, their
support from the United States shrinking, resumed peace talks with
Sandinista government officials aimed at restoring some of their
native rights.
   ``We have sought dialogue with the Sandinista government because
our people are in a very difficult situation and because aid
approved by the American Congress has diminished,'' said Brooklyn
Rivera, a leader of the Yatama organization of Nicaragua's
Caribbean coast Indians.
   ``In Honduras, the government has closed our rearguard and has
adopted a hostile attitude against our organization while the
Americans say we are acting against our own interests and have cut
aid,'' Rivera told The Associated Press on Tuesday, when talks
resumed.
   Rivera began negotiating in February with Interior Minister
Tomas Borge, who heads a national commission on autonomy for the
Caribbean coast. They failed to reach concrete agreements in a
meeting in March ``but we delved deeper into the proposals'' made
by both sides, Rivera said.
   Yatama, which claims to have 2,000 guerrillas, has fought the
Sandinistas for regional autonomy along the coast. The Indians also
resisted any exercise of authority over them by the rightist,
pro-American Somoza dynasty which ruled Nicaragua for 42 years
until the Sandinistas came to power in 1979.
   The Indian organization does not belong to the Nicaraguan
Resistance, the umbrella group of the Contras, as the largest rebel
group is known. The resistance is engaged in separate peace talks
with the leftist government.
   Wicliffe Diego, one of five Yatama directors, was suspended for
forming an alliance with the resistance, said Stedman Fagoth
Muller, another Yamata leader.
   Yatama arose from the disintegration of Misurasata, an
organization of Miskito, Sumo and Rama Indians. Factionalism has
marked the Indian struggle against the Sandinistas since fighting
began in 1981, when the government tried to impose authority on the
isolated, traditionally independent coastal region.
   Rivera noted that the Sandinistas formerly viewed autonomy talks
as ``counterrevolutionary,'' but said their attitude had changed.
Still, the two sides differ over the definition of Indian self-rule.
   ``What the Sandinistas propose is decentralization of power, but
through its representatives in the region,'' Rivera said.
   ``We want to elect our own authorities and organize the Indian
nation according to our customs and tradition,'' he added. ``We
want our community borders to be as our grandfathers made them and
not in a mechanical form.''
   Yatama presented Borge with an autonomy proposal on Monday
``that is basic to talks for a permanent cease-fire,'' Rivera said.
   The talks are due to end Thursday.
   Rivera said a truce signed a week ago by a few Yatama leaders
was not significant and was not authorized.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
