<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Contras-Dissent     05-11 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras-Dissent,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caller: Contra Dissidents Demand Resignation Of Rebel Commanders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A telephone caller said 200
dissident Nicaraguan rebels have declared they will no longer take
orders from the insurgents' military commander, Enrique Bermudez.
   The call to The Associated Press on Tuesday reflected divisions
among the U.S.-backed insurgents during stalemated negotiations
between the rebels, known as Contras, and the leftist Sandinista
government.
   It could not be determined if the caller, who did not identify
himself, represented a substantial number of guerrillas opposed to
Bermudez.
   He said the dissidents also demanded the removal of eight other
military leaders of the Nicaraguan Resistance, the main
8,000-strong rebel force that fought the Nicaraguan government
before a recent truce.
   Before he left Miami for Honduras on Tuesday, Bermudez
acknowledged to reporters that there had been a rebellion and
hinted forceful action might be needed to end the mutiny, The Miami
Herald reported in today's editions.
   A Contra official in San Jose, speaking on condition of
anonymity, told the AP on Tuesday it was believed Bermudez would
come to meet with the dissidents.
   The caller did not say where the dissidents were located, but
The Washington Post reported on Tuesday that up to 3,000 dissident
rebels have been holed up at a Honduran base camp since Saturday.
It said the camp is in Yamales, a tiny Honduran village three miles
from the Nicaraguan border.
   There has been constant friction among Contras who served in the
national guard of the late right-wing President Anastasio Somoza
and groups who had fought to overthrow Somoza.
   The Sandinistas gained power after defeating Somoza's national
guard in a civil war that ended in July 1979. Many Somoza
supporters fled into neighboring Honduras, where they established
military camps, and were later joined by Nicaraguans who said the
Sandinistas had betrayed the revolution.
   Members of both groups formed the Nicaragua Resistance about
eight years ago and began guerrilla operations inside Nicaragua.
   The telephone caller said the dissidents were demanding the
resignations of Bermudez and eight other rebel military commanders
because: ``We disavow them as corrupt ... and assure the Nicaraguan
people that we, the workers, campesinos and students who form the
army of the resistance will not allow corrupt and dishonest people
in our ranks who want to return to the past.''
   The caller said the dissidents recognized the authority of rebel
military leaders Diogenes Hernandez Membreno, Walter Calderon
Lopez, Encarnacion Valdivia and Tirzo Roman Moreno.
   Calderon Lopez, Valdivia and Roman Moreno were among seven
Contra leaders expelled from Honduras on Friday after demanding
that Bermudez resign.
   Bosco Matamoros, a Nicaraguan Resistance spokesman in Honduras,
declined comment on the telephone call.
   Earlier, he denied the Post report that up to 3,000 Contras
taking orders from Hernandez Membreno had been holed up in a
Honduran base camp since Saturday and were refusing to take orders
from the resistance leadership.
   Matamoros said on Monday that Contra political and military
representatives met on Sunday at a camp ner the Honduran-Nicaraguan
border to try to resolve the disputes among the Contras.
   Bermudez reportedly opposes the 60-day cease-fire agreement
signed March 23 by Contra and government representatives.
   The pact calls for additional negotiations to make the truce
permanent. The last peace talks ended April 30 in Managua and no
date or location has been set for another round.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
