<HEAD>Iowa Democratic Chairwoman To Endorse Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa Democratic Chairwoman Bonnie
Campbell, abandoning months of neutrality in the party's
presidential nomination race, planned to endorse Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis today, an associate said.
   The move is a signal that the party's establishment considers
Dukakis an almost certain bet to win the nomination and is closing
ranks behind him.
   The endorsement comes on the eve of the party's congressional
district conventions Saturday at which 34 delegates will be picked
to attend the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   It gives a boost to the Dukakis forces who have been quietly
trying to build support in the state since their candidate finished
third in the Feb. 8 precinct caucuses.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, who won the caucuses, has
dropped from the race and second-place finisher Sen. Paul Simon of
Illinois has suspended his campaign.
   Ms. Campbell scheduled a Statehouse news conference to make the
announcement. She will be joined by at least two other party
officials who are also to endorse Dukakis.
   Ms. Campbell's associate, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said her endorsement is aimed at unifying the state party behind
Dukakis.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Dukakis Accepts Secret Service Protection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis is using
Secret Service protection beginning today, after relying for more
than a year on local police on the presidential campaign trail.
   Campaign aides said the timing was the result of several
considerations, including Dukakis' increasing prominence near the
end of what has become a two-man Democratic race with Jesse Jackson.
   The Massachusetts governor said there have been no incidents or
threats that prompted the change. However, he said, ``there comes a
point in all of this when Secret Service protection is necessary,
and in my judgment I've arrived at that point.''
   In addition, aides said there was some concern inside the
campaign about the potential for violence in California,
particularly in light of recent publicity marking 20 years since
the assassination of Robert F. Kennedy after his victory in the
1968 California Democratic primary.
   The protection, provided round the clock at taxpayer expense, is
to begin today as Dukakis leaves for a campaign trip through New
Jersey and Washington, D.C., en route to California.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Applegate Invites Ohio Congressional Dems To Back Glenn For VP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Douglas Applegate invited other Democrats
from Ohio's congressional delegation to a meeting today to push for
support for Sen. John Glenn as a vice presidential candidate.
   Jim Hart, Applegate's administrative assistant, said the meeting
would take place would take place in Washington.
   ``At this point, it's time we probably turn our heads as to who
will be the vice presidential nominee. Mr. (Michael) Dukakis
appears to have the nomination in the back pocket now. One of Mr.
Applegate's main themes has been that we need someone in White
House who will be a friend to us, to look out for our benefit. He's
always been a big supporter of John Glenn,'' said Hart.
