<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-11 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Says Booster Rocket Testing on Schedule for August Shuttle
Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA is confident that the first
post-Challenger space shuttle flight will go off as scheduled now
that a test-firing of a full-size booster rocket has been
successfully completed.
   Royce Mitchell, project manager of the booster program at the
Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala., said on Tuesday
the April 20 test showed nothing that would stand in the way of the
flight scheduled for August.
   The redesigned rockets must pass two more full-duration firings,
one in June and one in July, before they receive final
certification. The boosters, built by Morton Thiokol Inc., are
tested at that company's plant in Utah.
   A faulty Morton Thiokol booster rocket was blamed for the
January 1986 disaster in which the Challenger was destroyed and its
crew of seven killed.
   Mitchell spoke at a news conference from Huntsville that was
carried by television to National Aeronautics and Space
Administration centers around the country and to the agency's
headquarters in Washington.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Backs School-Inspection Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union official says an appeals court ruling
that local officials must inspect school buildings for
cancer-causing asbestos is ``a tremendous victory for the health of
children and school employees.''
   Gerald W. McEntee, president of the American Council of
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees said the
government regulations upheld by a federal court here Tuesday
should be applied in all public and commercial buildings.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals dismissed a challenge to the
Environmental Protection Agency regulations by a trade group that
complained the rules failed to set a safe level of exposure to
airborne particles of asbestos.
   ``This argument is meritless,'' a three-judge panel said.
``Congress explicitly recognized that experts presently disagree
over what levels of exposure are safe.''
   EPA's regulations require schools to conduct visual inspections
of asbestos-containing building materials to determine if they are
damaged. Undamaged asbestos is not believed to pose a health risk.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Koch: Drug Conference `A Farce,' War on Drugs `A Joke'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Mayor Edward I. Koch says the head of
the White House Conference for a Drug-Free America is under orders
not to embarrass the Reagan administration, and as a result, the
panel is ``a farce.''
   Conference Chairwoman Lois Haight Herrington is ``doing her job,
she's under orders and she's carrying them out very effectively,''
Koch said Tuesday outside a meeting of the conferees.
   Asked if he believed those orders were coming from the White
House, Koch said: ``or whoever is in charge of making sure that
this commission doesn't rock the boat, that this commission doesn't
fix responsibility and that this commission doesn't make requests
of the Reagan administration that they don't want to engage in.''
   And the mayor complained to fellow conferees that they had not
been given a draft report.
   ``If we are now dealing with the single most important issue in
America _ everybody says that _ and here we are in this small,
little, uncomfortable room, not having had the material presented
to us _ it's a farce,'' Koch said.
   After pointing out the failure of the current efforts to stem
the flow of drugs, Koch exclaimed, ``This is not a war on drugs _
this is a joke.''
   Herrington responded to Koch's criticism by saying, ``If I was
mayor of the biggest city with the biggest drug problem in the
world, I'd be frustrated, too.''
</TEXT>
