<DOCNO> AP880511-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Split-LiverTransplants Bjt   05-11 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Split-Liver Transplants, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Europeans Report Transplanting Parts Of Same Liver Into Different
Humans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's first two reported successful
attempts to transplant parts of the same liver into different
patients are big steps toward overcoming the chronic donor organ
shortage, say transplant surgeons.
   Dr. Henri Bismuth, a liver transplant surgeon at Paul Brousse
Hospital in Paris, reported here Tuesday that he had no choice but
to divide the liver of a 40-year-old brain-dead man for two women,
both unconscious and near death.
   The procedure, performed May 1, is believed to be the second in
the world, according to Dr. Christoph E. Broelsch, professor of
surgery at the University of Chicago. The previous one was
performed in February in West Germany.
   ``This is one way to increase the donors. If you have patients
who are terribly ill and in equal need, it's one way out,'' said
the University of Pittsburgh's Dr. Thomas E. Starzl, who performed
the world's first successful liver transplant in 1967.
   ``I can see this happening at our institution anytime soon if we
have the appropriate setting,'' Broelsch said in a telephone
interview.
   About 450 people are awaiting liver transplants in the United
States, according to Arthur Harrell of the American Council on
Transplantation. About half are children.
   In this month's transplant, the donor had been rushed to France
from Switzerland and was a suitable match for either the 40- or
54-year-old woman.
   Unable to choose between the women, Bismuth transplanted half
the liver into each patient. Because the liver is the only organ in
the body that can regenerate itself, it grows naturally along with
the body after being reduced in size.
   Bismuth told about 100 physicians from around the world gathered
in Pittsburgh for a conference on liver disease that both of his
patients' transplanted livers are functioning well.
   One of the women, however, is still critically ill because of
kidney and lung complications she suffered before surgery.
   On Feb. 2, Dr. Rudolf Pichlmayr of the University of Hannover's
Medical School in West Germany performed a similar split-liver
transplant.
   Pichlmayr said he, like Bismuth, was desperate to save two
patients' lives even though just one liver was available. As a
result, he split the liver of a 23-year-old man and transplanted
half into a 2-year-old boy and the other half into a 63-year-old
woman.
   Both recipients are back home and doing well, Pichlmayr said in
a telephone interview from West Germany early today.
   ``I guess the risk for both recipients will be a little bit
higher. So I think it's a step forward, but it's only a step
forward if one cannot manage the donor problem,'' Pichlmayr said.
   ``It's an enormous need for livers in our country,'' he said.
``We have too few donors, so we have to take all the maneuvers to
get more livers, particularly of course for the small children.''
   In recent years, Pichlmayr and other doctors in Europe and the
United States have trimmed livers so the organs can fit into
transplant patients, particularly children for whom donor organs
are most scarce.
   ``It's of course a pity to throw away the other half of the
liver,'' Pichlmayr said.
   Split liver transplants are more complicated than simply paring
down the organ because doctors need to divide a common artery and
bile duct, Pichlmayr said. As a result, half the split organ is
often weaker than the other.
   Broelsch said the one-year success rate is about 50 percent to
60 percent for children who receive reduced-size livers, compared
with 80 percent to 90 percent for those who receive an entire organ.
   The risk for split-liver transplants will likely be even greater
and, until more is known, will remain a method of last resort,
doctors said.
   ``Nevertheless, it's a big step,'' Starzl said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
