<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-11 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished lower today in dealings
against the Japanese yen, while stock prices fell back
substantially.
   The dollar closed at 124.24 yen, down 0.39 yen from its finish
on Tuesday. It remained little changed from its opening at 124.23
yen, hovering between the 124.17 and 124.35-yen level.
   ``Trading was mixed in selling and buying, but generally it was
a quiet day without incentives to direct the market,'' said an
official of a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   There was also a wait-and-see attitude among investors in regard
to the completion of the refunding auction of U.S. Treasury bonds,
which began Tuesday in the United States, and the pending
announcement in Washington next week of U.S. trade figures for
March, he said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 147.95 points Tuesday, lost 251.20
points, or 0.92 percent to close the day's trading at 27,161.05.
   Share prices fell sharply during the afternoon session on a news
report that British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said
there could be an internationally coordinated boost in interest
rates, traders said.
   The report by a Japanese news service quoted Lawson as saying a
coordinated effort to raise short term rates by West Germany, Japan
and other leading nations is ``certainly possible.''
   An official of a securities house, speaking anonymously, said
there were no changes in fundamentals, however.
   Volume on the first section trade was estimated at 1.1 billion
shares, down up from 700 million shares Tuesday.
   Losers included electricals, shipbuildings and machineries.
Papers, chemicals, constructions and foodstuffs were also lower.
Among the winners were steels and rubbers.
</TEXT>
