<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-China-Tibet     05-11 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Tibet,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Condemned on Tibetan Rights While Vice-Premier at White
House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges against China of genocide and
repression of Tibetans were aired by congressmen even as a Chinese
vice premier was meeting President Reagan and other U.S. government
officials.
   The Congressional human rights caucus heard the accusations of
abuses in Chinese-ruled Tibet during a hearing that, in an apparent
coincidence, began at the same hour Tuesday that Chinese Vice
Premier Tian Jiyun was at the White House talking with Reagan.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the Reagan-Tiang
meeting centered on trade, but Fitzwater did not say whether human
rights issues were raised. The State Department said also said a
meeting Tuesday between Tiang and Secretary George Shultz centered
largely with economic matters.
   Reps. Ben Gilman, R-N.Y., and Frank McCloskey, D-Ind., told the
human rights panel they are introducing legislation for economic
sanctions against China linked to human rights abuses in the
Himalayan region of Tibet.
   Gilman said his bill would ban U.S. support of credit for China
from international lending agencies and would provide for Voice of
America broadcasts in the Tibetan language and for U.S. aid for
Tibetan refugees and for preserving Tibetan culture.
   The U.S. recognizes Tibet only as a part of China and the State
Department does not require its officials in the region to have a
knowledge of the Tibetan language. McCloskey said that leaves the
U.S. ``indirectly aiding and abetting in the extinction of Tibetan
culture,'' McCloskey said.
   Actor Richard Gere, president of New York's Tibet House, told
the panel China has ``an ugly solution'' for the Tibetan problem
providing for ``total annihilation of the Tibetan people as a race,
as a culture ... probably within one generation.''
   The 35 years since the entrance of Chinese forces into the
Himalayan territory have brought ``one of the most devastating
genocides we have had in history ... on the order of Cambodia''
under the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s, said Gere.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., co-chairman of the caucus, said he
hopes the Reagan administration raises human rights with Chinese
leaders because the issue will not disappear.
   ``The cost of human rights violations to the Chinese will be
increased year after year after year until they realize it will be
not only in the interest of the Tibetan people but of the Chinese
themselves to put an end to those barbaric practices,'' he said.
   After the hearing _ and while Tian was having lunch with U.S.
Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter _ members of the caucus and
Thubten Jigme Norbu, brother of the Dalai Lama, the Tibetan
spiritual leader in exile, inaugurated a Tibetan art, antiques and
photographic exhibit at a congressional office building. Norbu is a
professor at the University of Indiana.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietAuction     05-11 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Auction,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sotheby's To Hold First Art Auction in U.S.S.R.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glasnost and an afternoon tea with Raisa
Gorbachev have led Sotheby's to arrange the first modern
international art auction in the Soviet Union.
   When Sotheby's gavel falls at the July 7 auction in Moscow,
Soviet artists whose works weren't officially recognized three
years ago will find themselves in the distinctly capitalist
position of selling their work to the highest bidder.
   ``They all saw this as an opportunity to get international
exposure, and were quite titillated to have their work auctioned by
Sotheby's,'' said Simon de Pury, Sotheby's managing director in
Europe, who will serve as auctioneer.
   In addition to 100 works by 29 living artists, 18 paintings by
five artists from the Russian avant garde period of 1910-1940 will
be on the block.
   With price estimates ranging from $3,500 to $35,000, Sotheby's
expects the sale of contemporary art alone to total about $1
million.
   ``Many of the artists, until a year or two ago, were
`unofficial' artists, who had difficulty exhibiting and exporting
their work,'' said de Pury, who proposed the sale. ``This has all
changed with glasnost.''
   Ronald Feldman, a Manhattan art dealer, said that with Mikhail
Gorbachev's policy of openness, ``You can now step in and buy
paintings. Before, everyone was in the smuggling business ...
   ``In many ways, this is a revolution going on here.''
   The distinction between ``official'' and ``unofficial'' artists
has faded and the auction virtually erases it, he said.
   Sotheby's was well positioned to be the first auction house to
be allowed to set up at least for one auction in the Soviet Union.
   De Pury had worked with Soviet cultural officials in his former
capacity as curator of the Thyssen-Bornemisza Collection in
Switzerland, arranging exchanges with the Soviets.
   In August, at tea with Mrs. Gorbachev, he broached the subject
of an auction. ``When I mentioned the possibility the first time,
to my amazement, they were intrigued, and said it was worth
exploring. There was a definite interest,'' de Pury recalled.
   De Pury said he had a free hand in selecting the contemporary
works for the auction, and he roamed Moscow and other cities,
visiting studios and picking paintings.
   ``It's a very lively, vital group of artists whose works have
been fought over by museums and collectors in the West,'' he said.
   For the artists, Feldman said, ``The prices they may get are
secondary to their desire to have their work seen in the West, to
be known in the West.''
   Soviet officials presented a list of avant-garde works that
could be sold, and Sotheby's selected from that.
   Highlights of the collection will be shown for five days in New
York starting Saturday; then in London (May 22-24); Paris (May
26-27); Cologne (May 31-June 3); and Zurich (June 9-15).
   Customers planning to attend the auction in Moscow can sign up
for a special program of visits to the artists' studios, as well as
lectures, museum tours and evening entertainment.
   Among the more established contemporary artists whose work will
be sold are Ilya Kabakov, Ivan Chuikov, Vladimir Yankilevsky and
Edward Steinberg.
   The avant-garde section includes seven works by Alexander
Rodchenko and four by Varvara Stepanova. The most valuable on sale
are Rodchenko's ``Line,'' estimated to sell for about $200,000, and
a gouache composition of his from 1916 which Sotheby's thinks will
fetch about $130,000.
   ``We will have to see how the sale goes,'' de Pury said. ``It
could possibly lead to other auctions _ this could be an annual
event, or biannual.''
   Nearly all of the contemporary artists represented in the
auction live in Moscow, though artists from Leningrad and Soviet
Georgia also have their works up for sale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
