<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Ogilvie     05-11 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Ogilvie,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Ogilvie Dead at 65 after Heart Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Richard B. Ogilvie, who won a battle
for Illinois' first income tax only to lose the state's highest
office after one term, has died at age 65.
   Ogilvie, a lawyer and the state's GOP governor from 1969 to
1973, died at Northwestern Memorial Hospital on Tuesday, a day
after he underwent emergency surgery for a massive heart attack.
   ``He always spoke his mind and had the strength of character to
stand behind issues he believed in, such as the state's first
income tax,'' said Gov. James R. Thompson.
   Oglivie's wife, Dorothy, daughter, Elizabeth, and her husband
were at the hospital when he died.
   Funeral plans were not announced.
   Ogilvie's 1972 re-election loss to Dan Walker was attributed in
part to the 1969 enactment of the state's first income tax, which
established a 2.5 percent tax rate for individuals and a 4 percent
rate for corporations.
   ``He made very tough decisions. He didn't measure the political
effect of them many times, and some of them hurt him,'' former Sen.
Charles Percy, R-Ill. said late Tuesday.
   Walker, who edged Ogilvie with 51 percent of the vote, is
serving a seven-year federal prison sentence for bank fraud that
occurred after he left office.
   Ogilvie took office a year after the 1968 riots at the
Democratic National Convention in Chicago.
   In his final State of the State address to the General Assembly
in 1973, Ogilvie listed among his accomplishments the enactment of
the tax, reorganization of the government and the curtailment of
civil disorders.
   Among his failures, he said, were the inability to secure the
enactment of merit selection of judges, and a lag in enforcement of
anti-pollution rules for Lake Michigan.
   In recent years, Ogilvie had become much sought-after in
untangling complicated legal matters, including the Milwaukee Road
bankruptcy proceedings, considered one of the most successful rail
bankruptcy reorganizations.
   He was named trustee of the Chicago Missouri & Western Railway
Co., which has been under federal bankruptcy reorganization since
April.
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer had been preparing to name Ogilvie chairman
of the Chicago Housing Authority, the city's troubled public
housing agency.
</TEXT>
