<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NebraskaPrimary     05-11 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nebraska Primary,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Karnes And Kerrey Win Senate Nods; Bush And Dukakis Claim
Victories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED HOWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. David Karnes won a battle for the
GOP nomination, but faces the beginning of another tough contest
today as he looks ahead to the general election campaign against
Democrat Bob Kerrey.
   Karnes defeated Rep. Hal Daub, a four-term Omaha congressman, in
a Republican race in which each said his record had been
misrepresented by the other.
   Republican State Chairman Norm Riffel said it might take time
for the wounds to heal.
   Kerrey, who served one term as governor and declined to seek a
second, overwhelmed Ken Michaelis in Tuesday's Democratic primary.
   Republican Vice President George Bush and Democratic Gov.
Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts won predictable victories in their
respective primaries. Neither candidate spent more than a few hours
campaigning in Nebraska.
   Dukakis easily outdistanced Jesse Jackson, the only presidential
hopeful who visited the state twice. However, Jackson appeared to
win votes sufficient to give him seven of Nebraska's 25 delegates.
   With 1,850 of 1,870 precincts reporting, or 99 percent, Dukakis
had 104,264 or 63 percent, while Jackson had 44,079 or 26 percent.
   Bush, with 99 percent of the precincts reporting, had 136,593 or
71 percent. Sen. Robert Dole had 23 percent while Pat Robertson had
5 percent.
   Nebraskans also gave a special victory to its one-house,
nonpartisan Legislature, approving lawmakers' first pay raise in 20
years. The constitutional amendment will boost salaries from $4,800
to $12,000 annually.
   In the Omaha-dominated 2nd Congressional District, former state
Sen. Peter Hoagland scored an upset over Cece Zorinsky for the
Democratic nomination.
   Mrs. Zorinsky, widow of U.S. Sen. Ed Zorinsky, had been favored
by as much as 45 percentage points in early polls.
   With all precincts reporting, Hoagland had 33,155, or 55
percent; Mrs. Zorinsky 28,377 or 43 percent; two other candidates
also were on the ballot.
   Jerry Schenken won the Republican nomination in the 2nd
District, defeating three challengers.
   With all precincts reporting, Schenken had 22,927 or 38 percent;
state Sen. Chris Abboud 18,162 or 30 percent; Ally Milder 18,096 or
30 percent; and Carl Jennings 1,945 or 3 percent.
   Hoagland and Schenken will meet in November for the seat being
vacated by Daub.
   Incumbent 1st District Rep. Doug Bereuter was unopposed in the
GOP race, while Corky Jones easily defeated Marlin Pals for the
Democratic nomination.
   With 603 of 658 precincts reporting, Jones had 29,844 or 92
percent, while Pals had 13,172 or 31 percent.
   U.S. Rep. Virginia Smith was unopposed for the GOP nomination to
an eighth term in the 3rd District. Democrat John D. Racek was
unopposed for the Democratic nomination.
   In the Senate race, Kerrey and Republican Gov. Kay Orr
acknowledged that he would likely be the front-runner in the early
stages of the campaign. Kerrey said he'd work to keep it that way;
Mrs. Orr said Kerry's gubernatorial record would make a profitable
target.
   Kerrey, 44, lost part of a leg and won the Medal of Honor as a
Navy commando in Vietnam. He returned home to build a successful
restaurant business. In his first bid for office, he ousted
Republican Gov. Charles Thone in 1982.
   With 1,857 of 1,870 precincts reporting, Kerrey had 152,505 or
92 percent, while Michaelis, a disbarred lawyer, had 13,909 or 8
percent.
   Karnes, at 39 the youngest U.S. senator, won his first election
Tuesday. Mrs. Orr appointed Karnes, a political unknown, to fill
Zorinsky's seat in March 1987. Daub had been among the party
regulars lobbying for the job.
   With 99 percent of the precincts reporting, Karnes had 114,232
or 55 percent while Daub had 93,416 or 45 percent.
   ``We did it!'' Karnes told supporters. ``And the thing that I am
so proud about is that we did it the old-fashioned way _ we earned
every single vote.''
</TEXT>
