<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ZeroTolerance     05-11 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zero Tolerance,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Yacht Seized As Ark Royal Leaves Key West</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. authorities released one luxury yacht
seized under the ``zero tolerance'' anti-drug policy, but announced
the seizure of a similar vessel also found with minuscule amounts
of drugs on board.
   The 133-foot Ark Royal was released Tuesday afternoon after
Michael Rogerson, president of the California company that owns the
vessel, paid $1,600 in fines and fees and agreed not to hold the
government responsible.
   The Ms. Mindy, a $600,000, 52-foot sportfishing boat owned by
the Cigarette Racing Team of North Miami, was seized Monday as it
returned from the Bahamas and docked in Port Salerno, the Coast
Guard announced Tuesday.
   U.S. Customs Service agents turned up cocaine residue on a
dollar bill and traces of marijuana in a plastic bag, according to
the Coast Guard.
   Neither person aboard the Ms. Mindy _ ship's captain Lewis
Shaver and an unidentified first mate _ was charged with drug
possession.
   Also seized under the policy last week was a 68-foot shrimper.
   Officials have not decided whether to pursue civil forfeiture of
the boat or allow a fine to paid as in the case of the Ark Royal,
said Leon Guinn, assistant regional Customs supervisor.
   Rogerson, president of the Tomima Corp. and chairman of the
Rogerson Aircraft Corp., criticized the policy in a statement
Tuesday by his office in Irvine, Calif.
   ``This type of action presents an unreasonable danger to all
boat owners for the isolated actions of passengers and crew,'' he
said. ``The seizure of this vessel for the apparent individual
actions of a crewmember against the stated policy of the
corporation and the vessel for minute traces makes no sense.''
   Under the policy, which went into effect April 15, vessels with
drugs on board are seized by the Coast Guard and turned over to the
Customs Service _ no matter how petty the drug offense, how
valuable the boat, or if a shrimper's family depends on the living
he makes from the boat.
   Civil libertarians say the policy puts punishment before the
trial.
   ``What's wrong with it is the same thing that's wrong with
shooting someone or hanging someone, and then saying, `We're going
to give you a trial to see if you're guilty,''' said James Powell,
national legal director for the American Civil Liberties Union.
   Michael Sheehan, a spokesman for the Miami Customs office, said
it was obvious ``that the program is strict, stringent and tough.
   ``However, zero tolerance is also fair, reasonable and
judicious,'' Sheehan said. ``That has been pointed out by the
release of the Ark Royal.''
   Fewer than 10 percent of vessels seized by the government are
ever returned to owners. The Ark Royal was in that minority because
its owner moved swiftly and filed a convincing petition, Customs
officials said.
   The yacht's crew had undergone drug testing before being hired,
said Rogerson, who was not aboard the vessel when it was seized in
international waters. And the government was unable to charge any
of the six crew members with possession of the 10 marijuana seeds
or two stems discovered by the Coast Guard when it boarded the boat
Saturday.
   David Phelps and his two crewmen were arrested and charged with
misdemeanor possession of marijuana when Phelps' 68-foot shrimper
returned a week ago Tuesday from an eight-day trip.
   The Miss Lorraine carried 1,750 pounds of shrimp _ and a few
marijuana seeds the Coast Guard discovered during a routine safety
check, authorities said. Phelps and his two crewmen said the
marijuana was from a previous crew.
   ``What is a captain supposed to do? Frisk the crew and strip the
passengers?'' asked Capt. Thom Antoszewski, one of the bitter
fishermen who say their livelihoods and human rights are
jeopardized by the policy.
   Several Key West boat captains have drafted forms for their crew
to sign in which they swear they won't bring drugs aboard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
