<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AsianDrugs     05-11 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asian Drugs,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds: Laotian Officials Accused of Supervising Heroin Smuggling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men extradited from Hong Kong to face drug
smuggling charges here said Laotian officials supervise heroin
production there and take a cut of the proceeds, according to court
documents.
   The allegations, which name no specific officials but referred
to a ``big official'' who was in charge of the ``upcountry
province,'' were contained in affidavits requesting the extradition
of Cheng Ah-Kai, 60, of Hong Kong, and Wichai Chaiwisan, 55, of
Thailand.
   The defendants are charged with shipping 70 pounds of heroin to
an undercover agent in New York. They were arrested in Hong Kong in
March and waived extradition.
   They arrived here Tuesday night and were to be arraigned today.
   U.S. Attorney Andrew J. Maloney said Tuesday the two claimed
they needed permission from the communist ruled Laotian government
to manufacture heroin and that officials received payments of
approximately $2,000 for every 700 grams of heroin produced.
   In a secretly recorded conversation with an informant, the two
said that Laotian officials also supervised the production to
ensure they were not cheated, according to the affidavits.
   ``This is the first prosecutable case in the United States which
actively discusses the possible involvement of Laotian government
officials'' in drug trade, said Robert Stutman, head of the Drug
Enforcement Administration's New York office.
   An official with the permanent United Nations Mission for the
Laos People's Democratic Republic disputed the allegations.
   ``The government does not encourage the Laos people to grow or
to produce or to trade in opium or heroin,'' said S. Sisouvong, a
third secretary at the Laos U.N. mission.
   He said the Southeast Asian government fully supported the
elimination of illicit drug trafficking and was trying to encourage
Laotians to grow crops like rice and vegetables.
   DEA intelligence sources have reported that the production of
opium, the base for heroin, had increased in Laos to more than 250
metric tons in 1987 from 50 metric tons in 1984, according to
Stutman.
   ``This type of growth can't go on without someone in the
government knowing about it and approving it,'' Maloney said.
   Stutman said U.S. officials would have problems pursuing the
matter because there was not much contact between the United States
and Laos.
   Cheng and Wichai were believed to have been involved in the
importation of heroin to the United States for more than 20 years,
according to Maloney. He said they received much of their supply in
Laos.
   The case began in January 1987 when the DEA learned that Cheng
was seeking a new route to smuggle heroin into the United States,
Maloney said.
   Through a confidential informant in Hong Kong, the DEA set up a
series of negotiations with an undercover agent who posed as an
organized crime figure with connections at Kennedy International
Airport here.
   These negotiations resulted in the shipment from Bangkok of 70
pounds of heroin, valued at $50 million, which arrived at Kennedy
on Jan. 16, concealed in a shipment of brass animal figures,
authorities said.
   Cheng and Wichai were charged in a three-count indictment,
handed up Feb. 9, alleging conspiracy to import heroin and
importation of heroin. They face up to life in prison if convicted.
   Stutman said the investigation abroad was continuing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Redford     05-11 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Redford,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actor Robert Redford Opens Moscow Film Series</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Redford opened an exhibition of his movies
by telling an audience that films are a powerful way to bridge
differences of opinion and that he supports glasnost in Soviet
cinema.
   Glasnost, the Russian word for openness, is a key term in
Mikhail Gorbachev's policy of reforms in certain areas.
   ``Obviously this is a very important time for our countries,''
Redford told the audience at Moscow's Oktyabr theater on Tuesday,
the exhibition's opening day. ``And I believe that film is a very
powerful tool to translate differences of opinion and points of
common interest.
   ``And for that reason, I support glasnost in both American film
and Soviet cinema.''
   President Reagan and Gorbachev are to meet May 29 in Moscow,
their second summit since last December, when the two signed a
treaty scrapping intermediate-range nuclear missiles.
   Redford, 51, is most widely known among Soviets for his role in
``Three Days of the Condor,'' a 15-year-old spy movie that
continues to be shown in Soviet theaters.
   He came to Moscow after spending three days in Leningrad where
the eight-film exhibition opened.
   ``The Milagro Beanfield War'' which Redford directed but in
which he does not appear, and ``All the President's Men'' were the
opening-night films, shown at two different theaters in Moscow.
   Igor N. Lissakovsky, vice-president of the Association of
Filmmakers, said the general public was being admitted to the films
for 3 rubles a ticket (about $4.70), but that blocks of seats for
each showing had been reserved for members of the Filmmakers Union.
   Lissakovsky said the money from ticket sales, which usually goes
to the state, will be turned over to the Filmmakers Union for
projects encouraging young artists.
   He said he did not know how many seats were available to the
general public. Redford spokesman Gary Beer said the Soviets told
him the theater admitting the public will have three showings a
day, making available 6,000 seats daily, with 1,500 reserved for
Filmmaker Union members.
   The other theater is a private theater of the Filmmakers Union,
with admission by invitation only.
   Other films to be shown are ``The Candidate,'' ``The Sting,''
``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' ``The Electric Horseman,''
``Jeremiah Johnson,'' and ``The Natural.''
   Redford's stay in Moscow, which ends Friday, will include a
meeting on ecology, a cause the actor-director has supported for
years.
   He also plans to moderate a workshop on global warming caused by
the depletion of the ozone layer in the upper atmosphere. The
workshop is the effort of the Institute for Resource Management,
which Redford founded, and the Soviet Academy of Sciences.
   Redford next travels to Tblisi, capital of the Soviet Republic
of Georgia, to open the film exhibition Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
