<DOCNO> AP880511-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-11 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Thin European Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar held steady in thin trading in
Europe this morning, with foreign exchange dealers saying they
expected it to remain in a narrow range throughout the session.
Gold prices rose.
   Traders said volume was modest ahead of the long weekend due to
start for many dealers in Europe on Thursday.
   One trader in Milan said dealers might try to test the dollar's
lower levels against the West German mark.
   ``I see the dollar a little lower. But traders will try and move
it down carefully,'' she said, citing fear of central bank
intervention as the reason for their caution.
   Another trader in Milan said attention had shifted to sterling,
following statements by Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel
Lawson that he favors a closer link between sterling and the West
German mark.
   The Milan dealer said he expects the pound to edge up against
the mark.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.39 yen to a closing 124.24 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 124.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   --1.6765 West German marks, down from 1.6783
   --1.3925 Swiss francs, down from 1.3955
   --5.6915 French francs, up from 5.6905
   --1.8789 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8815
   --1,248.00 Italian lire, unchanged
   --1.2370 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2375
   The British pound rose to $1.8865 from $1.8825 on Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $450.40 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $446.50. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$449.35.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $449.20, up from $446.50 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.73 to close at a bid $451.68.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London today at a bid price of
$6.52 a troy ounce, up from Tuesday's $6.45.
</TEXT>
