<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VDTLaw     05-11 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-VDT Law,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Local Law To Regulate Use In Suffolk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies with 20 or more computer
terminals would be required to provide employees with work breaks,
eye care, special lighting and detachable keyboards, under a bill
approved by the county Legislature.
   If Suffolk County Executive Patrick Halpin signs the bill, which
passed 13-2 Tuesday, it would be the first law in the country to
regulate the terminals in private businesses, workplace design
experts said.
   Business leaders have sharply criticized the measure, charging
it would be costly to implement and put placing them at a
competitive disadvantage in the marketplace. They contend the bill
will drive companies out of the county.
   Mitchell Pally, a spokesman for the Long Island Association, the
region's largest business organization, said the bill ``threatens
the continued economic vitality of the community.
   ``We're obviously very disappointed and will urge Mr. Halpin to
veto the bill,'' he said.
   The bill is intended to protect the health and safety of
employees who use video display terminals (VDTs), according to
legislator John Foley, sponsor of the bill.
   Foley, calling many offices ``high-tech sweatshops,'' said he
believed there was a need for regulation.
   Halpin, who must act on the bill within 60 days of its passage,
said he would hold a public hearing before deciding whether to sign
it.
   Lawmakers in the Long Island county approved a similar bill last
summer, but it was vetoed by the acting county executive at the
time, Michael A. Lo Grande.
   Labor unions, business leaders and workplace experts from around
the country said the Suffolk bill would serve as a model for other
municipalities or states.
   ``Whether this bill will result in legislation elsewhere is
unclear, but it'll rejuvenate a lot of campaigns for VDT standards
around the country,'' said Laura Stock, associate director of the
Labor Occupational Health Program, an advocacy group in Berkeley,
Calif.
   Legislator Joseph Rizzo, who abstained from voting, said, ``this
legislation is doing what a union should be doing.''
   Some companies hinted that they may consider areas outside of
Suffolk for future expansion.
   ``We view the law as a potential deterrent to doing business in
Suffolk,'' said Bruce Reisman, a spokesman for New York Telephone.
``Undoubtedly the law would have to be taken into consideration as
a factor in planning expansions.''
   New York Telephone has 1,500 employees in Suffolk _ operators
and office personnel who use VDTs routinely.
   Optometrist Joseph Hallick testified at the hearing that many of
his patients complain that they never needed glasses until they
started working at VDTs.
   Suffolk companies, however, argued that there is no evidence
that the prolonged use of a VDT is harmful to the employee.
   It mandates that companies pay 80 percent of the cost of annual
eye exams and eyewear required for an operator and provide
15-minute work breaks every three hours for employees who work at
the terminals.
   Businesses would be given six months from the bill's passage
date to comply. If the employer does not comply with the
regulations, the bill provides a basis for an employee to seek
damages in court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
