<2ND_LINE>PM-Storms Rdp,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms That Unleashed Tornado, Hail Move out to Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hail-spitting thunderstorms that pelted the Atlantic coast for
two days began blowing out to sea early today, while the National
Guard helped enforce a curfew on a Kentucky town ``buried'' by a
tornado blamed for one death.
   The storms, which shattered windows and downed power lines as
far south as the Gulf coast and as far north as Pennsylvania,
surprised motorists throughout the Deep South with icy roadways on
Tuesday.
   ``We've got wrecks everywhere,'' said Vicki Griffith, a police
dispatcher in Tallassee, about 20 miles northeast of Montgomery,
Ala. She said at least three people were injured in accidents
during the afternoon storm. The extent of the injuries was not
immediately known.
   School officials in Tallassee and nearby Wetumpka delayed the
dismissal of students Tuesday afternoon to allow the storm to
clear, said Robyn Hearn, a spokesman for the Alabama Emergency
Management Agency. No funnel clouds were sighted despite tornado
warnings.
   Thunderstorms also lashed Georgia and North Carolina, where
residents spotted several funnel clouds, and West Virginia before
beginning to move out to sea early this morning, the National
Weather Service reported.
   In Mississippi, winds overturned three mobile homes, caused
minor power outages and hurled a 50-foot communications tower 30
feet onto a nearby business. No injuries were reported.
   The storms produced golfball-sized hail near Saucier, Miss., and
in central Texas, where the wind gusted up to 76 mph. In
Winston-Salem, N.C., about 5,100 homes lost power due to the storm,
but it was restored by 9:15 p.m., Duke Power Co. said.
   Kentucky Gov. Wallace Wilkinson on Tuesday toured a 6-mile-long
path of destruction left the night before by a tornado that killed
a woman in a house trailer and injured at least 15 people in
Middlesboro, a town of 11,000 just north of the Tennessee border.
   ``It just kind of hopped along the valley,'' Wilkinson said.
``And it's very obvious where it touched down.''
   ``You just can't believe the kind of destruction we're talking
here,'' said Mayor Troy Welch. ``The city's just buried.''
   Joe Iovine, who watched bulldozers clearing debris Tuesday from
a furniture store owned by his family since 1910, said, ``It was
wiped out in 30 seconds. I get to talking about it and it chokes me
up. I've had it.''
   Wilkinson said a preliminary survey showed that 38 businesses
and 26 homes suffered major damage, but that damage was not severe
enough to warrant a federal disaster area designation.
   Welch, estimating damage in the millions, declared an emergency
shortly after midnight, and Wilkinson activated 30 National
Guardsmen to help clean up, keep the peace and enforce an 8 p.m.
curfew in the damaged business district.
</TEXT>
