<HEAD>Thunderstorms Move Out to Sea After Unleashing Damaging Winds,
Hail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms moved out to sea today after lashing the East
Coast with hail and powerful winds that blew windows out of
buildings and downed trees and power lines.
   Thunderstorms Tuesday also dropped hail as big as golf balls
along the Gulf Coast and unleashed winds gusting to 76 mph in
central Texas. Strong winds damaged homes near Eola, Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued early today along the middle
Atlantic Coast and the Carolina coast. Cloudy skies prevailed from
northern Florida to New England and the lower Great Lakes region.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms extended from central Texas to
southeastern Colorado, and a few showers and thunderstorms dampened
North Dakota.
   Much of the southern Plains were under cloudy skies. Clouds
spread over the Pacific Northwest, but fair skies prevailed in the
rest of the West.
   In the upper Great Lakes, temperatures were in the upper 20s and
30s, prompting frost and freeze warnings for northern lower
Michigan.
   On Tuesday, strong winds blew out windows in Thomasville, Ga.,
and downed trees around Newton, Ga., and in the northern Florida
cities of Darlington and Bonifay. Trees and power lines were
knocked down in Greensboro, N.C.
   The thunderstorms also dropped dime-sized hail on Newton and the
Pennsylvania towns of Elizabethtown and Coatesville.
   Thunderstorms spawned golf ball-size hail near Saucier, Miss.,
and in Miles, Texas, and gusts to 76 mph in San Angelo, Texas.
   Today's forecast called for showers and a few thunderstorms
scattered across New England, most numerous over northern and
coastal sections; scattered showers and thunderstorms in the Texas
Panhandle, west central Texas and the Rio Grande Valley; clouds
prevailing in northeast Minnesota and the northern half of Florida
and sunny skies in the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 70s or 80s across
much of the nation; 60s from northern Minnesota to the lower Great
Lakes, eastern Ohio Valley and much of New England; 50s across the
northern Great Lakes and the upper Ohio Valley; and 90s in much of
central and Southern California to the Rio Grande Valley and south
central Texas and 100 to 105 degress across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 28
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 81 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
