<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Denmark 2ndLd-Writethru a0569 05-11 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denmark, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0569,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Resigns After Danish Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Schlueter resigning, talks
to begin on forming new government. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``The
resolution...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK POWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Poul Schlueter
resigned today in a bid to form a new center-right coalition after
an inconclusive parliamentary election called over Denmark's
nuclear-arms policy and its allegiance to NATO.
   Danish radio said Schlueter submitted his resignation to Queen
Margrethe II at Amalienborg Palace and told her negotiations would
begin this afternoon.
   Tuesday's balloting ended in a stalemate in which neither major
bloc could form a majority government.
   Schlueter's outgoing minority, four-party coalition retained its
70 seats in the Folketing, the 179-member parliament. The socialist
opposition dropped two seats for a total of 79.
   The opposition Social Democrats, Denmark's largest party,
touched off the election by pushing through parliament a new
anti-nuclear resolution the government refused to implement because
of strong objections from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   The resolution, designed to bolster Denmark's 1957 peacetime ban
on nuclear arms, calls for notifying visiting warships that such
weapons were not allowed in port. Unless the resolution is
overturned by the new parliament, the government will have to carry
it out, after the wording has been determined.
   Despite the vote, the government and the opposition both claimed
the outcome vindicated their position on the NATO issue.
   Schlueter, speaking during a televised post-election roundtable
discussion with other party leaders Tuesday, claimed that the four
coalition parties opposing the April 14 resolution came out best.
   ``The parties that voted for the Social Democratic resolution on
NATO policy were weakened,'' he said.
   Schlueter, who had called the election just eight months after
the last one, claimed the outcome would ease Denmark's crisis in
NATO. He had wanted voters to endorse the country's ``full
membership'' in the Western military alliance.
   But Social Democratic leader Svend Auken insisted ``there was
still a majority backing the resolution'' and said his party would
work for its implementation in the new parliament.
   In reply, Schlueter invited Auken to negotiate with government
parties ``a sensible solution'' to the issue.
   Until the opposition resolution was passed last month,
successive governments assumed that NATO allies abided by Denmark's
non-nuclear policy.
   The United States and Britain said the new measure, if
implemented, would jeopardize their plans to land troops in times
of crisis to reinforce Denmark, which controls the narrow access to
the Baltic Sea.
   They also said the measure threatened the solidarity of NATO and
was against their own policies, which forbid disclosure of which
ships carry nuclear arms.
   Final results showed 3,913,318 ballots cast for a turnout of
85.8 percent.
   Schlueter's Conservatives lost three seats, retaining 35.
   Foreign Minister Uffe Ellemann-Jensen's Liberals, the senior
coalition partner, won 22 seats, three more than it had before.
   The coalition's nine-seat Center Democrats and four-seat
Christian People's Party were unchanged.
   Capturing seven additional seats to total 16, far-right Progress
Party was the biggest winner. Shunned by the mainstream parties for
its anti-immigration campaign, it is not expected to join a new
non-socialist coalition.
   The Social Democrats stopped their slide from the past two
elections by capturing 55 seats, a gain of one.
   The opposition Socialist People's Party dropped from 27 to 24
seats, while the far-left Common Course failed to poll the 2
percent necessary for representation.
   The swing party Social-Liberals held 10, a loss of one.
   Two semi-independent territories, the Faeroe Islands and
Greenland, each elect two representatives.
   A diplomat from a NATO country, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the nuclear issue ``couldn't come at a worse time.''
   The election came the day before U.S. Secretary of State George
P. Shultz was to meet Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
in Geneva to prepare for a Moscow summit in two weeks. A perception
that Denmark is wavering in its support of NATO could strenghthen
the Soviets' hand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
