<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CancerKid     05-11 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancer Kid,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Easton Boy Granted Wish, Plays Army General</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FORT INDIANTOWN GAP, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Given the chance to be anything
they wanted for a day, many kids might choose to become president
of the United States, an astronaut or a performer.
   But not 4-year-old Jamie Dayhoff, who was recently given such an
opportunity by Dream Come True, an organization that gives
seriously and terminally ill children trips, gifts and celebrity
visits.
   Jamie, who has lymphatic cancer, always said he wanted to be a
soldier so when Army recruiters commissioned him a one-star general
Monday, he was ready.
   He stood tall as he was outfitted in a tailored battle dress
uniform, cap, general's star, a Combat Infantry Badge and dog tags.
   ``Doggie tags, woof, woof,'' Jamie said as the ID tags were
slipped over his head. ``Woo, they're cold.''
   He swore ``to support the Constitution ... against all enemies''
and saluted Lt. Col. Robert Thorlakson, commander of the Harrisburg
Battalion, U.S. Army Recruiting Command.
   ``I'm here to be a general, a GI Joe, a good guy,'' Jamie said
before asking Thorlakson's advice on what orders to give his
soldiers.
   ``Tell them to stand straight, march good, run fast and be good
boys,'' Thorlakson said.
   Despite being a rather young general, the Easton boy took to his
duties like an old pro.
   He fired two blank rounds from an M-16 rifle, carefully
retrieved the spent shells and stored them in his battle fatigues.
   ``I want to do it again,'' Jamie said after trying some
electronic rifle training. Each time Jamie pulled the trigger and
the electronic bullets hit their targets, he squealed in delight.
   ``He always enjoyed the GI Joe experience,'' said Charles
Dayhoff, Jamie's father. ``That was his dream, to eat with and take
a nap with soldiers, take a ride in a jeep and see how they train.''
</TEXT>
