<2ND_LINE>PM-WVa Primary,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moore, Caperton Claim Gubernatorial Nominations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-State Primaries Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By T.J. SIMONEAUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Gov. Arch Moore, seeking an
unprecedented fourth term, beat a strong primary challenge and will
face Democratic political novice Gaston Caperton in November.
   Moore edged Republican challenger John Raese, while Caperton
easily defeated former House of Delegates Speaker Clyde See in
Tuesday's primary election.
   In non-binding presidential preference races, Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis defeated Jesse Jackson, while Vice President George
Bush won the GOP race.
   With 2,079 of 2,151 precincts reporting, or 97 percent, Dukakis
had 243,906 votes, or 79 percent, while Jackson had 43,771 votes,
or 14 percent. In the Republican presidential race, with 2,028
precincts, or 94 percent, reporting, Bush had 104,019 votes, or 90
percent.
   U.S. Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd will face Republican
state Sen. Jay Wolfe in the November general election.
   With 2,078 precincts, or 97 percent, reporting, Byrd, who is
seeking his sixth term, gained 237,037 votes, or 80 percent;
Huntington moving company owner Bob Myers had 57,330 votes, or 20
percent.
   With 2,028 precincts, or 94 percent, reporting, Wolfe won 75,736
votes, ort 70 percent; welfare recipient Bernie Lumbert had 32,491
votes, or 30 percent.
   Byrd promised that, if re-elected, he will step down as majority
leader to become Senate Appropriations Committee chairman so that
he can secure funds and advance programs important to the state.
   The veteran Moore, 65, overcame a late campaign furor over
reports he tried to buy his way onto a political slate for $12,000
in 1972 and held off Raese in the toughest primary he ever faced.
   With more than 2,051 precincts, or 95 percent, reporting early
today, Moore had 73,503 votes, or 53 percent, to Raese's 64,897, or
47 percent.
   Caperton, 48, was a political unknown as the primary season
began, but he poured more than $1.8 million into his successful
attempt to wrest the nomination from See, the Democrats' 1984
nominee.
   With 2,058 precincts, or 96 percent, reporting, Caperton had
122,276 votes, or 38 percent, to See's 87,753, or 27 percent.
Caperton's victory culminated the most expensive primary campaign
ever by a single West Virginia candidate; five other candidates
split the rest of the vote.
   No allegations of voter fraud were lodged in Mingo County, where
Tuesday saw where Tuesday's was the first election since a grand
jury indicted 16 Mingo County politicians on election law charges
as part of a state and federal investigation into political
corruption.
</TEXT>
