<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Nunn-Treaty     05-11 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nunn-Treaty,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Soviet</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nunn Says Pact Could Still Be OKd by Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Sam Nunn, chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said today the Senate could ratify the
U.S.-Soviet nuclear arms agreement in time for the upcoming Moscow
summit if Secretary of State George Shultz works out disputes in
talks this week with the Soviets.
   ``I think there's still time to get the consent of the Senate to
ratification prior to the summit. But these matters have to be
dealt with,'' the Georgia Democrat said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America.''
   Senate leaders said this week consideration of the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty would be delayed
indefinitely because of a dispute between the superpowers over
verification of settlement accords.
   The dispute has almost dashed hopes the INF treaty would be
ratified by the time President Reagan travels to Moscow for the May
29-June 2 summit meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Shultz was in Geneva today for a long-planned meeting with
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze that has taken on
greater importance because of the verification issue.
   Nunn said if the impasse is not resolved, the treaty could
languish in the Senate well after the summit.
   ``Even though I can't visualize these matters not being worked
out, it is possible,'' said Nunn. ``Unless they are worked out, I
think we'll have a long delay and no ratification of the treaty
anytime soon.''
   Nunn said that although the verification provisions under
dispute are technical issues, enough Democrats and Republicans in
the Senate are concerned to keep the treaty on hold.
   ``It is a serious problem because on-site verification goes to
the heart not just of this treaty, in terms of verifying, but also
future treaties,'' he said.
   ``Frankly, the military significance of this treaty is marginal
at best,'' Nunn said. ``But the symbolic and precedent kind of
example here is very important, so we've got to clear these matters
up.''
   Nunn also raised the possibility that the dispute over
provisions signed by negotiators in December could reflect
disagreements among Soviet officials.
   ``It may be that this is not the top leadership at all, but
rather people who lost their points in the negotiation and now are
trying to restore those points through obstruction in
implementation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
