<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Beaches     05-11 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Beaches,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Party Expels Durban Mayor For Opposing Segregated
Beaches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of Durban said today
that the governing National Party suspended him because he opposes
whites-only beaches.
   Henry Klotz, who was elected mayor of South Africa's third
largest city last September, said he would rather be ousted from
the party than retract his support for integration of the entire
Durban beachfront.
   ``The policy of opening facilities must be pursued and I shall
support it absolutely,'' Klotz said in a statement. ``If this means
my explusion from the National Party, then so be it.''
   Durban, along with Cape Town, is one of South Africa's two
largest tourist destinations, and its Indian Ocean beachfront is
lined with resort hotels.
   Klotz received a letter from the Natal Province branch of the
party on Tuesday saying he was being suspended for disloyalty
because he refused to endorse President P.W. Botha's policy on
segregated beaches.
   Botha has supported the integration of some beaches but says
other beaches should remain exclusively for whites. Durban's
beaches reflect this policy _ most areas have been opened to all
races but one prime section called South Beach remains whites-only.
   Klotz said he formerly opposed integration of beaches but now
felt this step was essential ``if we are to succeed in becoming a
truly 21st century, cosmopolitan city.''
   ``All beaches are the property of all people of Durban in
partnership with visitors from South Africa and other countries,''
he said. ``I am duty-bound to act in the interests of all the
citizens of this fair city and I shall do so for as long as I am
able.''
   The far-right Conservative Party, the largest white opposition
party, won three parliamentary by-elections in March with a
campaign platform opposing integrated beaches. Klotz said he did
not believe the issue was a key factor in the by-elections, which
were held in districts far from the coast.
   Last week, a court in Port Elizabeth ruled that the city council
had acted without proper authority in 1966 when it proclaimed the
local beaches segregated. The government promptly appealed the
ruling and said the beaches would remain segregated until the
appeal process was completed.
</TEXT>
