<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Cheever     05-11 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Cheever,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cheever's Widow Trying To Stop New Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Pulitzer Prize-winning author John
Cheever is suing a small Chicago publishing house to halt
publication of a new book of short stories due out in September,
her attorney said.
   ``The Uncollected Short Stories of John Cheever'' is set to be
published by Academy Chicago, which is primarily known for
importing British mystery novels.
   ``Mrs. Cheever objects to the very cavalier treatment she has
been given by this publishing company and the cavalier treatment to
Mr. Cheever's work,'' her attorney, Martin Garbus, said Tuesday.
   The suit will seek to have the contract with Academy declared
invalid because the publisher failed to consult Mrs. Cheever about
the book's content as promised, Garbus said. He said the suit would
likely be filed by week's end in either federal or state court in
Manhattan.
   Mrs. Cheever particularly objected to a forward by Scott
Donaldson, professor of literature at the College of William & Mary
and author of a Cheever biography to be published in June by Random
House.
   Mrs. Cheever said Donaldson was wrong to say that her husband's
early works were left out because he ``repudiated his
apprenticeship and formative years.''
   She said Cheever did not want them used in a 1978 collection and
would not want them used now because they were ``embarrassingly
immature.''
   Mrs. Cheever also objects to Donaldson's interpretation that
Cheever's works were a personal history.
   The 550-page Academy book collects 68 Cheever stories written
for magazines between 1931 and 1981.
   Academy has already brought the matter before the Circuit Court
of Cook County in Chicago to have the contract declared valid. The
company wants the court to enjoin Mrs. Cheever's from interfering
with publication.
   The author, who published his first short story when he was 17,
died in July 1982 at age 70. He won the 1979 Pulitzer Prize for
``The Stories of John Cheever,'' a collection of short fiction
works.
   Other Cheever works include ``The Wapshot Chronicle'' and
``Falconer.''
</TEXT>
