<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0479 05-11 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Premier Picks Chief Of Staff, Promises Prompt Choice Of
Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Rocard choosing chief of
staff, newspaper reaction on his choice as premier. Picks up 21st
graf pvs, `The president...'
^By ELAINE GANLEY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Michel Rocard appointed a longtime aide as
his chief of staff today and consulted with senior Socialists on
choosing Cabinet ministers in his new government.
   President Francois Mitterrand, re-elected on Sunday, appointed
Rocard on Tuesday to succeed conservative Jacques Chirac.
   Rocard, long a rival to Mitterrand within the Socialist Party,
said he would not delay naming his Cabinet ministers, but it was
not clear how soon the appointments would come.
   The first move by the 57-year-old premier was to name Jean Paul
Huchon his chief of staff. Huchon was chief of staff to Rocard when
he was planning minister, then agriculture minister, in Socialist
governments from 1981-85.
   He is first deputy mayor of Conflans St. Honorine, the
working-class town in the Paris suburbs where Rocard has been mayor
since 1977.
   It is common in France for senior national officials to keep
their mayoral posts. Chirac, who was premier for two years, has
been mayor of Paris for more than a decade.
   Mitterrand, 71, was re-elected to a seven-year term in a
landslide victory over Chirac on Sunday. But the success of a new
government will depend largely on whether the Socialists gain the
confidence of a broad spectrum of voters _ and backing from
centrist politicans.
   Chirac's center-right coalition still controls the 577-seat
National Assembly, marking the first time in the 30 years of the
French Fifth Republic that a government must face a hostile
Parliament.
   Commentary on Rocard's appointment was largely favorable in
French newspapers, even those that traditionally support rightist
policies.
   The conservative daily Le Figaro noted that Rocard favored a
free-market economy and said he had ``shown his independent
spirit'' by bucking official Socialist positions in the past.
   Former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, a prominent centrist
member of the assembly, said on Tuesday that he was ``waiting for a
gesture toward a united France'' in the composition of Rocard's
Cabinet.
   Rocard, 57, told reporters Tuesday that he would keep in mind
French people's concerns ``for their future, for their jobs, for
their education, for their security.''
   He must assemble a government which reflects the Socialists'
swing to the center and which can try to work with the conservative
parliamentary majority.
   Mitterrand says he will not automatically dissolve the assembly
to try to gain a leftist majority, choosing to try for success with
the present system. He also says the new government will include
non-Socialists.
   The new government is expected to profit from an increasingly
divided right wing, ranging from centrists to ultraright.
   Presenting himself as France's ``unifier,'' Mitterrand wooed
over some centrist politicians upset with Chirac's attempt to
accommodate the growing far-right movement.
   Rocard, a self-described ``free enterprise leftist,'' was
prepared to run for the presidency this year until Mitterrand
declared his candidacy.
   Polls usually rate him as one of France's most popular
politicans. A non-doctrinaire Socialist, he symbolizes the
president's effort for a policy of ``enlargement'' beyond the
Socialist ranks.
   The debonair, 5-foot-7 Rocard is known for his independent and
outspoken views. He resigned as agriculture minister in 1985
because he objected to a new system of proportional voting
instituted by the Socialists.
   The president bucked pressure in affirming that he will not
immediately dissolve the National Assembly, in which the Socialists
hold 211 seats.
   Mitterrand is being urged to take advantage of the victory
momentum and move quickly with changes.
   The president, stressing the new political configuration, has
made few concrete proposals for change.
   One of the few significant programs Mitterrand says he intends
to pursue is re-establishing the Socialist wealth tax abolished by
Chirac in 1986. He wants the proceeds to fund a minimum guaranteed
income.
   Mitterrand also says he will not continue the Chirac
government's privatization of state-owned companies.
</TEXT>
