<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0837EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TransplantAftermath     05-11 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transplant Aftermath,0428</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Heart Transplant Recipients Risk Mood Troubles, Family Distress,
Study Says
^By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study of heart transplant recipients has
found that half suffered mood disturbances after the operation and
many faced family problems related to the surgery and recovery.
   The results indicate psychiatrists must work to help recipients
get the most out of life after transplants, researchers said
Tuesday.
   Side effects of post-transplant medications cause some of the
psychological problems, said Peter Shapiro, assistant clinical
professor of psychiatry at the Columbia University College of
Physicians and Surgeons in New York.
   He and colleague Donald Kornfeld did the work, which Shapiro
presented Tuesday at the annual meeting of the American Psychiatric
Association.
   ``This is a very important paper. It's really pace-setting and
pace-making,'' said Norman B. Levy of the New York Medical College
at Valhalla, an authority on psychiatric aspects of transplants.
   The research was done with two groups of recipients. One group
of 30 was interviewed at up to a year after surgery, while another
43 were studied up to six years after the transplant.
   Overall, 37 of the 73 recipients had experienced some kind of
mood disturbances following the surgery. Problems ranged from
demoralization and difficulty adjusting to post-transplant life to
four cases of major depression.
   Fifteen of the 37 patients reported a period of mood swings,
irritability and argumentativeness, often with some mild mania.
Symptoms began in the first few weeks after transplantation and
gradually receded as dosages of drugs to prevent organ rejection
were tapered off.
   Twenty-two patients reported sexual problems as a side effect of
anti-rejection drugs.
   Twelve patients said they had experienced family or marital
troubles, such as children running away from home or picking fights
with their parents.
   The second problem was especially common with teenage sons who
resented the father's trying to re-assert a role of disciplinarian
now that the disabling heart condition was over, Shapiro said.
   Some problems result from the use of the anti-rejection drug
cyclosporine, which is inconvenient to administer and accompanied
by such side effects as headache, burning pains and interference
with sexual performance, researchers said in a written version of
the report.
   ``Impotence and fearful avoidance of sexual intercourse lead
many patients to feel guilt and disappointment, which is expressed
in fighting or creating psychological distance from the partner,''
they said.
   ``These problems tend to work out over the course of 12 to 18
months.''
   Sixteen patients also complained of decreased memory.
</TEXT>
