<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Crash-Drugs     05-11 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Drugs,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Traces Found in Rail Workers; MTA Chairman Seeks Review of
Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials will seek an immediate review of drug
and alcohol testing practices on local railways following the
discovery that five employees involved in a fatal commuter train
crash last month had used drugs.
   The Federal Railroad Administration released test results
Tuesday showing that an engineer killed in the April 6 Metro-North
train crash had marijuana in his system, and that a dispatcher's
urine contained morphine and codeine.
   ``This insanity has got to stop,'' John Riley, head of the FRA,
said.
   Discovery of the drug traces also prompted Riley to reissue his
call for random testing of rail workers.
   In the last 16 months, Riley noted, there has been a rail
accident every 10 days somewhere in the nation in which at least
one employee tested positive for drugs. The dead or injured in
these accidents number 370, he said.
   Metropolitan Transportation Authority Chairman Robert R. Kiley
called for an immediate review of testing practices at Metro-North,
the Long Island Rail Road and the city's Transit Authority.
Metro-North serves Westchester County, north of the city, and
Fairfield County, Conn.
   In the Metro-North crash, morphine traces found in dispatcher
Thomas Furlong's urine were ``comparable to those which could be
expected following heroin use,'' said Lou Brott, an FRA spokesman.
   Engineer Raymond Hunter was killed when his empty train slammed
into the rear of another empty commuter train. He tested positive
for marijuana in his urine and his blood, the FRA said.
   Metro-North officials have blamed Hunter, 42, for failing to
activate an automatic safety system that could have prevented the
collision. They also said the train appeared to be traveling well
over the 15 mph speed limit.
   Three other railroad employees who controlled train movements
also had controlled substances in their systems, the FRA said.
   The three, who worked at a station near the crash site, have
been absolved of responsibility for the crash, according to Susan
Gilbert, a Metro-North spokeswoman. Along with Furlong, who worked
in Manhattan, they were suspended after the accident and now face
disciplinary hearings.
   Metro-North employees found to have used drugs on the job must
enter a substance abuse program or face dismissal. They also are
subject to spot drug testing while in the program.
   Riley declined to say whether the tests indicated drugs might
have affected the men's performances. A final report on the
accident, to be released in about two months, will determine what
role drug use played in the crash, he said.
   The tests, he said, did not indicate how recently the workers
might have used the drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
