<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrailsideSlayings     05-11 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trailside Slayings,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Convicted Quickly in California `Trailside Slayings'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury took only seven hours to weigh 500
pieces of evidence and testimony from 91 witnesses, then found a
man guilty of killing five hikers in a series of ``trailside
slayings'' that terrorized Northern California parks.
   The Superior Court jury that convicted David J. Carpenter on
Tuesday will return next week to begin for the penalty phase to
determine whether the he should be executed or spend the rest of
his life in prison.
   Carpenter, 58, of San Francisco, was convicted of first-degree
murder with special circumstances in the 1980 killings of five
hikers in two Marin County parks, part of a series of crimes dubbed
the ``trailside slayings'' eight years ago.
   After four months of hearing evidence, the jury returned the
verdict against Carpenter at the end of its second day of
deliberations. Attorneys on both sides were surprised by the quick
decision.
   ``It certainly seems to suggest they didn't buy anything the
defense presented,'' said Marin County Deputy District Attorney
John Posey, who portrayed Carpenter in closing arguments as a
cold-blooded killer whose ``ultimate goal'' was to commit murder
and rape and get away with it.
   ``We were much more hopeful than this,'' said defense attorney
Frank Cox. ``It came as a surprise to have an unfavorable verdict
as fast as this.''
   Defense attorneys argued Carpenter deserved acquittal because of
``serious doubts'' created by what they termed questionable police
procedures and inconsistencies in the testimony of witnesses.
   Carpenter, who already has been sentenced to the gas chamber for
two related killings in Santa Cruz parks, sat expressionless as
Judge Herbert B. Hoffman read the verdict.
   Carpenter spent eight days on the stand testifying in his own
defense, alleging he was miles away from the murder sites on the
days of the killings at Point Reyes National Seashore and Mount
Tamalpais State Park.
   He was convicted of murdering Richard Stowers, 19, of Petaluma;
Cynthia Moreland, 18, of Cotati; Anne Alderson, 26, of San Rafael;
Diane O'Connell, 22, of San Jose, and Shauna May, 23, of San
Francisco.
   Carpenter was also convicted of raping two of his Marin victims
and trying to rape a third.
   Defense attorneys said they would spend the rest of the week
developing a strategy for the penalty hearing scheduled to begin
Tuesday.
   Carpenter's automatic appeal in the Santa Cruz case is pending
before the state Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
