<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0905EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BeefFat     05-11 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beef Fat,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Beef Fat Not As Bad As Experts Once Believed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: The 6 p.m. EDT embargo on this story has been broken</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study suggests that eating beef may not be
as bad for the heart as experts had once assumed because one of its
major forms of saturated fat lowers cholesterol.
   Despite their findings, however, the study's authors recommended
that people stick to widely accepted dietary guidelines and keep
their fat intake as low as possible.
   The study, conducted by Drs. Scott M. Grundy and Andrea
Bonanome, found that stearic acid, one of the main components of
saturated fat in the diet, appears to lower the body's cholesterol
levels.
   Until now, many experts assumed that all kinds of saturated fat,
including those containing stearic acid, were bad for the heart
because they promote clogging deposits of cholesterol.
   Grundy said that if people eat moderate portions of lean beef,
``it should not be feared as a cholesterol-raising food.''
   The research, conducted at the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center at Dallas, was scheduled to be published in
Thursday's issue of the New England Journal of Medicine.
   In an accompanying editorial, Drs. Irwin H. Rosenberg and Ernst
J. Schaefer of the USDA Human Nutrition Research Center on Aging at
Tufts University in Boston praised the work. They said it
``demonstrates convincingly'' that a diet high in stearic acid does
not raise blood cholesterol.
   But they were also cautious in interpreting the findings,
concluding, ``This study should not change our chief dietary
message to the American people.''
   Beef contains two major forms of saturated fat _ stearic acid
and palmitic acid. And while stearic acid lowers cholesterol,
palmitic acid raises it significantly.
   Stearic acid is found in varying amounts in many other foods,
too, including chicken and vegetables.
   Saturated fats are hard at room temperature, while
polyunsaturated and monosaturated fats, which come largely from
vegetables, are liquid.
   The researchers said the food industry may be able to use
stearic acid to make margarine that is more like butter, as well as
a cholesterol-lowering form of shortening for cooking.
   The study was based on 11 men who consumed three liquid diets
that were high in either stearic acid, palmitic acid or oleic acid,
a monosaturated fat that also lowers cholesterol.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
