<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Ng     05-11 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Ng,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect in U.S. Mass Murder Case Wins Five-Month Extradition Delay
^EDS: Ng is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Ng, wanted in connection with
the slayings of 12 people in California, has won a five-month delay
in his Canadian extradition hearing.
   On Tuesday, a judge in the Alberta Court of Queen's Bench
granted the delay until Oct. 17 at the request of defense lawyer
Donald MacLeod.
   Ng, a 27-year-old former U.S. marine, listened intently to three
hours of procedural arguments but displayed no emotion. Dressed in
blue jeans and a plaid shirt, he was shackled at the wrists and
ankles.
   A dozen police officers provided tight security, reporters and
spectators were checked with metal detectors and a police dog was
at the courtroom entrance.
   Ng faces 25 criminal charges in the United States, including 12
of capital murder. Eleven of the homicide charges involve 1985
sex-torture killings at a rural cabin in Calaveras County, east of
San Francisco. The other concerns the 1984 slaying of San Francisco
disc jockey Donald Guiletti.
   U.S. authorities applied for Ng's extradition in February 1987.
His lawyers have said they will fight his return to the United
States unless they are convinced he won't face the death penalty in
California if convicted.
   When the Canadian Parliament banned capital punishment in 1976,
the government signed an extradition treaty which allows it to
refuse to extradite fugitives who may face the death penalty in the
United States. However, the federal justice minister can waive that
right.
   Ng is serving a 4{-year sentence at the federal penitentiary in
Prince Albert, Saskatchewan, for armed robbery, aggravated assault
and unlawful use of a firearm. He was convicted in December 1985
after a shoplifting attempt at a Calgary department store during
which Ng shot a security guard in the hand.
</TEXT>
