<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Regan-Bush     05-11 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Regan-Bush,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Regan Says Bush Should Run on Reagan's Economic Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House chief of staff Donald T.
Regan today urged likely Republican nominee George Bush to use
President Reagan's economic record as his platform in the race for
the presidency.
   ``I certainly make the case for Reaganomics and the Reagan
record in my book,'' Regan said on CBS-TV's ``This Morning'' show,
referring to his recently-released memoir, ``For the Record.''
``And if George Bush chooses to run on the Reagan record, I think
he'll be running on a very strong platform.''
   The vice president has a mathematical lock on the nomination and
is expected to pick up Reagan's endorsement later today.
   Regan, whose behind-the-scenes book has angered the Reagans for
its descriptions of a disengaged president influenced by a first
lady motivated by astrology, said he often failed to get Reagan to
focus on critical economic issues.
   As Treasury secretary, Regan said he was ``flying by the seat of
my pants.''
   ``The president never told me what he believed or what he wanted
to accomplish in the field of economics. I had to figure these
things out like any other American, by studying his speeches and
reading the newspapers,'' Regan writes.
   While crediting Reagan with creating ``an atmosphere of
confidence,'' that helped in the recovery from 1981-82 recession,
Regan said, ``the president himself had very little to do with the
invention and the implementation of the policies'' that came to be
called ``Reaganomics.''
   Nevertheless, Regan said today that Reaganomics deserves high
marks.
   ``I think Reaganomics has proven successful. We've had 5{ years
of expansion ... and the possibility of more months to come in
that,'' he said.
   ``We've had a change in morale in the American people over the
last few years. Remember that ... the malaise and all that sort of
thing, that's what Reagan inherited and yet as he leaves office we
feel a lot better about ourselves. Internationally, I think we're
better off too,'' he said.
</TEXT>
