<HEAD>Billionaire Boys Club Members Get Life Sentence Without Parole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge, ignoring a plea for mercy
by the victim's widow, sentenced two members of the Billionaire
Boys Club to life in prison without parole for murdering one
defendant's father.
   Sentenced Tuesday were Arben Dosti and Reza Eslaminia, the
26-year-old son of Hedayat Eslaminia, who was kidnapped and
suffocated in a steamer trunk in July 1984.
   San Mateo County Superior Court Judge Robert D. Miller sentenced
Eslaminia and Dosti, 26, despite Eslaminia's mothers' plea for
leniency.
   ``I believe Reza is innocent,'' Mina Hakimi, widow of the
victim, told the judge in broken English. The elder Eslaminia had
at one time been an adviser to the Shah of Iran.
   ``Your crime involved a great deal of thought, planning and
execution,'' the judge said. ``For that reason, I'm sentencing you
to life without possibility of parole.''
   Eslaminia's attorney, Gary Merritt, said his client was not
present during the kidnapping or death of his father and was only
involved in conspiracy to kidnap.
   Assistant state Attorney General John Vance noted that the jury
had found Eslaminia guilty of murder after a trial of about 50 days.
   The two were convicted in January of murder, kidnapping for
extortion and conspiracy in the plot to kidnap the elder Eslaminia
for ransom, then kill him. The victim suffocated, apparently
accidentally, inside the steamer trunk hours after being kidnapped
from his condominium in July 1984.
   Authorities had originally suspected that the elder Eslaminia, a
former Iranian Parliament member and Cabinet member under the Shah,
had been killed by a hit squad sent by the Iranian revolutionary
government that deposed the Shah in 1979.
   Eslaminia was active in the movement against Iran's leader,
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Dosti and Eslaminia were members of the BBC, which was founded
by Joe Hunt in 1983 as a business fraternity of bright young men
from some of Southern California's wealthiest families.
   Hunt, 27, was sentenced last July 6 to life in prison without
parole in the slaying of Ronald Levin, who vanished in the summer
of 1984 and whose body was never found.
</TEXT>
