<2ND_LINE>PM-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0589,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Move Sharply Lower On Interest Rate Fears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with later trading, details; a version on the
financial wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were sharply lower at midday today
with the market unnerved after Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel
Lawson said a rise in interest rates of the major world economies
was possible.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 30.2
points, or 1.7 percent, to 1,762.4 by 12:15 p.m., its lowest level
so far in the session.
   Volume was a relatively strong 355.7 million shares compared
with 233.5 million shares at the same time on Tuesday.
   Lawson's comment, published in European editions of the Wall
Street Journal, that a worldwide rise in interest rates could be in
the cards sent share prices plunging, dealers said.
   Lawson said a coordinated effort by West Germany, Japan and
other leading nations to hike interest rates ``is certainly
possible'' following the Federal Reserve's increase in short-term
rates to curb U.S. inflation.
   The equity market was shaken by the idea that the leading
economic nations could join in a bid to choke off inflationary
pressures by pushing up the cost of borrowing.
   The Lawson comment was acting as ``a dark cloud over the entire
market,'' one equity salesman said.
   Some favorable earnings results by major U.K. companies were
ignored by the market, dealers said, as players chose to focus on
Lawson's remark.
</TEXT>
