<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpanishBanned     05-11 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spanish Banned,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nursing Home's English-Only Policy Upsets Hispanic Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hispanic workers at a nursing home have
been told they can no longer speak their native tongue on the job,
an order some of the workers have challenged as discriminatory.
   ``I continue to speak Spanish,'' said Doris Leal, a nurses' aide
at Nutmeg Pavilion Healthcare. ``Maybe I'm going to be fired, but
I'm going to fight for my rights.''
   ``I don't feel comfortable in my job anymore,'' said Maria
Rivera, another aide at Nutmeg. ``I don't feel free when I'm
working, so it's very difficult to do the job.''
   Officials outlined the policy to employees at a staff meeting
last week, according to staff members quoted in today's editions of
The Day newspaper of New London. The policy requires that employees
speak English in all areas except the coffee lounge during working
hours.
   James O'Kane, administrator of the facility, defended the policy
and said the workers have not filed any formal protest.
   ``On the floor we're to communicate with patients and other
staff to the utmost,'' O'Kane said. ``If I don't know what you're
talking about, it's difficult to be a team.''
   O'Kane said it makes English-speaking patients uncomfortable
when they cannot understand the health-care workers. ``Whether it's
Spanish or German or Greek or Gaelic is beside the point,'' O'Kane
said.
   Louis J. Halpryn, director of the Connecticut Nursing Home
Association, said he has not heard of any similar policies at other
nursing homes.
   Arvid J. Anderson, vice president of Lawrence and Memorial
Hospital in New London, said most of L&M's employees speak English
on the job, ``but we don't have any policy that says they have to.''
   Anderson said he values multilingual employees who can interpret
for non-English speaking patients, and he often hears employees
speaking in another language in the patient care areas, which he
has no objections to.
   Mrs. Leal said the policy affects seven nurses that she knows of.
   ``There is no law I know of in the United States that says you
can only speak English,'' she said. ``Maybe I'm wrong, but I think
it's discrimination.''
   The nurses said they have complained to the state Commission on
Human Rights and Opportunities, but have been told that panel
cannot help them.
</TEXT>
