<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Census-Dropouts     05-11 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Census-Dropouts,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Older Minorities in High School, Census Bureau Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Census Bureau says that 11 percent of
black and Hispanic Americans aged 18 to 21 are still in high
school, double the rate for whites.
   The agency, in a report released Tuesday, also found that 25
percent of the young blacks and 22 percent of the Hispanics in that
age group were enrolled in college, compared with 39 percent of
their white peers.
   The proportion of young blacks dropping out of high school
plummeted from 27 percent in 1975 to 17 percent in 1985, while the
proportion who were graduated from high school rose from 61 percent
to 71 percent.
   But the proportion enrolled in college stayed the same _ 25
percent, said the Census Bureau report, ``School Enrollment: Social
and Economic Characteristics of Students.''
   Forty-seven percent of the blacks in the 18-21 age group were
high school graduates not enrolled in college, up from 36 percent
in 1975.
   Eleven percent of blacks were still in high school in 1985, down
from 12.5 percent in 1975.
   Among Hispanics, the proportion enrolled in college dropped over
the decade from 24 percent to 22 percent; the proportion of high
school graduates not enrolled in college rose from 33 percent to 38
percent; the proportion of dropouts fell from 31 to 29 percent; and
the proportion still in high school dipped from 12 percent to 11
percent.
   Among whites, the proportion enrolled in college grew from 35
percent to 39 percent; the proportion of high school graduates not
enrolled in college dropped from 46 percent to 42.5 percent; the
proportion of dropouts fell from 15 percent to 14 percent; and
those still in high school grew slightly, from 4.7 percent to 5.1
percent.
   Other Census Bureau reports have previously noted a sharp spurt
in black college enrollments before 1975, and a drop since then in
the proportion of black graduates advancing to college.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
