<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Fiji 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0558,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fiji Sends Gunboat To Island As King Plans to Secede</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead to CLARIFY that king wants to secede from Fiji.
Pick up 2nd pvs, `It said...' Minor editing thereafter.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunboat with 30 Fiji soldiers today headed
for an island where a self-styled king threatened to declare
independence from the South Pacific archipelago, the army said.
   It said a navy patrol boat was on its way to the Rotuma, 400
miles north of Suva, in case of trouble from the Malmahao clan,
whose leader intended to secede from Fiji.
   Reports from Rotuma said the island would hoist the British flag
and declare its secession on Friday, the 107th anniversary of
Rotuma's annexation by Britain. Fiji was a British colony until
1970, when it became an independent nation within the Commonwealth.
   Saturday marks the first anniversary of the military coup that
ousted the Indian-dominated government of Timoci Bavadra. Seven
months ago, coup leader Sitiveni Rabuka declared Fiji a republic.
   Rotuma's self-styled king is Sau Lagfatmaro, also known as Henry
Gibson, a martial arts expert with a home in Auckland, New Zealand.
He is partly of Rotuman descent.
   Lagfatmaro has claimed the title ``gagaj,'' meaning king, of one
of the seven clans forming the Rotuman community and has said that
on Friday his supporters will lower the Fiji flag.
   Rotuma since 1881 has been administered from Suva, first by the
British and since 1970 by Fiji.
   Unlike Fiji, where most of the 715,000 population is Melanesian,
Rotuma's 3,000 residents are mostly Polynesian.
   Lagfatmaro's whereabouts were not immediately known, but several
of his followers had been reported arrested and charged with
sedition.
   Britain's ambassador to Fiji, Roger Barltrop, was visiting
Rotuma at the invitation of the island council. Further details
were not available.
   Rabuka, meantime, was reported planning a parade on Saturday to
commemorate the South Pacific's first military takeover.
   Army sources said Rabuka, army commander as well as a member of
the semi-military government, had called all territorial soldiers
to barracks as a precaution against expected protests by coup
opponents.
</TEXT>
