<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeSillers     05-11 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DeSillers Lashes Out at Report of Misspent Donations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria DeSillers responded angrily to a
court-appointed official's report that she spent some $200,000
donated for her late son's liver transplants on herself, relatives
and friends.
   ``I am not a thief. I did not do anything wrong,'' Ms. DeSillers
said Tuesday after an unrelated hearing over a $1,000 state fine
levied against her in the wake of charges that she violated
Florida's charity laws.
   ``I resent the way I'm being treated, the way it's been
handled,'' she said.
   Ms. DeSillers' 7-year-old son Ronnie died at Children's Hospital
in Pittsburgh last year while awaiting a fourth liver transplant.
His plight resulted in a highly publicized fund-raising drive that
included a $1,000 donation from President Reagan.
   Karen Geivers, appointed at the request of the Dade state
attorney's office to review Ms. DeSillers' spending, on Monday
filed court documents listing questionable expenses paid from the
donations.
   Among the payments were $10,850 to a jewelry store, $23,700 to
Ms. DeSillers' ex-boyfriend, and $96,527 in cash withdrawals for
personal expenses.
   Ms. DeSillers has said the expenditures were reasonable and that
she needed the clothing and jewelry to look ``professional'' when
she tried to raise money for organ donor awareness after her son's
death. She is president of the Ronnie DeSillers National Foundation.
   Ms. Gievers in her report accused Ms. DeSillers of having
``ignored the laws ... when it suited her purposes to do so.''
   Ms. DeSillers denied the charges. ``I'm not saying I'm perfect.
But ... how could she say on there that I know the law and I
disregarded it. It's crazy.''
   Among the questionable expenditures found by Ms. Gievers were
$5,798 to the Cache clothing store, $3,163 for furniture, $6,134
for Ms. DeSillers' brother Osvaldo Marchante, $13,500 for a used
BMW, $23,700 to her attorneys and $44,359 to other sick children.
   Ms. DeSillers said the money to Dimas jewelry was to buy back
items she had pawned in early 1987 to pay her son's medical
expenses. The payments to her brother and to her boyfriend Jose
Castillo were for loans they had made to her, she said.
   Ms. DeSillers is appealing the charity law fine, and at the
Tuesday hearing Timothy Jansen of the Florida Secretary of State's
Office accused Ms. DeSillers of misleading the public.
   ``I don't think that the people who donated money intended that
the money for Ronnie should go for cars, the rent, jewelry and
certain other expenditures,'' Jansen said.
   Hearing examiner Donald Alexander will make a decision on the
fine within 30 days, said Harry Robbins, Ms. DeSillers' attorney.
   According to court documents, almost $300,000 of the $527,000
that remained in Ronnie's account when he died has been spent.
About $243,500 remains in the estate.
</TEXT>
