<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0545,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Arrest Journalists, Uprising Leaders Prepare For
Monthlong Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with arrests, issuing of leaflets,
other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers and police arrested at least six
Palestinian journalists today, and leaders of the Palestinian
uprising issued a new leaflet calling on Arabs to store enough food
for a month of civil disobedience.
   The army command today said it was pleased with the response of
Palestinians in the occupied Gaza Strip to a potentially explosive
campaign to issue new identity cards to the area's 400,000 adults.
   Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel has
occupied since 1967, began demonstrating against the occupation
last Dec. 8. According to U.N. figures, 185 Palestinians have died
in the five months of violence. An Israeli soldier and a Jewish
teen-age settler also have been killed.
   ``The uprising has made the Palestinian problem a central issue
in the world,'' said the leaflet distributed in the occupied lands
and in Arab east Jerusalem, which was annexed by Israel. ``The
uprising is becoming a ghost which scares the enemy.''
   It urged ``a complete boycott of the Zionists'' and asks the
people to ``ready themselves for civil disobedience by storing food
in houses, enough for at least a month.''
   In Jerusalem and its suburbs, police and soldiers began rounding
up journalists and community leaders at about 1 a.m. (6 p.m. EDT
Tuesday), according to Arab reports.
   At least 11 people were seized, including two editors of the
pro-Palestine Liberation Organization newspaper Al Fajr, which has
become a voice of the uprising. Four other journalists were
arrested, along with a union leader, head of a youth council, and
several other Palestinians, the reports said.
   The army refused to comment on the reports.
   Israel radio reported that 47 people have been charged with
manslaughter in the death of man who allegedly collaborated with
Israeli authorities. The victim, Mohammed Id Sakanda, was lynched
by a mob in the village of Qabatiye in the West Bank in February.
   Today, soldiers with loudspeakers ordered West Bank merchants to
close their shops in the morning but said they could open any time
after noon.
   The move is part of a continued effort to force storekeepers to
operate at times dictated by the army, not by uprising leaders who
have ordered repeated general strikes.
   The new leaflet, the 16th issued by the United Leaders of the
Uprising, called for demonstrations on the Moslem holy day, Friday,
and a general strike and ``day of anger'' next Sunday.
   It also urged protests on Id el Fitr, the end of the Moslem
fasting month of Ramadan, which is expected to be Monday or Tuesday
when the new moon is sighted. It also urged a general strike on May
21.
   The leaflet called on Palestinians to keep refusing to pay taxes
to Israel and to refuse to obtain new government identity cards.
   The army began a campaign on Tuesday to force 400,000 residents
of the Gaza Strip to get new cards, a move that protest leaders say
is aimed at catching tax evaders and breaking the five-month
uprising.
   ``The first day of the program to issue new identification cards
passed very well,'' an army spokesman told The Associated Press on
condition of anonymity. ``There were no incidents and 2,000 people
received new cards.''
   The army has outlined a month-long first phase encompassing
200,000 adults between the ages of 16 to 60 in Gaza City.
   The government also has been pushing to collect back taxes and
other lapsed fees.
   Underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising issued leaflets
and had broadcast warnings from mosque loudspeakers urging
residents not to cooperate with the army. They charge the ID
program is a plot to break the Palestinian uprising, a main tactic
of which is nonpayment of taxes.
   The left-wing daily Al Hamishmar today issued a scathing
editorial of the army plan, saying the army might be trying to put
pressure on the families of young Palestinian protesters by denying
their parents the new card.
   It could create ``a layer of `cardless' residents who will be
illegal residents in an area where they live and even were born.''
   Jewish settlers, meanwhile, reacted angrily to charges by the
chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, that they were aggravating
tensions in the occupied territories.
   Shomron angered Jewish settlers on Tuesday when he told a
parliamentary committee the settlers were raising tensions in the
occupied lands.
   ``It's as if he would say the residents of Israel's northern
border were responsible for the Katyusha rockets fired at them
(from Lebanon),'' said Benny Katzover, a leader of Gush Emunim, a
religious settlement movement. ``The Arabs want to throw us out of
all of the Land of Israel.''
</TEXT>
