<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0595 05-11 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0595,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Declared In Lebanon After Battle Kills 19</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE casualties. Pick up 5th graf
pvs: `We hold...' Edits thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shiite Moslem militias with tanks,
howitzers, rockets and mortars fought each other today for control
of the slums of south Beirut. Police said 26 people were killed and
61 wounded.
   A cease-fire called by Syrian and Iranian mediators went into
effect eight hours after fighting began at 2:30 a.m., police said.
   Earlier today, Syria repeated a warning that it might use its
troops to halt the battle between the pro-Syrian Amal militia and
the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, which had shattered an earlier 24-hour
truce.
   The battle occurred near where many of the 18 foreign hostages
in Lebanon are believed held. There was no word on the hostages.
Since fighting broke out Friday, 180 people have been killed and
433 wounded.
   ``We hold the (militia) leaders responsible for all the crimes
committed against humanity in south Beirut and urge them to order a
cease-fire before it is too late,'' acting Prime Minister Salim
Hoss said in a statement broadcast by all radio stations before the
truce was announced.
   Beirut residents were shaken awake by the thuds of exploding
shells that echoed across the Lebanese capital as Amal, Arabic for
hope, mounted a five-pronged attack against Hezbollah, or Party of
God.
   A police spokesman said tank-led Amal forces, advancing behind a
fierce barrage of howitzer, rocket and mortar fire, dislodged
Hezbollah fundamentalists from several areas they had conquered in
the past five days on the western edge of south Beirut abutting the
airport highway.
   He said flight schedules were unaffected and that passengers
reached the airport through side streets.
   Hezbollah stormed Amal positions deep in south Beirut and
occupied the militia's main base in the district of Bourj
el-Barajneh, east of the airport highway, he said.
   The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity according to
regulations, said Hezbollah occupied a police station in Bourj
el-Barajneh.
   The Sahel hospital, closest to the contested area, advised
rescuers through the Moslem-run Voice of Nation radio to take the
wounded to other hospitals because ``we can't cope with the flood
of casualties.''
   The police spokesman said Syrian officers and Iran's Deputy
Foreign Minister Hussein Sheikholeslam ordered the cease-fire, the
fourth since Friday, after contacting Amal and Hezbollah leaders.
``Fighting eased into sporadic exchanges of automatic fire,'' the
spokesman said.
   Before the cease-fire was announced, Syria's military
intelligence chief in Lebanon, Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, repeated a
warning that his troops may intervene to stop the fighting.
   ``If the bloodletting continues, we will have no other option
but to respond to the pleas of the population and end their
ordeal,'' Kenaan said in a statement broadcast by all Beirut radio
stations.
   Syria sent 7,500 troops to west Beirut in February 1987 to curb
militia lawlessness in the Moslem sector of the Lebanese capital.
The slums, however, were outside the Syrian contingent's
jurisdiction.
   Thirty-six Syrian officers and six joint cease-fire committees
moved into the slums on Tuesday to enforce the truce. But Amal and
Hezbollah used the calm to fortify their positions for another
round of violence.
   Police said Amal brought about 2,500 fighters from its
strongholds in south Lebanon during the 24-hour lull to help its
4,000-strong force in south Beirut stage today's attack.
   Hezbollah had gained control of much of the slums before Friday.
Its fighting strength is estimated at 3,000.
   Syria is Iran's main Arab backer in its Persian Gulf war with
Iraq. But there have been growing signs of a strain in the alliance
amid pressures on Damascus from other Arab nations to distance
itself from Persian Iran.
   Syria, which considers Lebanon its exclusive sphere of
influence, also has been angry over Iran's drive, using Hezbollah
as its instrument, to dominate the 1.2 million Shiites in Lebanon,
the country's largest single sect.
</TEXT>
