<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagans-Astrology 2ndLd-Writethru a0654 05-11 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagans-Astrology, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0654,320</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new, picking up 5th graf pvs, White House.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After saying Nancy Reagan had not talked with
her astrolger in a couple of months, White House officials were
caught off guard today when the stargazer said she had been in
touch with the first lady this week.
   ``I just don't know anything about it,'' said Elaine Crispen,
the press secretary to Mrs. Reagan. ``I wasn't aware they had
talked. I had no idea.''
   The astrolger, Joan Quigley of San Francisco, said she had
spoken with Mrs. Reagan this week but would not reveal her reaction
to the flap over the use of stargazing in planning the schedule of
President Reagan.
   Quigley's statement contradicted what White House officials were
saying.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater and Mrs. Crispen both
said on Tuesday that it had been ``a couple of months'' since Mrs.
Reagan had been in touch with the astrologer.
   In his new book, former White House chief of staff Donald T.
Regan says the first lady regularly consulted a San Francisco
astrologer about scheduling for the president, policy matters and
decisions.
   The White House has adopted a ``no-comment'' policy on specifics
in the book, trying to dampen the stargazing controversy.
   Fitzwater, at his regular news briefing, was asked whether Mrs.
Reagan had used a ``secure'' telephone line to speak with Quigley,
and if not, had there been a breach of security.
   ``I have no idea,'' Fitzwater replied.
   Asked to assess the role of astrology in preparation of the
president's schedule, Fitzwater said, ``We have not commented on
that in the past, and I would say only that the president's
scheduling is a process involving many people and many different
considerations and concerns.''
   Mrs. Crispen said Quigley had been to the White House only once,
at a state dinner. Other than that, the first lady had communicated
with her only by telephone, Mrs. Crispen said.
   She said she did not know how often they talked.
</TEXT>
