<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Arrests     05-11 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Arrests,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seize Huge Arms Cache, Arrest Four Whites As Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four whites, including a woman
and two army deserters, were arrested and accused of amassing a
large arms cache to carry out attacks for the African National
Congress, police said today.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok, in a statement, described
the four as ``a highly specialized terror unit.''
   The weaponry seized in connection with their arrests Sunday was
described as the largest arms cache ever uncovered by the police.
Vlok said it included a Soviet-made ground-to-air missile, limpet
mines, hand grenades, assault rifles, pistols, mchine guns, mortars
and explosives.
   Vlok alleged that the suspects had been trained in Moscow, Cuba
and Angola, and had radio transmitters which they used to
communicate with the headquarters of the African National Congress
guerrilla group in Lusaka, Zambia.
   The congress, outlawed in South Africa since 1960, began a
sabotage-and-bombing campaign the next year aimed at toppling
white-minority rule.
   Vlok said three of the suspects were South African citizens and
declined to give the nationality of the fourth. He said two had
deserted from the armed forces and one was a former South African
journalist. They all were in their 20s and 30s, he said.
   Vlok said police were still investigating how the weapons were
brought into South Africa, but he said the arms came overland
through Zambia and Botswana.
   By law and custom in South Africa, apartheid establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
