<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSResignation 1stLd-Writethru a0648 05-11 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Resignation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Education Director For CDC Quits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead and SUBS 5th graf, ``The agency has xxx, with three
grafs to include CDC confirmation, effort to reach Van Ness</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paula Van Ness, director of the Centers for
Disease Control's AIDS education campaign, has resigned just as the
agency is about to mail controversial AIDS brochures to 107 million
households across the nation, a spokeswoman said today.
   Ms. Van Ness, director of the CDC's National AIDS Information
and Education Program, said she will leave the agency June 3 to
become project director of a Ford Foundation plan to funnel funds
into community AIDS prevention and social service programs.
   Ms. Van Ness resigned a week ago Saturday, three days before the
government unveiled the brochure it plans to send to every American
household, according to today's editions of The Atlanta
Constitution. The brochures are scheduled to be mailed beginning
May 26.
   She told the newspaper she was working 90 hour weeks and was
leaving the AIDS information program ``partly to find some balance
in my life.''
   The agency made no public announcement of Ms. Van Ness'
departure, but CDC spokeswoman Gayle Lloyd said today there was no
attempt to keep it secret. The CDC does not routinely announce
staff resignations, she said.
   Ms. Van Ness was out of town and could not be reached today for
comment on the reason for her resignation.
   ``My understanding is she was made an offer too good to
refuse,'' Ms. Lloyd said. ``I don't know of any dissatisfaction she
had about the pamphlet.''
   An assistant, Laurie Sherman, also will leave the agency June
30, to return to California and work on various projects, said Ann
Sims, a CDC spokeswoman. Ms. Sims said she did not know why Ms.
Sherman was leaving the AIDS program, and Ms. Sherman could not be
reached for comment.
   Dr. Gary Noble, the CDC's deputy director for AIDS activities
and Ms. Van Ness' supervisor, was out of the country and could not
be reached for comment.
   Ms. Van Ness said the job change will provide relief from the
constant pressure, unending travel and ``90-hour weeks'' of the
AIDS education effort.
   ``For me it is partly an opportunity to find some balance in my
life, to work at a pace that will allow me to have more of a
personal life. No matter what some people say about government, we
work real long hours, really hard,'' she said.
   Ms. Van Ness joined the CDC on April 19, 1987, after serving as
executive director of AIDS Project Los Angeles, an AIDS service
agency. Before that she served on the project's board of directors
while working for a variety of family planning groups.
   At the CDC, Ms. Van Ness was put in charge of plans for the
first national direct mail campaign sponsored by the federal
government.
   The campaign got off to a rocky start. Secretary of Education
William Bennett and officials on the president's Domestic Policy
Council initially opposed spending the $20 million allocated by
Congress on brochures that would carry explicit information about
AIDS directly to American households.
</TEXT>
