<1ST_LINE>r w PM-VietnamWomen     05-11 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam Women,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs Nurse's Statue at Viet Memorial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill authorizing a statue of an Army nurse
at the Vietnam Veterans Memorial was approved by the Senate Energy
and Commerce Committee today over objections that it might
encourage other groups to demand similar sculptures.
   The committee passed the measure, which has 63 sponsors, on a
voice vote and sent it to the Senate floor after the lone
dissenter, Sen. Daniel Evans, R-Wash., protested what he called a
threat to the artistic integrity of the memorial.
   The bill, however, contained an amendment by Sen. Dale Bumpers,
D-Ark., that strengthens a declaration that Congress would not
allow any other statues to be placed at the memorial if the bronze
sculpture of an Army women's sculpture is approved.
   ``This will be the last one,'' said Sen. Bennett Johnston,
D-La., the committe chairman. ``But the last for how long?''
retorted Evans, who took pains to stress that his opposition had
nothing to do with his respect for American women.
   The proposal for a new statue honoring the 10,000 women who
served in the Vietnam conflict was introduced by Senate Majority
Whip Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn.
   At a committee hearing last February, the proposal was applauded
by veterans' groups but criticized by Robert W. Doubek, former
executive director of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund, who said
the woman's statue would ``destroy the symbolism and aesthetics of
the memorial.''
   Doubek said the National Park Service already had received
demands for statues honoring others who had served in Vietnam,
including native Americans and even scout dogs.
   The memorial, situated on the Mall near the Lincoln Memorial,
features a long black granite slab bearing the names of 58,156
Vietnam War dead, including eight uniformed nurses.
   Two years after the memorial was dedicated in 1982, a
controversial statue of three battle-weary infantrymen and a
60-foot flagpole were erected on the 2.2-acre site.
   The proposed addition to the Vietnam memorial, the most popular
tourist attraction among national monuments in the capital, has
been endorsed by the Interior Department but rejected by the
Commission of Fine Arts and the National Capital Planning
Commission.
   The approval of all three agencies in required before any new
memorial is built on federal parkland in Washington.
</TEXT>
