<DOCNO> AP880511-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Boys'Home-Raid     05-11 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boys' Home-Raid,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Authorities Raid Unlicensed Boys' Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities launched a surprise
inspection at an unlicensed home for boys today, taking away one
youth and issuing citations to 19 men who locked arms to hinder
officials from entering.
   Authorities snapped a padlocked gate and broke through the human
chain shortly after 6 a.m. to begin inspecting birth certificates
of children at the facility run by the Rev. W.N. Otwell.
   The inspection involved the state attorney general's office, the
Department of Human Services, Department of Public Safety and the
Texas Rangers.
   Otwell and state Attorney General Jim Mattox have disagreed for
two years about whether the facility should be licensed by the
state, and Otwell at one time agreed to close the facility.
   The facility is a combination home for troubled boys, a
church-run school and preschool. It has about 25 boys and 10
toddlers and pre-schoolers, said church secretary Deborah Anderson.
   A state district judge ruled April 12 that state officials could
inspect the facility in the Community Baptist Church compound at
any time and remove children found there without a relative or
guardian.
   ``They played it low-key. They said they didn't want a
confrontation,'' said Rocky Otwell, the reverend's son, of today's
multi-agency inspection.
   Ron Dusek, a spokesman for the attorney general, said a
17-year-old youth lacking guardianship papers was removed from the
facility and taken to a Department of Human Services emergency
shelter, and that 19 men were cited for preventing execution of
civil process.
   In March 1986, a state district judge in Austin ordered Otwell
to close the home, but in November 1987 suspended $97,000 in fines
after the minister promised he would keep the home closed unless
the state passed a law exempting church homes from licensing. The
state has never done so.
   Otwell reopened the facility this spring in mobile homes, vowing
to renew his fight over licensing.
   ``If they come to shut us down, we'll just pick her up and sail
her on down the road,'' said Otwell, who has previously contended
that the requirement that he seek a state license violated the
constitutional separation of church and state.
   Parents of several of the 25 students attending the school have
been staying at the compound in past weeks anticipating an
inspection, said Ms. Anderson.
   Authorities herded everyone into the school auditorium, asked to
see children's birth certificates and released them when parents
showed documents, she said.
   Rocky Otwell, interviewed by telephone, said his father was too
busy to comment on the incident.
   ``He's upset, but there's not visibly any angry words
exchanged,'' said Ms. Anderson.
</TEXT>
