<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0507,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Meets Thousands of Jobless and Poor in Mining Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with pope addressing miners and
peasants, meeting in Paraguay canceled. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COCHABAMBA, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today promised tens
of thousands of jobless miners and dirt-poor peasants the church
would help them pursue a society of love, solidarity and justice.
   In a one-hour morning visit to the hard-hit mining city of
Oruro, the pontiff said he was aware of the crisis in Bolivia's tin
mining industry.
   In Asuncion, Paraguay, meanwhile, the government of President
Gen. Alfredo Stroessner canceled a scheduled meeting between John
Paul and a group of Paraguayans that included opposition leaders.
Authorities cited ``security reasons.''
   The pontiff arrived in Uruguay on Friday for a 13-day tour of
four South American nations. He is to leave Bolivia Saturday for
Peru and is scheduled to arrive in Paraguay on Monday.
   ``The deep mines that years ago were the great source of
national wealth ... are now only mute witnesses to the so many
lives consumed silently there,'' the pope told the miners.
   ``I come with a message of hope, which does not mean passivity
in the face of misery that each day becomes more evident, but
instead is an obligation to construct a new society founded in
love, solidarity and justice.''
   The pope spoke from a tall platform that gave him a clear view
of the entrance to Oruro's state-run San Jose mine, from which most
workers have been laid off in a government austerity program.
   An umbrella held by an aide sheltered the pontiff from the
intense sun of Bolivia's wind-swept altiplano, or high plain. Oruro
is 12,160 feet above sea level.
   Local mining union leader Victor Lopez told the pope: ``Today
you have not heard the call of our work sirens, because the mines
are empty, and in our mining camps you hear only the wail of
children, because they cannot lift bread to their mouths.''
   A rural farmer also spoke to John Paul: ``We peasants suffer a
lot. Treated very badly, we suffer for our produce. Prices are not
good. We are cheated.''
   Unemployment in Oruro, a city of 132,000, is running at easily
twice the national average of 22 percent. It is considered the
center of misery in Bolivia, itself South America's poorest country.
   The collapse of world tin prices prompted Bolivia's conservative
government to shut down 14 of 21 state-run mines, leaving 21,500 of
27,000 miners out of work.
   The pope was to return from Oruro to Cochabamba, where he spent
Tuesday night in a monastery. He had several events planned for
this afternoon in Cochabamba, including a mass and an encounter
with the country's youth.
   Cochabamba is the gateway to the country's principal
coca-growing region and a center for cocaine trafficking. It also
is plagued by a growing problem with local drug consumption,
especially among the young and poor.
   In La Paz, the pope reaffirmed the importance the Roman Catholic
Church places on traditional values and criticized a Bolivian
Indian custom of concubinage.
   The meeting in Asuncion was scheduled to bring together diverse
members of the Paraguayan civilian sector, including leaders of
opposition parties that are not recognized by the government.
   The government had criticized the invitation of opposition
politicians to the meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
