<DOCNO> AP880511-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs 2ndLd-Writethru   05-11 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0555,0732</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five More Killed In Fighting At Golden Temple</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with 2 more bodies seen, quotes from
police officer vowing to drive out militants, chief priest
conferring with officials. No pickup
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces exchanged gunfire today
with Sikh extremists holed up inside the Golden Temple, and police
said witnesses had seen the bodies of five radicals inside the
complex.
   Electricity and water were cut off to the temple, Sikhism's
holiest shrine, on Tuesday after more than 800 pilgrims were
evacuated, according to security sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Heavy firing was reported early today between an estimated 100
extremists and about 2,500 police and paramilitary forces
surrounding the walled complex, which covers about five city blocks.
   A.A. Siddiqui, deputy inspector general of police, said at least
10 people have been killed and 10 injured since the violence began
Monday.
   He said there were reports that five bodies of Sikh radicals
were inside the temple but there was no way for police to verify
them.
   Police earlier reported that three bodies, believed to be Sikh
militants, were seen at daybreak on the ground outside the temple
complex.
   A. Hakeem, a paramilitary police commander, said it could not be
determined if the men had fallen from the temple rooftop or killed
while attempting to sneak in or out of the shrine.
   Siddiqui said his men had orders to fire on anyone moving inside
the shrine. He said that his troops could see entrances to food
stores and an ammunitions dump inside the shrine and were
preventing militants from getting to them.
   ``We will keep this up for a least a few more days,'' Siddiqui
said. ``Either the militants will be forced to surrender or will be
eliminated.''
   He added, ``We have no plans to enter the temple at this time.''
   The temple's head priest, Jasbir Singh Rode, was out of the
temple for a speaking engagement on Monday and has not been allowed
to return. He told reporters he asked authorities Tuesday for
permission to return but was denied.
   He was conferring with Indian officials today on ways to resolve
the confrontation, said Amritsar Police Supterindent Baldev Singh
said.
   Meanwhile, a curfew imposed three days ago remained in place in
most parts of Amritsar's old, walled sector.
   Elsewhere in Punjab state, two men were killed by Sikh gunmen
early today in the central Jalandhar district, the United News of
India reported. The latest slaying raised to more than 940 the
number of deaths blamed on the extremists this year.
   Since 1982, militant Sikhs have been waging a guerrilla war for
an independent homeland for their minority sect in the northern
state. Their attacks have increased in recent months, despite the
federal government's decision a year ago to take direct control of
security in the state.
   Although a majority in Punjab, Sikhs comprise just 2 percent of
India's 800 million people. The Sikhs claim they are discriminated
against by Hindus, who make up 82 percent of the nationwide
population.
   The temple siege began after at least five people were killed
and 10 hurt in a gunbattle Monday between Sikhs inside the complex
and security forces.
   The Golden Temple has become the main stronghold of Sikh
separatists, and an estimated 100 were believed holed up in and
around the shrine.
   The complex includes offices, living quarters, hostels for
pilgrims, dining halls and kitchens. The temple itself is
surrounded by a pool and reached by a single walkway.
   The security forces, beefed up after the initial outbreak of
fire, were given orders on Tuesday to shoot anyone attempting to
leave the shrine.
   Much of their gunfire on Tuesday afternoon was directed at a
watch tower overlooking the temple's main entrance.
   In June 1984, the Indian army carried out a raid to drive
militants from the Golden Temple and more than 1,200 people were
killed. Five months later, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was
assassinated by two Sikh bodguards in revenge.
   In New Delhi, P. Chidambaram, minister of state for home
affairs, told Parliament today that ``other forces'' were being
moved to Amritsar to deal with the situation, the United News of
India reported. He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
