<DOCNO> AP880511-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SpacePlatforms     05-11 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Platforms,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Science Academy Urges Robot Research and Manufacturing Facility in
Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Academy of Sciences has come down
on the side of those who advocate that NASA establish a robot
research and manufacturing facility in space to fill the time until
a space station is in orbit.
   ``We add our voice to the growing chorus of those urging NASA's
development of a mixed fleet of craft for access to space using
ELVs (expendable launch vehicles) for launching unmanned experiment
packages and the shuttle for those that require human presence,''
the academy said in a report Tuesday.
   It urged the National Aeronautics and Space Administration to
develop methods for keeping the shuttle in orbit for longer periods
of time than has been the case and to develop ``free-flier''
platforms.
   The Reagan administration wants the space agency to encourage
private development of space by agreeing to lease 70 percent of a
robot factory, which would be put into orbit by the space shuttle.
Such a scheme would cost $140 million a year and require astronaut
visits every three months for servicing.
   Congressional committees have balked at the idea, viewing it as
a move to deprive the space station program of funds, thus killing
it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
