<DOCNO> AP880511-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FreeDrugs     05-11 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Free Drugs,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Doctors Sign Up For Free Heart Medicine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 12,000 doctors have joined a pharmaceutical
company program that gives free heart medicine to needy patients
since the program was expanded five weeks ago, a company spokesman
said.
   Under the program, G.D. Searle & Co. issues certificates to
participating doctors, clinics and hospitals for heart medicine.
Patients obtain the certificate and prescription from their
doctors, then give them to pharmacists, who mail the certificate to
Searle for reimbursement.
   ``We are satisfied the program is a success,'' Searle spokesman
Bill Vaughn said by telephone Tuesday from Searle's corporate
headquarters in suburban Skokie.
   During a 14-month pilot program that ended in April, Searle
distributed two kinds of high-blood pressure medication to 20,000
patients. On April 6, the company announced it would expand the
giveaway to all seven of its heart medicines.
   Other drug companies have similar programs, but Searle's is more
extensive, said Judee Shuler, a spokeswoman for the Pharmaceutical
Manufacturers Association in Washington, D.C.
   The value of the pilot program was put at $9 million by Searle,
Vaughn said.
   Vaughn said the program is available to clinics nationwide and
that there is no time or money limit. ``These are life-time drugs.
You wouldn't want to put someone on a drug that he is going to need
all his life, then pull the plug on it later,'' he said.
   The drug giveaway is for people with no insurance or other
assistance, and annual incomes of $8,000 or less for a family of
one or two and $11,000 for larger families.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--RefineryBlast     05-11 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Refinery Blast,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Victim Of Refinery Blast Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORCO, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seventh and last victim of the Shell Oil
Co. refinery explosion here was found in the burnt rubble of the
plant after six days of searching, company officials said today.
   The body identified Tuesday night was that of Bill Coles, 27, of
LaPlace, Shell Oil spokesman Bill Gibson said.
   Seven Shell workers were killed and 42 other people were injured
Thursday when the gasoline-refining unit exploded and caught fire
before dawn. At least 250 homes in Norco were heavily damaged and
windows were broken up to 20 miles away in New Orleans.
   Two men remained hospitalized: Richard Hodges, 34, of Norco in
critical condition at West Jefferson Hospital and John Violette,
43, of LaPlace in stable condition at River Parishes Hospital.
   The cause of the blast has not been determined, Gibson said.
   ``The main thing going on is the investigation of the cause,''
he said. A team of Shell specialists and federal Occupational
Safety and Hazard Administration investigators are examining the
site today, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Trade 1stLd-Writethru a0454 05-11 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,680</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats rallied on Capitol Hill today and
vowed to fight President Reagan from now until November if he makes
good on his threat to veto the 1,000-page trade bill.
   ``If you decide to pull out that pen, Mr. President, we will
have to override that veto and we have the votes to do it,'' Rep.
Tony Coelho, D-Calif., told listeners gathered at the steps of the
Democratic National Committee.
   It remained unclear, however, where supporters of the measure
would find enough support in the Senate to override a presidential
veto. The bill fell three votes short of what would be needed.
``We'll consult the stars,'' Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said,
drawing a laugh from the crowd.
   Several hundred supporters including congressmen, their aides
and labor officials spilled into the street as party leaders urged
Reagan to relent and sign the measure. It was the final show of
political muscle before sending the measure to Reagan's desk.
   Absent from the ceremony, however, was Rep. Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., the chairman of the House-Senate conference committee that
fashioned the legislation. In reply to a question, Rep. Beryl
Anthony, D-Ark., said Rostenkowski may have had a scheduling
conflict.
   There have been recurrent reports, however, of friction between
Rostenkowski and House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, over provisions
of the measure. At the rally, Wright introduced Majority Leader
Thomas Foley, D-Wash., as ``the architect'' of the bill.
   The ornate Statuary Hall next to the House chamber was chosen as
the site for ceremonies in which Wright was signing the bill and
sending it on to Reagan. Officials of labor unions and religious
groups are among the invitees.
   Republicans are expected to be mainly absent from the
festivities, aimed at pressuring Reagan to drop his veto threat and
sign the bill after all.
   Reagan has been critical of the bill's curbs on Alaska oil
exports and its provision requiring companies with 100 employees or
more to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale
layoffs.
   Meanwhile, Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin told a manufacturers'
association the Reagan administration recognized the popularity of
the plant notification provision.
   ``We've gotten together _ you and us and everyone whose been
trying to `fight' the notification (provision) _ a real political
problem,'' she told the National Association of Manufacturers.
   ``The polls have indicated that, from the people I've talked to,
62 percent of the people think that plant notification is the right
way to go. Another 13 percent think it should be much more
stringent,'' she said.
   The major provisions of the bill have hardly figured in the
debate in recent weeks. They would streamline the system under
which the United States imposes import restrictions and takes other
steps to aid endangered U.S. industries and retaliate against
international trade violations.
   But there are numerous other provisions ranging from
agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil
companies.
   Reagan has been saying the Alaska provisions violate the
Constitution by discriminating against that state's ports while the
plant-closings feature would dull rather than sharpen the nation's
edge in global markets.
   Supporters of the plant-closings provision call it a humane and
decent way to treat employees and their families. But there are
only a handful of supporters for the Alaska provisions, which
Democratic leaders have been trying in vain to erase from the
legislation.
   ``I had hoped that if these offending provisions had been
eliminated the president would have had one less reason for vetoing
this bill,'' Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said
Tuesday.
   The remark appeared to mark the end of efforts to erase the
provisions.
   The bill won final passage on April 27 but has been becalmed on
Capitol Hill while leaders sought to do some after-the-fact custom
tailoring.
   The House last week approved a resolution that would have
instructed a congressional employee to call the enrolling clerk to
smooth out any minor wrinkles in the bill _ and erase the Alaska
provisions while he was at it.
   To bring up the resolution in the Senate, however, Byrd needed
unanimous consent and was unable to obtain it Tuesday when he
sought to do so.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JoyceBrown     05-11 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Joyce Brown,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Woman Who Battled Koch Admitted to Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was at the center of a controversy
over the homeless when she was hospitalized against her will was in
stable condition today after apparently suffering seizures,
authorities said.
   Joyce Brown was admitted to St. Clare's Hospital on Tuesday
after being brought there by ambulance, according to a hospital
statement. Her illness had not been diagnosed.
   Ms. Brown, whose streee Boggs, was the central
figure in a fight between civil liberties advocates and Mayor
Edward I. Koch over the constitutionality of a program to remove
mentally ill homeless people from the streets.
   St name was Billihe was ordered released after she objected to being
treated
against her will last October.
   ``Joyce Brown is resting comfortably at St. Clare's Hospital,
where she was admitted yesterday for observation,'' said hospital
spokeswoman Virginia Stuart. ``She is undergoing medical
evaluation, and her condition remains stable.''
   Koch said Tuesday, ``Obviously everyone will be very saddened by
any medical problem she has. I hope that she's getting good medical
care and I wish her the best.''
   New York Civil Liberties Union lawyer Rob Levy said Ms. Brown
``basically wasn't feeling good'' and was taken to the hospital
from her room at the Traveler's Hotel.
   Ms. Brown had been living on a sidewalk grate in Manhatuding congressmen,
