<HEAD>UNDATED: legal liabilities.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 6
   The News Tribune, Woodbridge, N.J., on amnesty for illegal
aliens:
   Were we dreaming? Did the wealthiest nation on the planet just
open its doors to about 2 million people who have lived illegally
within its borders for the past six years?
   And is it prepared to say all is forgiven and soon you can
achieve full citizenship? ...
   We had every right to gather up illegals and give them the boot
_ a remedy that may well have been preferred by those Americans
prejudiced against the immigrants, many of whom are dark skinned.
...
   We are a nation of immigrants. With the sad exception of slaves,
our kin arrived here seeking what the best nation in the world had
to offer.
   We have not slammed the door. This unprecedented amnesty program
gives us additional reason to be proud.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 6
   The Worthington (Minn.) Daily Globe on Vice President George
Bush:
   Vice President George Bush was telling reporters (last)
Wednesday he sometimes doesn't speak up at presidential Cabinet
meetings because he fears one day he may be mentioned in a ``kiss
and tell'' book.
   Other times, Bush said, he doesn't speak up ``because I don't
want the president to have to be choosing between his vice
president and the other members of the Cabinet.''
   Bush offered several reasons for not having expressed opinions
through the past eight years.
   But what kind of president would George Bush make if he is loath
to speak up even as vice president because someone, someday might
quote something he said?
   Anyone who aspires to the White House must be willing to speak
out and to express himself, must be willing even to risk
embarrassment.
   We must wonder what kind of president George Bush would be when
he is afraid, even now, to state his views at Cabinet meetings
because his words might sometime be included in someone's book.
  
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 4
   The Honolulu Advertiser on the Reagans' interest in astrology:
   Like other personal beliefs or superstitions, (astrology) may or
may not help, but isn't likely to hurt much _ including in the
White House, where Reagan can use all the help he can get.
   What should hurt Reagan is Regan, Speakes and other aides
writing books about him.
   Maybe an astrologer or somebody else should have warned him
about people like that.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 7
   The Augusta (Ga.) Chronicle, Augusta Herald on Pete Rose's
suspension:
   A powerful message was sent to professional baseball managers
and players in the 30-day suspension of Cincinnatti Reds' Manager
Pete Rose for shoving umpire Dave Pallone in a game with the New
York Mets.
   Although Pallone showed poor judgment in delaying his call some
four seconds, thus infuriating Rose, National League President Bart
Giamatti is warning the league that pushing an umpire will not be
tolerated for any reason. ...
   But the chief reason Rose was rapped so harshly ... is because
Reds fans became unruly, throwing objects at Met players and
Pallone. ...
   Holding Rose, or any other manager, responsbile for the actions
of those in attendance doesn't make sense. ...
   The most feasible solution would be to make a team forfeit a
game if crowd control becomes a problem. And forfeit another if the
crowd still won't calm down.
   Two or three forfeits in a row should bring the rowdies to their
senses.
