<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cyprus-Explosion 6thLd-Writethru a0676 05-11 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyprus-Explosion, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0676,0817</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills Three People Near Israeli Embassy In Cyprus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 3, `A caller...' to CORRECT where NBC received call
claiming bombing responsibility and change attribution. PICKS UP
graf 4 `Abu Nidal...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car packed with explosives blew up
today on a bridge minutes after police had chased it away from the
Israeli Embassy, authorities said. Three people were killed and 15
wounded.
   The semi-official Cyprus News Agency said an Arab man who owned
the car was arrested while trying to run away from the scene.
   A caller claiming to represent terrorist Abu Nidal's group told
NBC News this morning at a bureau in the Middle East that Abu
Nidal's organization was responsible for the bombing. Bill
McAndrew, NBC's manager of news information, quoted the caller as
saying it was the first of future attacks against Israeli targets.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabry al-Banna, has been accused
by Israeli, Arab and Western intelligence agencies of directing
scores of terrorist attacks. They include simultaneous assaults at
Rome and Vienna airports Dec. 27, 1985, that killed 20 people.
   His group, Fatah-Revolutionary Council, broke in 1976 with
Fatah, the mainstream guerrilla faction led by Palestine Liberation
Organization chief Yasser Arafat.
   Israeli Ambassador Aharon Lopez said the Israeli Embassy was a
possible target of today's bombing. Authorities said windows were
shattered in the building but no one there was injured.
   The Mitsubishi Pajero exploded and disintegrated in the middle
of the bridge on a main highway, less than 200 yards from the
embassy. The explosion set four other vehicles on the bridge ablaze.
   A police statement said a briefcase containing a remote-control
detonating device was found about 200 yards from the site of the
blast. No further details were available.
   A police statement said the car's driver and a Greek Cypriot
woman who was in a car immediately behind were killed. Another
Greek Cypriot, Andreas Frangos, a retired diplomat, was in another
nearby car and died of his wounds in a hospital a few hours later.
   Fifteen other people were taken to Nicosia General Hospital with
various wounds, hospital officials said.
   The news agency said the arrested Arab, whom it did not name,
had arrived on the island on March 21.
   Later today, scores of policemen converged on a Nicosia
apartment building where the man lived and searched it.
   Police said the car with the bomb had a foreign visitor's
temporary Cyprus registration plates and twice tried to park
outside the four-story embassy in a narrow side street.
   Cypriot police guards told the driver parking was forbidden and
the car sped off toward the Grivas Avenue bridge. The explosion
came a minute later, the statement said.
   ``There must have been a lot of explosives packed in that car,''
Nicosia Police Chief Andreas Trifyllis told newsmen at the scene.
   Lopez told Israel army radio: ``We do not know yet who is
responsible. But it is certainly possible that the embassy was the
terrorists' target and that the car (bomb) exploded prematurely for
some reason.''
   Meanwhile, in Jerusalem, the Foreign Ministry condemned the
attempted bomb attack.
   ``The explosion, in the wake of which innocent Cypriots were
hurt, was another attempt to exploit the soil of Cyprus for
terrorist attacks against Israel,'' the ministry said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin called it another ``terror
attempt against Israel, Israelis, Israeli representation outside
the region. Terror has become part of our life.''
   However, Rabin said he would not describe the attack as an
escalation in the war between Arab guerrillas and Israel.
   On Monday, police arrested a Lebanese at Larnaca airport who was
carrying a silencer-equipped pistol and two full ammunition
magazines hidden in a radio-casette player.
   The arrested man, Hassan Moussa, 22, had just arrived on a
Middle East Airlines flight from Beirut and the pistol was
discovered during an X-ray check.
   Moussa was ordered in custody for eight days by a Larnaca court
on Tuesday, pending the completion of police investigations.
   Police prosecutor Andreas Charalambous told the court Moussa
admitted he had arrived in Cyprus ``to commit a crime,'' but did
not give more details.
   The bridge on Grivas Avenue is crossed by the main road from the
capital of this Mediterranean island to western and northwestern
Cyprus.
   In October 1984, a car bomb explosion damaged the multi-story
building housing the Israeli Embassy, which was then in a different
part of town. No one was injured.
   Responsibility for that attack was claimed by the mainstream
Fatah faction of the PLO.
   The PLO has accused Israel of killing Khalil Wazir, a top PLO
leader, in Tunis last month as well as killing three PLO officials
in a Cyprus car bombing last February.
</TEXT>
