<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Robertson-CBN     05-11 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson-CBN,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Says He Likely Will Return Soon To CBN</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson says his decision to leave the
ministry to run for president was right but he may return soon to
his ailing Christian Broadcasting Network, according to a newspaper
report today.
   Robertson left CBN and resigned his ordination as a Southern
Baptist minister in September 1987 to campaign full time for the
1988 Republican presidential nomination.
   At the White House today, Robertson endorsed Vice President
George Bush and told reporters that he will officially withdraw
from the race on Monday.
   Asked if he would run again in 1992 if Bush loses this fall,
Robertson replied, ``It's conceivable. It's not a certainty.''
   In his interview with The Virginian-Pilot and The Ledger-Star,
Robertson said of the television network he formerly led, ``I can't
abandon CBN. It's too important to me. I've got to do everything I
can to make sure that it's healthy.''
   Robertson told the newspaper he likely would return to CBN as
chief executive officer, the title his eldest son, Timothy, now
holds. The senior Robertson also said he would appear on the air,
probably as a news commentator.
   Asked when he might return, Robertson said, ``Very shortly. It's
not too long.''
   Robertson has lost badly to Bush and former candidate Bob Dole
in GOP contests nationwide. Meanwhile, CBN has lost viewers and
donors, laying off hundreds of workers.
   ``I assumed that I had built a very competent staff and that
they would be able to run CBN in my absence,'' Robertson told the
newspaper. ``I did not realize that my personal presence on `The
700 Club' was as important as it is to the audience.
   ``I was able to do news analysis and at the same talk about
spiritual things, and we've had a hard time getting a replacement
for that, so the audience has dropped dramatically in the last
year. That has, of course, impacted contributions.''
   Robertson said his return to the airwaves would not necessarily
spell a return to ``The 700 Club,'' CBN's flagship show and
mainstay of the past two decades.
   ``It may be time to look for other vehicles to talk to the
American public and the world public,'' Robertson said. ```The 700
Club' has been around since 1967 and that's 21 years. That's a long
time for any television program.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
