<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MultipleTransplant     05-11 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Multiple Transplant,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toddler Suffers Infection, Condition Deteriorates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's longest survivor of a five-organ
transplant was deteriorating today as her organs failed due to
serious infection, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Tabatha Foster, 3{, of Madisonville, Ky., was in very critical
condition late this morning at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh,
said the spokeswoman, Sue Cardillo.
   ``It's very bad,'' Ms. Cardillo said. ``She's beginning to show
signs of multiple organ failure, and her heart ... is being
supported by medication.''
   Tabatha's condition fell Monday from serious to critical after
surgeons changed drainage tubes inserted last month to relieve a
buildup of bile in her transplanted liver, Ms. Cardillo said.
   Tabatha was connected to a breathing machine and was unconscious
and under sedation, Ms. Cardillo said.
   The medication that subdues the body's tendency to reject
transplanted organs left Tabatha susceptible to infection, Ms.
Cardillo said. Doctors did not know what caused Tabatha's
infection, which has entered her bloodstream, to flare.
   Tabatha received a new liver, small intestines, pancreas and
parts of a stomach and colon during experimental surgery that ended
Nov. 1.
   Similar procedures had been performed only twice before in the
world. Both patients died.
</TEXT>
