<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Uganda-AIDS     05-11 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uganda-AIDS,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ugandan Delegate Proposes Week of Sexual Abstinence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A debate on AIDS at a World Health Organization
conference took an unexpected turn Wednesday when a delegate of
Uganda proposed an international week of sexual abstinence to
increase public awareness of the disease.
   Dr. I. S. Okware, saying he was speaking on a ``light note,''
said that barring an accord on proclaiming such a week, the agency
might consider introducing it ``on a voluntary basis.'' Other
delegates reacted with laughter.
   According to the latest WHO statistics, Uganda had a total of
2,369 cases of AIDS registered by last October. It was the highest
number of all African nations and the third-highest rate worldwide,
after the United States and France.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a deadly
disease caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
