<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Brink'sTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0690 05-11 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brink's Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Convicted In 1981 Armored Truck Robberies That Left Four Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs, attorney plans appeal; picks up 7th graf
pvs, ``The jury also xxxxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury today convicted two admitted
revolutionaries of armed robbery, racketeering and murder in a
series of crimes that included two 1981 armored truck robberies
that left two guards and two police officers dead.
   The jury found Mutulu Shakur and Marilyn Jean Buck each guilty
on all eight counts. Both defendants face maximum sentences of life
in prison for the convictions of murder while committing robbery.
   The charges against Shakur, 37, and Ms. Buck, 40, included a
string of robberies and attempted armored truck robberies in New
York and Connecticut.
   Among the robberies was the $1.6 million holdup of a Brink's
truck in Rockland County, north of the city. A guard and two Nyack
police officers were killed in the bloody aftermath of the Oct. 20,
1981 robbery.
   The pair also were convicted of a June 1981 armored truck
robbery in the Bronx in which a Brink's guard was killed.
   One of Shakur's defense attorneys, Jesse Berman, said the
verdict would be appealed. Both Shakur and Ms. Buck remain jailed,
and U.S. District Judge Charles Haight did not set a sentencing
date.
   The bank robbery and racketeering convictions carry maximum
20-year sentences.
   The jury also found, by way of the racketeering conviction, that
Shakur and Ms. Buck played key roles in the 1979 prison escape of
black radical Joanne Chesimard.
   Chesimard, a Black Liberation Army leader serving a life
sentence for the murder of a New Jersey state trooper, escaped from
state prison at Clinton, N.J., and is believed to be living in Cuba.
   The defense had said that Shakur, who is black, and Ms. Buck,
who is white, are revolutionaries who were put on trial because of
their political beliefs.
   Both Shakur and Ms. Buck were fugitives during an earlier trial
of several defendants in the Brink's case.
   Shakur, who has said he considers himself a ``prisoner of war,''
was on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted List until he was captured in Los
Angeles last year.
   Ms. Buck, a fugitive since 1977 when she escaped from a West
Virginia prison, was captured in 1985 with a loaded revolver. She
was convicted and sentenced to five years in prison on a weapons
charge.
   The jury reached its verdict on the seventh day of
deliberations. The trial began with opening arguments Nov. 30, 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
