<DOCNO> AP880511-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-VietnamWomen     05-11 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam Women,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Sculpture of Woman at Vietnam Memorial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation authorizing a bronze statue of a
female Army nurse at the Vietnam Veterans Memorial was approved by
a Senate committee Wednesday over a dissenter's protest that the
memorial might become a sculpture garden for special interest
groups.
   Before the bill was passed by the Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee by voice vote and sent to the Senate floor, it
was amended to stress that Congress would not approve any further
additions to the memorial once a woman's statue is built.
   But Sen. Daniel J. Evans, R-Wash., was not satisfied. He noted
that a statue of three Vietnam infantrymen and a 60-foot flagpole
already have been erected on the 2.2-acre memorial site near the
Lincoln Memorial, and he predicted there would be further demands
to recognize others who served in Vietnam.
   Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., the committee chairman, said the
bill specifies that ``this will be the last.''
   ``But the last for how long?'' Evans retorted.
   Evans, alone among 17 committee members in opposing the bill,
said that ``adding bits and pieces to this stark and dramatic
memorial'' would destroy its artistic integrity. He made clear that
his dissenting vote had nothing to do with his respect for American
women.
   The politically popular measure, introduced by Sens. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., and David Durenberger, R-Minn., with 63
sponsors, has been endorsed by the Interior Department.
   But it is opposed by the Commission of Fine Arts and the
National Capital Planning Commission, whose approval also is
required before any new monuments can be built on federal parkland
in the capital.
   At a committee hearing last February, the bill was applauded by
veterans' organizations but criticized by Maya Lin, the architect
who designed the Vietnam Veterans Memorial.
   ``I cannot see where it will all end,'' she said. ``What is to
stop someone from trying to add a female statue to the Iwo Jima
Memorial?''
   She and J. Carter Brown, chairman of the fine arts commission,
said it might be more appropriate to build a separate monument to
all American women who have served in the armed forces since World
War II. Congress authorized such a monument in 1986.
   Robert W. Doubek, former executive director of the Vietnam
Veterans Memorial Fund, warned that to add a woman's statue would
``open a Pandora's box of competing and proliferating statuary to
the ephemeral goal of literally depicting every possible
subcategory'' that served in Vietnam.
   Doubek said the National Park Service already had received
requests for statues honoring native Americans and scout dogs at
the Vietnam memorial.
   The memorial's black granite slab bears the names of more than
58,000 Vietnam War dead, including eight uniformed nurses.
   Built with $11 million in private funds, the memorial has become
the most popular tourist attraction of any national monument in
Washington. The memorial, which was dedicated in 1982, has
attracted an estimated 20 million visitors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
