<2ND_LINE>PM-Trip Trouble, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,420</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, The 185, to CORRECT airline to American
sted United.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students from a California junior high got a
lesson from the school of hard knocks when the agency that arranged
their East Coast tour ran out of money midway through the trip,
leaving them without cash for food, lodging or airplane tickets
home.
   The 185 youth from Emerald Junior High School in El Cajon were
able to continue their planned itinerary today, heading for
Philadelphia in buses, only after their school board agreed to pick
up costs for the trip and American Airlines donated plane tickets
home.
   The youths' 38 teachers and parent chaperones pooled their cash
Tuesday to stay the night at a lower-cost Washington hotel after
the travel agency that arranged the pre-paid tour ``just ran out of
money,'' said principal Marge Dean, trying to oversee the situation
from California.
   ``I don't know what the travel agency did with the money but
it's gone,'' she said today.
   She said the school board voted Tuesday night to pick up
remaining costs for the trip, estimated at $47,000, and would ``ask
the parents to have some kind of fundraising activity ... they'll
probably have to have car washes'' to help defray the costs.
   ``The kids have been wonderful, a little bit teary-eyed and
concerned, but now that they know that they can continue the trip,
they're wonderful,'' she said.
   Ms. Dean said no one at East@West Travel and Tours of San Diego
had been available to comment since the agency announced Tuesday
the trip was being cancelled due to a lack of money. Telephones at
the agency went unanswered early today.
   Tour director Steve Ewalt, an employee of the travel agency who
said he was sticking with the students even though he wasn't
getting paid, said he'd directed hundreds of tours for the company
but ``this time we could sense that it was a little different.''
   ``We just found that the money was drying up,'' he said. ``When
it stops right in the middle, there's really nothing we can do
about it.''
   He said he didn't know what had happened back at the travel
agency, but that continuing the tour for the students was the top
priority for now.
   ``The kids I don't think have experienced any of the real
heartache that some of us have,'' he said.
   Ewalt said the students boarded buses for Philadelphia early
today and would spend the end of the week in New York before
heading home on Saturday.
   ``I'm just making calls letting everyone know we're still
coming,'' Ewalt said this morning prior to leaving Washington.
   The students began their East Coast tour Friday in Williamsburg,
Va., then toured Thomas Jefferson's home, Monticello, and arrived
in Washington over the weekend.
</TEXT>
