<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatherArrested     05-11 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Father Arrested,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Arrested After Speeding To Get Pregnant Wife To Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 3-day-old Brandie Nicole Kristoff
grows up, she'll have a fantastic story to tell about the day she
was born.
   No doubt she'll tell how dad was arrested, handcuffed and taken
to the police station for driving recklessly when he drove her
mother to the hospital.
   ``It's not funny to him at this point,'' Richard Kristoff's
wife, Jennifer, said Tuesday from Memorial Hospital of Carbondale.
``He'll look back at it and laugh _ maybe later.''
   At 5:45 a.m. Monday, Mrs. Kristoff started having labor
contractions.
   Mrs. Kristoff, 24, thought they had plenty of time for the
25-mile trip to the hospital. But, she said, every time she had a
contraction, she yelled a little louder _ and her husband drove a
little faster.
   ``Sure, I was driving faster than normal. But what else could I
do?'' Kristoff, 26, said Monday.
   When the labor pains became more frequent, Kristoff said his
wife ``was screaming and, at one point, grabbing my hair as I was
driving. I was afraid she was going to have the baby right there,''
he said.
   Police Chief Ed Hogan said Wednesday the couple was about a
half-mile from the hospital when police noticed their car.
Kristoff, they said, was driving about 50 mph, or 25 miles over the
speed limit.
   Kristoff cut off another driver while making a turn and nearly
plowed into the back of a truck, police said.
   Shortly after the couple arrived at the hospital, Officer Gerald
Edwards asked Kristoff for his license. After admitting that he
speeded, police said, Kristoff told Edwards to take his license as
bond and let him go inside.
   Kristoff acknowledged he then ``got smart'' with the officer. He
said he started to walk away but didn't get far. Edwards grabbed
him, handcuffed him and took him to the station.
   Shortly before 7 a.m. _ a little more than an hour after he and
his wife started their trip _ Kristoff was released; a police
officer drove him back to the hospital. Kristoff ran into the
delivery room just as 5-pound, 4-ounce Brandie Nicole was born.
   Edwards said ``his intentions from the very first were to write
a warning,'' said Sgt. John Knapp. ``But the guy talked himself
into a ticket, calling him all sorts of vile names.''
   Knapp said police decided a written warning was sufficient.
   After seeing his healthy daughter, Kristoff said, his anger
subsided.
   ``At least, after all of this,'' Kristoff said, ``Brandie will
have a funny story to tell about being born.''
</TEXT>
