<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CitrusBan     05-11 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Citrus Ban,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Denies Texas Ban On Florida Citrus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today ruled that the
U.S. Department of Agriculture did nothing wrong when it lifted a
ban on shipments of Florida citrus to other citrus-producing areas.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela's ruling was in response to a
suit filed by the state of Texas in an effort to keep Florida fruit
out of the state.
   The USDA on Feb. 11 lifted a 3{-year ban on shipments of fresh
Florida citrus into Texas and other citrus-producing areas. The
Florida fruit was quarantined after an outbreak of citrus canker in
parts of Florida in the fall of 1984.
   Officials of the Texas attorney general's office and state
agriculture department filed suit on March 9, contending that the
USDA violated its own rules in lifting the ban.
   ``With all the information put before me, I am satisfied'' that
the USDA followed the law in promulgating the rule, Vela said today.
   Texas officials sought to have the quarantine reinstated and
claimed the USDA did not allow adequate time for comment when it
lifted the ban.
   But Vela said the new protocol is so similar to one the USDA
proposed last fall that there had been plenty of time for comment.
</TEXT>
