<2ND_LINE>PM-Multiple Killings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0607,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killer Grinned As He Fired, Witnesses Testify</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with today's testimony,
transition. Pickup 7th graf ``According to police...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was wounded during a Christmas
rampage by a gunman who killed 16 people testified today that she
crawled along the floor and hid behind a counter after being shot
in the mouth.
   ``I thought to myself, there is nowhere else to go, so I stayed
quiet,'' Roberta Woolery, a market cashier, testified during the
trial of R. Gene Simmons, 47.
   Mrs. Woolery said identified Simmons as the gunman and said she
and Simmons had been co-workers at the market for 3{ years.
   Simmons, a retired Air Force master sergeant, is on trial in the
Dec. 28 deaths of former co-worker Kathy C. Kendrick, 24, and James
D. Chaffin, 33, in Russellville. Four people were wounded during
the shootings.
   Simmons is to be tried July 18 in the deaths of 14 relatives,
including his wife, children and grandchildren. The bodies were
found at his home near Dover after the shootings in Russellville.
Police said the 14 were killed during the Christmas holidays.
   Mrs. Woolery testified that she did not know how many shots were
fired because the incident happened so quickly and she could not
distinguish gunshots from the noise made by bottles and cans that a
customer threw at the assailant.
   On Tuesday, a witness testified that the gunman wore a ``horrid
grin'' as he aimed his revolver at office workers during the
rampage.
   The gunman stepped over the body of one of his victims, ``took a
stance and pointed the gun at me,'' said Juli Money, extending her
arms with hands clasped to show how the man held the gun.
   ``I screamed, `No!' and dived behind some boxes,'' she said.
``He was grinning. He had a horrid grin that looked like false
teeth and his eyes were wide open.''
   According to police, Simmons used two .22-caliber revolvers to
kill Miss Kendrick, who friends say rejected Simmons' amorous
attention, and Chaffin, who apparently was a chance victim. Police
said Simmons had a grudge against most of the people he is accused
of shooting.
   Chaffin was shot in the right eye at point-blank range as he
opened a door at Taylor Oil Co. after he and Ms. Money heard two
shots fired in the office area, Ms. Money said. The gunman had
already wounded the company president, Rusty Taylor.
   It was Chaffin's body, Ms. Money testified, that Simmons stepped
over before aiming at her.
   David Salyer, who was shot in the forehead, also said Simmons
fired with a grin on his face.
   Simmons, who had worked for Taylor and Salyer, then went to a
nearby law office where Miss Kendrick worked and stood in front of
her desk, according to another witness, Brenda Jones. Miss Kendrick
returned to her desk a short time later and said, ``Can I help
you?''
   Simmons had his hands in his pockets but jerked his right arm up
and started firing a pistol, Miss Jones said. ``He missed her at
first,'' she said. ``She just stood there. He kept shooting.
Finally, he hit her.''
   Prosecutor John Bynum said in his opening statement Tuesday that
Miss Kendrick, a legal secretary, was shot at least four times in
the head as she sat at her desk.
   About 60 spectators were present in Franklin County Circuit
Court, including relatives of some of Simmons' family members.
   Pat McNulty, 36, of Bryant, whose brother was among the dead
family members, said, ``We've got our grief to deal with and Gene
Simmons has got God to deal with.''
   Judge John Patterson replaced one juror with an alternate during
a closed hearing. The judge said someone reported that the replaced
juror said something derogatory about Simmons.
   The trial was moved here because of extensive pretrial publicity.
</TEXT>
