<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietRiotTrial     05-11 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Riot Trial,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins for First of 80 People Charged in Ethnic Riots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Azerbaijan metalworker went on trial for murder
Wednesday in connection with ethnic riots that killed at least 32
people in February, Pravda reported. He was the first of more than
80 people charged to stand trial.
   The Communist Party newspaper said the defendant, identified as
T. Ismailov, was accused of participating in the riots in the
Azerbaijan city of Sumgait and intentionally killing someone for
``hooligan motives.'' Ismailov is an employee of a pipe and tube
plant.
   Ethnic violence broke out Feb. 28 in Sumgait during a
territorial dispute between Azerbaijan and the neighboring republic
of Armenia. Armenians had demanded that Nagorno-Karabakh, an
Armenian-dominated region of Azerbaijan, be annexed to Armenia.
   Armenian activists said Armenians living in Sumgait, an
industrial city on the Caspian Sea about 20 miles of Baku, were
hunted down by bands of Azerbaijanis.
   Soviet media have said 26 ethnic Armenians and 6 Azeris were
killed. Officials said 200 people were injured.
   All those charged will be tried in Sumgait by a tribunal led by
Albert K. Klokov, a member of the Azerbaijan Supreme Court, Pravda
said. If convicted of murder, Ismailov could be sentenced to death
and shot by a firing squad.
   Pravda quoted Zulfi S. Gadzhiev, head of the Sumgait Communist
Party, as saying even petty crime has declined since the riots, but
effects of the violence remain.
   ``Many families that left the city during those bitter February
days have still not returned home,'' he said. ``We will be exact:
more than 1,200 jobs at factories and institutions are still
empty.''
   Gadzhiev said the jobs were being kept open because officials
expect the people who held them to return.
   The unrest caused a ``bleeding wound'' that made a rift between
Armenians and Azeris, Pravda said.
   It also declared that the trials will show ``who needed to sow
hostility between the two peoples,'' a possible reference to
official allegations of foreign involvement in the riots.
   Soviet media customarily accuse such Western media as the Voice
of America and Radio Liberty of trying to foment trouble among the
many Soviet ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
