<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Islam     05-11 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Islam,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Proposes to Make Islam State Religion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government introduced legislation
in Parliament on Wednesday to make Islam the state religion of
Bangladesh. The move sparked street protests and was denounced by
opposition parties and women's groups.
   ``Like the water lily is the state flower, Islam shall be the
state religion,'' Information Minister Mahbubur Rahman told
reporters before Prime Minister Maudud Ahmed introduced the bill in
the house.
   The bill was expected to pass easily because the ruling Jatiya
Party of President Hussain Muhammad Ershad holds 251 of the 300
seats.
   ``The government is trying to divide the nation in the name of
Islam,'' opposition member Shahjehan Siraj said. ``Government seems
to have some bad motives behind it.''
   Witnesses and opposition leaders said at least 50 people were
injured when more than 1,000 opposition supporters stoned six
government-owned buses in downtown Dhaka.
   Bangladesh's 105 million people are 85 percent Moslem, with
Christian, Hindu and Buddhist minorities. The country has had a
secular constitution since it won independence from Pakistan in
1971.
   Ershad told a religious gathering in March that ``the day-to-day
life of the nation must be guided by the tenets of Islam and the
ideals of Prophet Mohammed.''
   ``This law will curtail the activities of the fundamentalists,
who are gaining ground because of Islamic slogans,'' said a senior
leader in Ershad's Jatiya Party, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The constitutional amendment is the first major bill to come
before the Parliament, which was elected last March 3. Most
opposition parties boycotted that election, and only about half of
the nation's 48 million eligible voters cast ballots.
   Twenty-one opposition groups, which have been agitating since
last November for the ouster of Ershad, pledged to oppose any
attempts by the Parliament to change the constitution. These
parties, which have no seats in the house, contend Parliament does
not represent the people.
   But Ahmed promised that the bill would not be rushed to passage.
``There shall be enough time for the opposition to speak on it,''
he said.
   ``The government will seek public opinion on the legislation,''
he added.
   Several women's rights groups have already held demonstrations
against the idea of making Islam the state religion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
