<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SmartStart     05-11 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smart Start,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Groups Laud Bill Provide Quality Schooling for All 4-Year-Olds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent business group and the nation's
two major teachers unions on Wednesday endorsed a Senate bill aimed
at making high-quality nursery schooling available to all
4-year-olds.
   The so-called Smart Start program, proposed by Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., would provide money to supplement and strengthen
existing early childhood education programs run by schools,
community groups and others. States and communities would share the
cost.
   The bill reserves at least half the spaces in the program for
poor children. Better-off families would be charged on a sliding
scale. The Kennedy bill authorizes $500 million for the program in
its first year, $750 million in the second year and $1 billion in
its third year.
   ``We believe the time for this legislation has arrived,'' Albert
Shanker, president of the American Federation of Teachers, said in
testimony to the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee chaired
by Kennedy.
   Both Shanker and Mary Hatwood Futrell, president of the National
Education Association, said preschool programs receiving money
under the bill should not emulate kindergarten or grade school but
should help young children develop and learn as individuals.
   They also said the federal government should set high training
standards for preschool teachers in federally supported programs.
   Owen Butler, vice chairman of the Committee for Economic
Development, said the group of 250 academic and corporate trustees
views the Kennedy bill ``with considerable enthusiasm.''
   Butler, retired chairman of Proctor & Gamble Co., recommended
merging Smart Start with the existing $1 billion Head Start program
at the Department of Health and Human Services. ``It makes little
sense to have two programs,'' he said.
   Butler also said he was concerned about the federal government's
reliability in paying for the preschool programs. Under the bill,
states would have to put up 30 percent the first year; 40 percent
the second; and 50 percent thereafter.
   Butler said states should have to pay 50 percent right from the
start. ``History has shown that where the federal government takes
on too big a role and the federal funding is later reduced, many
programs die,'' he said in his testimony.
   The Committee for Economic Development was formed to study ways
to address pressing economic and social problems. Last fall the
group released a study saying the nation should concentrate on
helping poor children in their earliest months and years of life,
including prenatal care and enriched preschool education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
