<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--JoyceBrown     05-11 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Joyce Brown,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Billie Boggs' Undergoing Tests, Resting at Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joyce Brown, the homeless woman whose refusal to
voluntarily leave the street ignited a battle with the city over
the rights of the homeless, remained hospitalized Wednesday with an
unknown ailment.
   ``Joyce Brown is resting comfortably at St. Clare's Hospital,
where she was admitted yesterday for observation,'' hospital
spokeswoman Virginia Stuart said in a statement. ``She is
undergoing medical evaluation, and her condition remains stable.''
   Brown, who used the name Billie Boggs while living on the
street, possibly suffered seizures, authorities said. But Stuart
said her illness had not been diagnosed.
   Brown was the central figure in a fight between the civil
liberties groups and Mayor Edward I. Koch over the
constitutionality of a city program to remove mentally ill homeless
people from the streets during cold weather.
   Brown had been living on a sidewalk grate when she was picked up
last October and hospitalized for psychiatric treatment against her
will. She eventually won her release.
</TEXT>
