<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Cisneros-Plot 1stLd-Writethru a0660 05-11 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cisneros-Plot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arrested in Reported Assassination Plot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with prosecutor's news conference,
details, CORRECTS reference to Bullock as actual target; ADDS
byline; No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested a former
congressional candidate on charges that he tried to hire a hit man
to kill Mayor Henry Cisneros for $5,000, officials said today.
   Officials arrested Parker E. Abell on Tuesday and charged him
with solicitation of capital murder, said District Attorney Fred
Rodriguez.
   ``He was doing it to make a statement. He wanted to get
publicity,'' Rodriguez said.
   Rodriguez said Abell had mentioned other possible targets,
including State Comptroller Bob Bullock, but decided on Cisneros.
   ``Bullock's name was mentioned, ... but for whatever reasons,
whether it was that (Bullock) was out of town or not a big enough
name, he settled on Mayor Henry Cisneros. He wanted someone at the
local level, but with a national reputation,'' Rodriguez said.
   Rodriguez said he informed the mayor's office of the alleged
plot, but did not recommend more protection for the mayor.
   Abell sought the 23rd Congressional District seat in 1982 as a
Liberterian and told detectives he was now leader of a political
extremists' group, the American Patriots.
   Gary Johnson, Texas secretary of Libertarian Party, said today
that Abell is no longer a dues-paying member and is not on the
party mailing list.
   Rodriguez said the state's investigation began about a month ago
after Internal Revenue Service officials contacted his office
because an IRS undercover agent had talked to a man who wanted to
assassinate a public official.
   The IRS agent gave the man the name of an undercover officer who
worked for prosecutors. The two talked on the telephone, then in
person for the first time on Tuesday, Rodriguez said.
   ``He wanted a patriot to carry out the execution,'' Rodriguez
said. ``He was firm in his convictions and he wanted a hitman with
the same resolve and same philosophy.''
   All conversations with Abell were taped, Rodriguez said. He was
arrested at a supermarket pay phone Tuesday afternoon.
   Rodriguez said that in Abell's car officers found a .22-caliber
rifle with 12 live rounds and ``execution warrants'' with blanks to
fill in names of public officials.
   ``The above-named traitor or traitors are to be executed on
sight,'' read the warrants. ``Each accused has given public proof
of guilt beyond reasonable doubt that he or she is a traitor to the
people of the United States and the United States Constitution.''
   Abell allegedly solicited ``this (undercover) officer as a
shooter for himself and unknown associates,'' wrote John Veltkamp,
the undercover investigator for the Bexar County District
Attorney's office who posed as the hit man.
   The mayor said Tuesday that he never met Abell and does not
recall receiving threatening letters from him.
   ``We get threats on a regular basis _ not always with a price.
That's what makes this a little more serious,'' said Cisneros.
   Rodriguez said the investigation is continuing and that he would
oppose the suspect's being relased from jail.
   ``We got a dangerous man here. If he seeks out two hitmen he is
determining his resolve to do something,'' Rodriguez said.
   Natalia, Abell's home, is 18 miles southwest of San Antonio.
</TEXT>
