<1ST_LINE>u a PM-LehderTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0523 05-11 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lehder Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0523,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Begins Closing Arguments</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with government finishing and
defense beginning closing arguments, transition. Pickup 7th graf,
`Merkle blasted ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense attorney in the cocaine
smuggling trial of reputed Colombian drug kingpin Carlos Lehder
Rivas told jurors in closing arguments today that Lehder's chief
prosecutor must have attended a different trial.
   ``He was in a trial in which all the witnesses told the truth,''
Edward R. Shohat said of U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, who wrapped
up the government's final arguments minutes earlier. ``He was in a
trial in which there was no cross-examination of the witneses. ...
That wasn't the trial that occurred in this courtroom.''
   Lehder, 38, whom prosecutors said was a key member of Colombia's
Medellin cartel, is charged with bringing 3.3 tons of cocaine into
the United States from 1978 to 1980, paying bribes and making
threats to use Norman's Cay in the Bahamas as a private relay
station.
   Co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged with smuggling conspiracy.
   Shohat said a big inconsistency in the government's case was
that the indictment claimed that all the cocaine was delivered to
Colombians in southern Florida, but the government's key witness,
an American, testified that some of the cocaine was delivered to
him.
   In his closing arguments, Merkle referred to trial testimony
that Lehder used bribes, charm and threats to run a smuggling
empire, and that for once Lehder was without such advantages.
   ``He cannot buy his way out of a just verdict. He cannot charm
his way out of a just verdict. And he cannot force his way out of a
just verdict,'' Merkle said.
   A day earlier Merkle said Lehder was waging a violent war
against the United States and viewed cocaine as a weapon.
   ``He's still at war,'' Merkle told the jury that has heard 22
weeks of testimony.
   Merkle said Tuesday that Lehder viewed cocaine as a weapon
against the United States. The prosecutor also said the Colombian
was responsible for smuggling 19 tons into the United States and
had earned $20 million.
   ``That is an example of Mr. Lehder's `children' you saw in this
courtroom,'' said Merkle. Several witnesses have testified that
Lehder referred to cocaine loads as children.
   Merkle blasted defense arguments that Lehder had been used by
convicted smuggler and key prosecution witness Ed Ward as well as
contentions that Lehder was a legitimate businessman who wanted to
develop Norman's Cay as a resort.
   ``There is simply no way the defense is plausible, credible or
believable,'' the prosecutor said. ``A legitimate businessman
doesn't attract tourists with machine guns.''
   The prosecutor said that to equate Lehder's drug organization to
Ward's group of American smugglers was like ``comparing the Boston
Red Sox to the Little League.''
   ``The evidence in this case shows a trail of bribery,
corruption, violence and personal debasement that has been created
and fostered by Mr. Lehder,'' he said.
   The jury likely will get the case Friday and begin deliberations
on the 11-count indictment charging Lehder with conspiracy,
possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of
cocaine and racketeering.
   A separate Miami indictment accuses Lehder of being one of the
leaders of the Medellin cartel, believed to be responsible for 80
percent of the cocaine smuggled into United States.
</TEXT>
