<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FarmerPlay     05-11 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmer Play,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Guard Writes Play About Farmer's Suicide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lenard is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After reading about the suicide of a financially
strapped farmer, a security guard began spending his evenings at
home writing a play to dramatize the plight of farm families.
   Bradford Riley's ``Foreclosure'' opens next week for a limited
run at an off-off Broadway theater in New York. Riley said he hopes
the drama will be presented across the country.
   ``No one is a spokesman for the farmer, because farmers don't
speak much,'' Riley said Tuesday in a telephone interview. ``Maybe
the play could do that. It's suited to play in a field, in
gymnasiums.''
   Riley's play is based on the experiences of the Hill family of
Waynesboro in east Georgia. Lenard Hill, whose farm had been in his
family for five generations, killed himself 20 minutes before the
land was to be auctioned in February 1986 to pay a $300,000 debt.
   Hill reportedly hoped proceeds from his life insurance policy
and a private land sale would settle the debt, but it was not
enough. When the plight of his widow, Annabell Hill, was
publicized, Atlanta businessman Frank Argenbright Jr. led a
fund-raising drive to help the family.
   That drew the attention of, among others, New York developer
Donald Trump, who contributed $39,000. Two days before Christmas
1986, the mortgage on the 705-acre farm was retired.
   ``I kept getting news clippings and cutting them out of the
paper about farmers committing suicide,'' said Riley, 38.
   But it was Mrs. Hill's story that inspired him to write.
   ``I tried to show what it's like, what makes a farmer commit
suicide,'' he said.
   ``Foreclosure'' doesn't follow the Hill story exactly. In the
play, for example, both husband and wife commit suicide, Riley
said. Mrs. Hill now lives in Augusta; her son runs the farm.
   Riley, who has dabbled in theater before but never tried a major
production, said he worked on the play for 1{ years. It will debut
May 19 at the LaMama Theater, and run for three weeks.
   Riley, who farms part-time in Blairsville in north Georgia, said
he planned to present Mrs. Hill with a signed copy of his play.
   ``Mrs. Hill's story personifies for me the American farmers'
condition,'' Riley said. ``My hopes are that `Foreclosure' will
bring the urgency of the farmers' situation to the American
conscience.''
</TEXT>
