<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MOVE-Developers     05-11 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MOVE-Developers,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Developer Convicted of Stealing Money Slated for MOVE housing
Reconstruction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A developer was convicted today of taking
more than $115,000 intended for the reconstruction of 61 houses
that burned in a 1985 police confrontation with the radical group
MOVE.
   Ernest Edwards, charged with stealing money from various
accounts intended for the rebuilding project, was convicted of
stealing mobilization money, bond money, transportation expenses
and unlawfully using workers paid by the city to work on a union
hall.
   He was also convicted in a kickback scheme involving a drainage
project at the neighborhood destroyed in the May 13, 1985 fire that
killed six MOVE members and five children. The fire began when a
police helicopter bombed members of the group who had barricaded a
house to resist eviction.
   Edwards was acquitted on charges he stole $85,000 for his own
salary and for workers on the project.
   His former business partner, W. Oscar Harris, was found guilty
of failure to make required disposition of about $90,000 and
acquitted of theft by deception and criminal conspiracy charged
related to the same amount.
   Neither Edwards nor Harris showed any emotion as the 31-count
verdict was read to Common Pleas Judge Angelo A. Guarino.
   The jury deliberated about 6 hours before returning the verdict.
   ``I'm not going to try to say what won the case. I'm just very
pleased,'' said Assistant District Attorney Janet P. Houser.
   ``He's not taking it very well. ... We thought it was a
compromise verdict and a verdict that really didn't indicate that
the evidence as we presented it was properly understood,'' said
Edwards' attorney, Hugh C. Clark.
   The two men are free on bail until Friday, when a new bond must
be posted on their convictions. Bail was set at $25,000 for Edwards
and $2,500 for Harris. Sentencing is scheduled for June 15.
</TEXT>
