<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Bribes     05-11 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Bribes,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Government Official Arrested On Bribery Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Wednesday arrested a former official
who had worked in the prime minister's office and charged him with
bribery.
   Tokyo prosecutors said Tetsuaki Hashimoto, 58, who was in charge
of the annual budget for government publicity since 1979, allegedly
received a total of $800,000 in cash from various advertising
firms, including $18,400 in bribes from July 1984 to last October.
   They said the latter sum was paid in six installments by
executives of two Tokyo advertising firms handling government
publicity.
   Arrested for allegedly bribing Hashimoto were Mokikichi
Fukuzawa, 60, president of the Sanko advertising agency, and
Tatsunori Kawamoto, 59, president of the Nihon Video Network
advertising firm.
   It was the first bribery case involving an official working for
the prime minister since World War II, news reports said.
   Hashimoto, who resigned March 1, reportedly handled the
government's publicity budget under four prime ministers, including
the current one, Noboru Takeshita.
   The government spent an annual $92 million through March 31 on
electronic media, newspaper and other forms of advertising,
according to government statistics.
</TEXT>
