<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Suspicious Teller,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teller Charged With Conspiracy In Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank teller who was seen walking
arm-in-arm with a person who fit the description of the man who
robbed her has been arrested on conspiracy charges.
   A robber escaped March 9 with nearly $3,000 from a branch of
Burritt InterFinancial BankCorp. after handing teller Cynthia
Langham a note and threatening her with a gun, police said.
   ``There was a long delay between the time she supposedly took a
note from him and announced that she'd been robbed. She waited on
two customers in the meantime,'' Detective William M. Kilduff said.
   The next day, some police officers at a conference saw the
teller walking with a man who resembled the suspect. After
notifying the FBI, police arrested Thomas M. Jenkins of East
Hartford in his room at the hotel where the conference was being
held.
   Langham, 23, was arrested Monday. Kilduff said police only
recently obtained enough information for a warrant for her arrest
on charges of third-degree larceny and third-degree conspiracy to
commit larceny.
   Jenkins has been held since his arrest. Langham was released
Monday on a written promise to appear in court later this month.
