<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EcstasyRuling     05-11 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecstasy Ruling,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Ecstasy' Drug Convictions Overturned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court has ruled that the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Administration does not have the authority to
temporarily outlaw ``designer drugs'' as they hit the market.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Tuesday threw out the
convictions of three men found guilty of distributing and
conspiring to distribute MDMA, or methylenedioxymethamphetamine in
1985 and 1986. The drug's street name was ``ecstasy.''
   The court said the U.S. Attorney General had not delegated his
authority to the administrator of the DEA to designate the drug as
a controlled substance.
   The opinion issued by Judge Robert Boochever said that federal
law governing permanent scheduling of controlled substances was
altered in 1984 with an amendment that fundamentally changed the
process for temporary scheduling.
   Judge Charles B. Wiggins dissented, saying, ``I believe the
majority demands too much of the government's crime-fighting
efforts in the face of an unambiguous delegation of responsibility
by Congress.''
   ``I believe the plain intent of Congress was to establish an
expedited system of review in order to criminalize the possession,
manufacturing and distribution of newly-developed `designer' drugs
before they become public health hazards,'' he wrote.
   In July, 1985, the DEA administrator added MDMA to a federal
list of temporarily controlled substances.
   Temporary scheduling, designed to take effect within 30 days of
announcement to avoid lengthy public comment that could jeopardize
public safety, expires after a year. It can be extended six months
if the Attorney General has begun efforts to make it permanently
illegal.
   The court did not make a finding that the Attorney General
couldn't delegate authority to place ``ecstasy'' on the emergency
list.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
