<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TripTrouble     05-11 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trip Trouble,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stranded Students' Trip Salvaged by School Board, Airline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students from a California junior high school
got to continue their weeklong tour of the East Coast on Wednesday
after school officials and an airline came to the rescue when their
prepaid tour went bust.
   The 185 youngsters from Emerald Junior High School in El Cajon
had been midway through their trip Tuesday when the travel agency
that arranged the tour left them without cash for food, lodging or
airfare home.
   ``I don't know what the travel agency did with the money but
it's gone,'' said school principal Marge Dean, who was in
California helping arrange a long-distance bailout.
   The youths' 38 teacher and parent chaperones pooled their cash
Tuesday to finance one night at a lower-cost Washington hotel after
East@West Travel and Tours of San Diego said the trip was being
canceled due to a lack of money, Ms. Dean said. Telephones at the
agency went unanswered Wednesday morning.
   The youngsters continued their planned itinerary, heading for
Philadelphia in buses Wednesday, after their school board agreed to
pick up remaining costs for the trip and American Airlines donated
plane tickets home.
   ``The kids have been wonderful, a little bit teary-eyed and
concerned, but now that they know that they can continue the trip,
they're wonderful,'' Ms. Dean said.
   ``There was a little bit of time when they were worried,'' said
tour director Steve Ewalt, an employee of the travel agency who
added that he would see the youth through even though he wasn't
getting paid. ``The kids I don't think have experienced any of the
real heartache that some of us have.''
   Ewalt said he'd directed hundreds of tours for the company but
``this time we could sense that it was a little different.''
   ``We just found that the money was drying up,'' he said. ``When
it stops right in the middle, there's really nothing we can do
about it.''
   Ms. Dean said the Cajon Valley School Board voted Tuesday night
to pick up remaining costs for the trip, estimated at $47,000, and
would ``ask the parents to have some kind of fund-raising activity.
... They'll probably have to have car washes'' to help defray the
costs.
   Ewalt said the students would wind up the week in New York
before heading home on Saturday. The students began their East
Coast tour last Friday, visiting Williamsburg, Va., and touring
Thomas Jefferson's home, Monticello, before sightseeing in
Washington.
</TEXT>
