<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush'sResume Bjt   05-11 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush's Resume, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Foreign Policy Resume May Be More Hindrance Than Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has a foreign policy resume that
stretches from Central America to the Great Wall of China, but as
he moves toward a fall presidential showdown his experience is
proving more of a political handicap than Michael Dukakis'
inexperience.
   The Republican vice president relishes describing the Democratic
governor of Massachusestts as one who ``doesn't know much about
foreign affairs.'' Bush clearly expects to overwhelm Dukakis
whenever foreign policy is an issue in the fall campaign.
   Granted that Dukakis has seemed ill at ease on foreign policy
questions including the continued validity of the Monroe Doctrine
against foreign intervention in the Western Hemisphere, U.S.
retaliation against Iran in the Persian Gulf and the use of nuclear
weapons in Europe.
   But those seemed brief, mostly forgotten incidents compared to
the incessant questioning Bush receives about his role in the
Iran-Contra affair and his knowledge of Panamanian strongman Manuel
Antonio Noriega's involvement in drug trafficking.
   And, it is Bush who will be haunted throughout the campaign by
the words of his rivals for the GOP presidential nomination,
particularly former Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig Jr. who
once questioned whether in administration councils the vice
president had been ``in the cockpit or ... on an economy ride in
the back of the plane.''
   Bush may yet prove correct as he anticipates that Dukakis' lack
of foreign policy experience will lead him into a damaging gaffe
when they debate in the fall.
   ``I can't wait for the debates,'' said the vice president.
   ``I can't wait for Mr. Dukakis to discuss the Noriega matter,''
he replied a week later when an Ohio high school student asked if
it was true, as Dukakis was charging, that the Panamanian general
had been on the U.S. payroll.
   Bush said he would ask Dukakis, ``What would you do about it?
... You can make a lot of unfounded criticism, but what's his
suggestion? What's he going to do and do it in a way that handles
the delicate Central American relationships that we're building.''
   Maybe, as Bush said, he can't wait to confront Dukakis on
questions like Noriega and Iran-Contra.
   But it is equally clear that Dukakis is just as eager to raise
those issues.
   What better way to defend his lack of foreign policy experience
than by going on the offense against the Bush resume.
   Hardly a day goes by that the Massachusetts governor doesn't
raise the Noriega matter. ``Who was dealing with him and why?''
Dukakis said Monday. ``Were we paying him and if so why? I can tell
you one thing: If I'm the president we won't be doing business with
drug-running Panamanian dictators.''
   Dealing with dictators is a fact of life in international
relations, one accepted by most voters.
   But the involvement in drug-trafficking makes the Noriega matter
a far more serious political issue.
   A pledge to wage a war on drugs was a theme common to the
rhetoric of all presidential candidates, Republican and Democratic.
That alone was recognition of the fact that voters were demanding
to know what the politicians intend to do about a serious national
problem.
   In 1984, Republicans were able to play back Sen. John Glenn's
jibes at Walter F. Mondale when they were battling for the
Democratic presidential nomination. It will be the Democrats' turn
this time.
   They are sure to recall Haig's comment on the Bush-Noriega
matter, the day the former Reagan Cabinet official ended his race
for the GOP presidential nomination.
   ``I do think there's been less than forthright discussion of
this issue by the vice president,'' said Haig. He refused to
elaborate, but the fact that he was secretary of state during the
first two years of the Reagan presidency made his comment
particularly tantalizing.
   Equally useful to the Democrats would be the collected jibes of
Bob Dole, the acerbic senator from Kansas who thrashed Bush in the
Iowa Republican presidential caucuses and then saw his hopes of
being the nominee buried on Super Tuesday.
   It was Dole who predicted Iran-Contra would be an issue for the
Democrats in the fall campaign. And in case the opposition needed
some help trying to describe the scandal, Dole referred to White
House advisers ``peddling arms to the ayatollah while others hear
no evil, see no evil.'' Dole left it clear that one of the
``others'' was Bush.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Donald M. Rothberg is the chief political writer
of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
