<1ST_LINE>r n PM-Sea-TacCrash 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sea-Tac Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY Gen, CP Note</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fuel Leak Found in Engine of Sea-Tac Crash Plane</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Pratt & Whitney comments, brings up details of crash,
number of injuries, makes editing changes throughout.</NOTE>
<HEAD>SE Locals Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fuel leak was found in the engine of a Horizon
Air comuter aircraft that caught fire and crash-landed April 15 at
Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, injuring 19 people,
investigators said.
   The leak occurred because an ``O'' ring was out of place in a
fuel filter assembly, and the filter wasn't seated properly, Ted
Lopatkiewicz of the National Transportation Safety Board said
Tuesday. The findings confirmed passenger reports of ``liquid
streaming out of the engine,'' he said.
   ``An X-ray revealed that the `O' ring was damaged and out of
place,'' and a manual test also confirmed the leak, Lopatkiewicz
said.
   John Kelly, president of Horizon Air, said investigators ``found
exactly what we said the cause was'' and that it was ``not
something Horizon had fixed, touched or been involved in.''
   After landing, the twin-engine de Havilland Dash 8, with 40
people aboard, careened out of control and crashed into three
passenger loading ramps. It came to rest against a terminal
concourse.
   The crew and airport firefighters were praised for coolness
under pressure and quick action in dousing the blaze.
   The turboprop engine, a 2,000-horsepower PW-120 manufactured at
the Pratt & Whitney of Canada Ltd. plant near Montreal, was
dismantled by investigators last week, he said.
   Pratt & Whitney of Canada has asked airlines in Europe and North
America that fly the Dash 8 to check the fuel filter assembly.
   ``They have checked and everything is in order,'' company
spokesman Pierre Henry said Tuesday. He said it was possible the
filter assembly on the Horizon plane might have been damaged during
maintenance.
   ``Every time you remove a filter and put a new one in, ... if
the cover is not on properly, a leak can develop because of the
pressure,'' Henry said.
   The filter assembly had been in service six or seven days on the
Horizon Air plane and was part of ``the fuel pump that had been
taken straight from the factory and put on this engine,'' Kelly
said. ``How it got in that shape, I don't know.''
   A check of other filter assemblies Horizon had in storage
revealed a similar seating problem in one other unit, which was
turned over to investigators, he added.
   Still unknown, Lopatkiewicz said, was how the fire ignited and
why the plane went out of control when it made an emergency landing
shortly after takeoff for Spokane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0176 </DOCNO>
