<1ST_LINE>r p AM-StatePrimariesRdp     05-11 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Primaries Rdp,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Pledge Unity in Nebraska; Democrats Divided in WVa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nebraska Republicans said Wednesday their bruising primary had
given Sen. David Karnes ``the strength to win'' against Democrat
Bob Kerrey, but West Virginia Democrats remained divided by their
fight to choose an opponent for GOP Gov. Arch Moore.
   Karnes, who was running in his first election after being
appointed 14 months ago, defeated Rep. Hal Daub by a
bigger-than-expected margin Tuesday for the right to face Kerrey,
the ex-governor who swamped one Democratic rival.
   Moore edged millionaire industrialist John Raese to grab the GOP
nomination for an unprecedented fourth term, and will face another
millionaire, insurance executive Gaston Caperton, who had never
before run for office.
   Also in West Virginia, Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd
easily won the Democratic nomination to a sixth term and will be
heavily favored over his Republican opponent, state Sen. Jay Wolfe.
   Daub appeared with Karnes at a unity gathering in Omaha on
Wednesday, drawing cheers from party leaders as he placed a
``Karnes for Senate'' sticker on his lapel.
   ``I learned a great deal from him,'' said Karnes, who at 39 is
the nation's youngest senator. ``Maybe he taught me too well.''
   The four-term congressman, who had attacked Karnes aggressively
during the campaign, praised his rival and said that without the
hard-fought primary ``neither one of us would likely have had the
strength to win'' in November.
   That sentiment was echoed by Tom Mason, director of
communications and research for the Republican Senatorial Committee
in Washington.
   ``Everybody would rather avoid a primary, but he got his
political act together,'' Mason said of Karnes. ``... Had Hal Daub
won, a lot of Karnes people would have sat it out.''
   But Anita Dunn, communications director for the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee, noted that Kerrey has been running
ahead in polls pitting him against either Republican in a state
where 51 percent of registered voters prefer the GOP.
   ``The race will tighten up,'' she said, ``but Bob Kerrey remains
a popular figure, and against that you have an appointed senator
who just came through one of the most bitter primaries that anyone
is going to see.''
   In West Virginia, Caperton said Wednesday his top priority was
to ``bring our party together because we share the common goals of
better jobs, improved schools and a balanced budget for our state.''
   But talk of party unity held little appeal for Clyde See, who
finished second in a seven-man field.
   ``He bought this election fair and square,'' was the assessment
from See, the former House of Delegates Speaker who was outspent by
Caperton $1.8 million to $500,000. See had been the Democratic
nominee in 1984.
   Here are the returns from the major races, with 100 percent of
the vote counted in Nebraska and 99 percent in West Virginia:
   _ Nebraska GOP Senate: Karnes had 114,783 votes or 55 percent;
Daub had 93,932 votes or 45 percent.
   _ Nebraska Democratic Senate: Kerrey had 153,611 votes or 92
percent; Ken Michaelis, a disbarred lawyer, had 13,996 votes or 8
percent.
   _ West Virginia GOP Governor: Moore had 77,626 votes or 53
percent; Raese had 67,986 votes or 47 percent.
   _ West Virginia Democratic Governor: Caperton had 128,593 votes
or 37 percent; See had 93,435 votes or 27 percent; state Sen. Mario
Palumbo had 50,955 votes or 15 percent; Agriculture Commissioner
Gus Douglass had 48,376 votes or 14 percent; the rest were divided
among three other candidates.
</TEXT>
