<1ST_LINE>u a PM-LiuKilling 1stLd-Writethru a0772 05-11 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liu Killing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0772,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gangster Sentenced in Murder of Chinese-American Journalist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 8 grafs at end with background</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gangster was sentenced today to a
maximum term of 27 years-to-life in prison for killing a
Chinese-American journalist in 1984, an act he testified was
ordered by the Taiwanese government.
   Tung Kuei-sen, a member of the International United Bamboo Gang,
was ordered to serve the prison sentence for the murder of Henry
Liu after he completes a 20-year sentence for heroin smuggling.
   San Mateo County Superior Judge Margaret J. Kemp rejected
defense arguments for concurrent sentencing that a prosecutor said
could have set Tung free in six years. Liu's widow also had asked
the court for mercy, saying she was touched by Tung's public
repentance.
   Kemp called the slaying ``an act of political terrorism.''
   Tung, 36, received 25 years to life for murder and two years for
use of a firearm. Prosecutor Bob Bishop said Tung will not be
eligible for parole for 17 years and eight months.
   Tung was convicted by a jury in March after admitting he gunned
down Liu in the garage of the dissident writer's home in Daly City
on Oct. 15, 1984. He claimed he carried out the act for patriotic
reasons, believing he was killing a traitor on order from Taiwan's
government.
   Wearing a red prison jumpsuit and manacles on his wrists and
ankles, the short, stocky member of the infamous Taiwan gang smiled
wryly as the sentence was explained to him by an interpreter in the
packed courtroom.
   The 52-year-old Liu was a columnist for Chinese-language
newspapers in San Francisco and was killed just after publishing an
unflattering biography of Taiwan President Chiang Chung-kuo, who
died four months ago.
   Helen Liu had testified at Tung's trial that before her
husband's slaying, the Taiwan government had started sending over
former friends of her husband's to try to convince him to quit
criticizing the government.
   Tung, who is serving his heroin smuggling sentence at Lewisburg
Federal Penitentiary in Pennsylvania, is one of two suspected
gunmen to be brought to trial in the United States.
   He pleaded innocent last June despite having admitted to the
slaying at his 1986 federal drug trial, saying he was unable to get
a plea bargain and wanted to tell his story for the record.
   Tung testified that Liu was killed on orders from his gang boss
and members of the Taiwanese government. He said he believed he was
duped by his government into killing a man who was not a traitor
and also sent a written apology to Mrs. Liu.
   In a letter to the court, Mrs. Liu said she hoped others
involved in her husband's ``bloody murder'' would be prosecuted.
   Bishop, an assistant district attorney, said during the trial
that Taiwanese Admiral Wang Hsi-ling hired Tung to assassinate Liu.
   The prosecution said Wu Tun, 35, was the second gunman and is
serving a life term for the killing in a Taiwanese prison. Chen
Chi-li, 43, the reputed head of United Bamboo, is also serving a
life term in a Taiwanese prison for Liu's killing.
</TEXT>
