<2ND_LINE>PM-Rainbow Family, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magistrate: Back-to-Nature Group Should Be Restrained from
Gatherings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to CORRECT that today's recommendation
involves only this weekend's meeting, picking up 4th graf pvs,
``Attorneys for xxx</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LUFKIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate today recommended that
Rainbow Family members be prevented from meeting this weekend in
advance of a July gathering by thousands of family members.
   In a hearing Tuesday before Magistrate J. Michael Bradford,
health and U.S. Forest Service officials said the Rainbow Family's
planned July 4 meeting in an East Texas forest could strain
resources.
   Bradford recommended to U.S. District Judge William Wayne
Justice in Tyler that the group be restrained from advertising and
organizing for the ``tribal council'' this weekend. Tyler will
consider the recommendation Thursday.
   Attorneys for the group and the government may file arguments on
Bradford's recommendation. He will hold another hearing Friday, a
law clerk said.
   Family members will fight the recommendation and still plan to
meet, spokesman Stephen Principle said.
   ``I don't know who can stop this,'' he said of both gatherings.
``All our literature every year has said, `Ignore any rumors of
cancellations, regardless of source.'''
   Principle said no state has ever stopped the annual July
gathering.
   At the Tuesday hearing, the forest service said the loosely knit
group had not applied for special-use permits.
   Dr. Marietta Crowder of the Tyler Health Department testified
that a Rainbow Family convention the size of one in North Carolina
last year that drew 17,000 people would strain drinking-water
supplies and garbage collection abilities.
   Members of the self-proclaimed peace and environmentalist group
gathered before the hearing on the federal courthouse steps to
protest the possible prevention of their gathering.
   The group, which held its first gathering in 1972, has no
headquarters and no membership list, said spokesman Garrick Beck in
New York.
   Officials predicted about 500 people would show for this
weekend's council meeting and up to 20,000 for the July 4 weekend
event, called the Rainbow Gathering of the Tribes.
   A Rainbow Family spokesman who identified himself only as
Alabama said today that the group had scouted four possible sites
for the gatherings _ Angelina, Davey Crockett, Sam Houston and
Sabine National Forests _ but had not chosen one.
</TEXT>
