<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Pepitone, the former New York Yankee
slugger, has lost a bid to reduce his sentence on misdemeanor drug
charges and will begin serving the six-month jail term Monday, his
attorney says.
   A four-judge panel of the state Appellate Division in Brooklyn
upheld the sentence Tuesday.
   Pepitone's attorney, John Kelly, had challenged the sentence as
excessive for a first offense misdemeanor conviction. ``If he had
been a nobody on the street, he wouldn't have received a jail
sentence,'' Kelly said.
   The 46-year-old Pepitone, who played for the Yankees from
1962-69, has been free on $15,000 bail pending his appeal since his
sentencing Oct. 22, 1986.
   A jury found Pepitone guilty of possessing 300 pills and
glassine envelopes used to package narcotics.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest edition of Donald Trump's
best-selling biography, ``Trump: The Art of the Deal,'' is two
sentences shorter after developer Samuel J. LeFrak complained a
reference to him was inaccurate.
   The mention comes during a reported conversation between Trump
and the late Roy Cohn, during which Trump tells the lawyer the
government had filed civil rights suits against his company and
many others, saying they discriminated against blacks in some
housing developments.
   Trump said he had been advised to settle, but goes on to write:
``The idea of settling drove me crazy. What we didn't do was rent
to welfare cases, white or black. I'd watched what happened when
the government came after Samuel LeFrak, another builder, and he
caved in and started taking welfare cases. They virtually ruined
his buildings.''
   The new printing of the book written by Trump and Tony Schwartz
eliminates the last two sentences of that paragraph.
   ``Sam called me and very politely said he was distressed, and
his lawyers wrote a letter to Random House,'' his publisher, Trump
told The New York Times Tuesday. ``There's nothing legally wrong
with what I wrote, but I happen to like Sam and ... didn't want him
to be distressed.''
   Gerald Hollingsworth, general counsel to Random House, said
``they were deleted out of deference to Mr. LeFrak's feelings and
out of a belief that they were not important to the book in any
case.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   HESPERIA, Calif. (AP) _ During his 30-year career as a
professional wrestler, stuntman and animal handler, ``The Great
John L'' has tackled bears, eaten fire and broken bricks with his
bare hands.
   But The Great John L may have met his match in a neighbor who
does not see his three pet mountain lions as mere pussycats.
   John L, known offstage as Bill Clark, says he asked neighbors if
they objected to the mountain lions before he moved last month to
this desert neighborhood, 65 miles northeast of Los Angeles.
   Now, he says he cannot afford to move right away.
   Phyllis Brooks of the San Bernardino County Department of Health
Services said Wednesday that John L has until May 20 to do
something with his ``cats,'' who have appeared in television
commercials. In the meantime, Ms. Brooks said, John L has moved the
cats to his brother's house in a more remote area nearby.
   ``These are professional cats,'' John L said earlier this week.
``Not run-of-the-mill ordinary cats.''
   ``The cats are like my kids _ it's like asking me to shoot
them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRESHAM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black Sabbath, Alice Cooper, Iron Maiden
and Kiss are giving some telephone users heavy-metal headaches in
this Portland suburb.
   About 200 phones are picking up the music of those rock groups
and other bands from radio station KZRC, which has its studio
nearby.
   A phone customer, Brad Moffenbier, described the music as
``noise of the worst kind.''
   Bob Simms, an installation supervisor for the GTE Northwest
telephone company, said the phenomenon was not uncommon. He
attributed it to broadcasting quirks, improperly grounded phone
lines and use of phones that are not equipped to screen out radio
waves.
   One of the station's owners, John Grant of Lake Oswego, said
KZRC, which broadcasts from sunrise to sunset, was cooperating with
the phone company in an effort to eliminate the problem.
</TEXT>
