<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Denmark     05-11 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Denmark,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Watches Election Aftermath in Denmark for Effects on NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With post-election maneuvering under way
Wednesday in Denmark, the Reagan administration declined to
speculate publicly about how the balloting will affect continued
Danish participation in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   ``The results are somewhat inconclusive,'' State Department
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said. ``The United States and Denmark
have a long and close friendship and the United States government
will continue to work closely with the government that is formed
after the Danes have evaluated their election.''
   The Reagan administration had been hoping Danish voters would
elect parliamentarians opposed to a recently passed resolution that
would make it impossible for U.S. ships carrying nuclear weapons to
visit Denmark. The resolution has raised questions about Denmark's
continued membership in NATO because nuclear deterrence is one of
the bedrocks of alliance doctrine.
   Tuesday's vote for 179 Parliament seats resulted in a modest
shift to the right and strengthened the parties that give
unqualified support to NATO, analysts there said.
   The future of the Danish nuclear resolution depends on whether
Prime Minister Poul Schlueter _ who doesn't want to implement the
policy _ is able to form another minority government.
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk said ``we have an interest
in the substance of the (nuclear) ship issue and expect to discuss
it with the new government once it is formed.''
   As the delicate coalition-bargaining unfolds in Denmark, the
United States is remaining noncommital about the situation, the
U.S. officials said.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz made clear, however, during
a trip to Europe late last month that he is disturbed by the
possibility that Denmark might institute a ban on nuclear-armed
ships.
   A similar ban enacted by New Zealand led to the demise of a
three-decade alliance in the South Pacific and Shultz asserted that
Danish action to limit nuclear missions would hurt NATO as well.
   Shultz, who has said his hand in dealing with the Soviets is
strengthened by NATO solidarity, said ``if you like the benefits,
if you like peace, if you like the fact that progress is being made
in negotiations, then you ought to like the responsibilities that
go with making that possible.''
</TEXT>
