<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1514EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Cubans-NewWave Bjt   05-11 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cubans-New Wave, Bjt,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mixed Reception Seen for Next Wave of 20,000 Cubans a Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-six bleary-eyed Cubans arrived before dawn
Wednesday to tears and hugs from relatives, but they and 20,000
other Cubans coming to Miami this year face a more uncertain
reception from the rest of the city.
   For some residents, concerns stem from memories of escalated
street crime after the 1980 Mariel boatlift; others, particularly
American blacks who feel their economic and political opportunities
will shrink with the rising Cuban population, also are concerned.
And government officials fret about the financial costs of the new
immigrants.
   ``It's a shame people tend to remember only the bad parts of
Cuban immigration, but the truth is that most Cubans have gone on
to be some of our most thriving citizens,'' said City Manager Cesar
Odio, a Cuban-American.
   Officials are quick to note that the new, carefully screened
Cuban immigrants, who began arriving by the hundreds this month,
have little in common with the 125,000 who came ashore when Cuban
President Fidel Castro opened the port of Mariel _ and his prisons
_ for six months and ignored Carter administration pleas for
controlled immigration.
   ``Not only have they been through a rigorous procedure by
federal immigration officials to ensure their financial stability,
but most will initially be living with relatives here _ that's a
support system the bulk of the Mariels never had,'' said Bobby
Bernal, refugee affairs coordinator for Dade County.
   Unlike most other immigrant groups, Cubans have chosen one city
as their own. More than 80 percent of the Cubans coming here since
Castro's 1959 revolution stayed in South Florida. They have
overtaken non-Latin whites, called ``Anglos,'' and make up 42
percent of Dade County's 1.86 million people as the largest group.
   Cubans dominate Miami politics, economy and society and
transformed a tourism-based southern city into a modern,
Latin-oriented financial center.
   Still, simmering resentment flared in the years immediately
following Castro's uncontrolled ``Freedom Flotilla.''
   A minority of hard-core criminals helped push Miami atop violent
crime statistics and that lawless image was spread with a Hollywood
remake of ``Scarface,'' starring Al Pacino as a Mariel cocaine
kingpin.
   Thousands were placed on the public dole, and state and local
governments still are seeking federal reimbursement for $150
million in services spent on the refugees.
   In 1980, Dade County residents expressed a backlash by passing
an anti-bilingualism ordinance, and continued resentment by the
remaining non-Latins often surfaces on radio talk shows and other
forums.
   ``Cubans already here would like to allow any Cuban to come over
here and live in liberty _ but you have to draw the line
somewhere,'' said WNWS radio talk show host Al Rantel, who roused
attention with his proposed referendum to put a cap on public
spending for refugees.
   Black leaders have protested every new influx, fearing Cubans
will further dilute black political and economic power.
   ``From day one they're competing for the same jobs as blacks,''
said Garth Reeves Jr., publisher of the black-oriented newspaper
The Miami Times. ``We need more Cubans like we need the plague.''
   The basis for the new immigration is an agreement signed by the
United States and Cuba in late 1984, only to be suspended by Castro
five months later after the start of U.S. Radio Marti broadcasts
into Cuba.
   That pact was revived seven months ago when Cuba agreed to take
back about 2,500 Mariel Cubans _ a move that sparked riots and
hostage sieges at federal detention centers in Oakdale, La., and
Atlanta.
   The United States then opened its doors to 3,000 political
prisoners and the annual flow of 20,000 immediate relatives of U.S.
citizens. The 36 former political prisoners and their families, who
arrived in a regular chartered flight at Miami International
Airport from Havana Wednesday, were part of another group of some
400 political prisoners and relatives whose release was secured
from the Cuban government by the U.S. Catholic Conference.
   Cubans are being issued 40 to 45 visas a day and the immigrants
are allowed to travel by any means they desire anytime within four
months of the visa, said Donna Sherman, a spokeswoman for the U.S.
Bureau of Consular Affairs in Washington.
   At that rate, about 250 arrivals per week are expected this
month and as many as 350 a week are expected by summer's end, she
said.
</TEXT>
