<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaughingJurors     05-11 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laughing Jurors,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trip to Comedy Club May Result in New Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense attorney found nothing funny about a
group of sequestered jurors taking in a show at a comedy club the
night before they convicted his client of murder.
   The night out, in apparent violation of the judge's order, could
lead to a new trial _ the third _ for Tommy Wayne Dunn, who was
convicted of paying a man $800 to kill his father in 1981.
   Attorney Mike DeGeurin appealed the case to the 1st Court of
Appeals.
   After a hearing Tuesday on the appeal, State District Judge
Jimmy James said he will urge the appellate court to deny a new
trial.
   Bailiff Don R. McCray said he ``basically didn't realize I was
doing anything wrong'' when he took eight jurors to the Laff Stop
nightclub last Aug. 19.
   DeGeurin noted a transcript that quotes James saying: ``Mr.
Bailiff, don't let the jury separate other than for purposes of
going to the hotel and (their rooms). They are not to separate at
any other time.''
   Five jurors testified that McCray told them they could stay at
the hotel with another bailiff or go to the club.
   The eight who went with McCray watched two comedians and a
hypnotist and ran up a $39.15 bar tab.
   While the hearing mostly concerned the violation of James' order
and whether the night at the club may have affected deliberations,
McCray said the liquor bill launched the fuss.
   ``This has escalated and been blown all out of proportion,'' he
said. ``It's always been my understanding that on a sequestered
deal, jurors can have drinks or wine with their meal.''
   ``This is highly unique, but nothing happened that affected the
defendant getting a fair trial,'' said Prosecutor Carol Davies.
   She and DeGeurin said they know of no other sequestered jury
being taken to a club for drinks.
   ``It's not a laughing matter,'' DeGeurin said Wednesday. ``Can
you imagine the defendant sitting in his cell with his head hanging
wondering what the jurors will decide on this case and on the other
side the jurors are out boozing it up at a club being hypnotized
and laughing it up?''
   Dunn's father, Alfred, 53, was shot twice in the back Oct. 12,
1981, as he walked across a parking lot with Robin Buchanan
Summers. She testified last year she had affairs with both the
father and son.
   The man believed to have fired the shots committed suicide in
jail while awaiting trial. Dunn, 40, is serving a life sentence on
his second conviction of murder.
   His first conviction was reversed because his lawyer, Stan
Schneider, was excluded from being present while detectives were
taking Dunn's confession.
</TEXT>
