<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Medicare     05-11 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicare,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Faults Quality Assurance Efforts by Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government efforts to make sure Medicare
patients receive good health care are hampered by poor
coordination, questionable information and a lack of treatment
standards, a congressional investigative agency said Wednesday.
   The General Accounting Office said it ``found reasons for
concern about current systems for monitoring'' the quality of care
given the Medicare program's 31 million enrollees. The government
spent $70 billion on such care last year.
   In a report, the GAO said review methods of ``uncertain
validity'' are being used and problems identified by one set of
reviewers are not coordinated for action by others.
   Further, it said, ``the accuracy of key information (generated
by reviews) is questionable'' and the federal Health Care Financing
Administration, or HCFA, does not have an adequate long-term
strategy to improve its overall Medicare monitoring system.
   Any future strategy should include setting minimum standards of
clinical practice and testing incentives to get doctors to follow
them, the GAO said.
   It recommended that the House Ways and Means health
subcommittee, chaired by Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., consider
proposals to assign quality-assurance responsibilities to a new or
existing federal entity.
   Stark, who requested and released the report, said he would use
it ``to look at whether we need to develop legislation to make sure
we get good quality care for the nation's retirees.''
   ``Right now we don't know if we're getting quality in the
medical care Medicare is paying for,'' Stark said in a statement.
``The GAO report makes clear that HCFA doesn't have a strategy for
finding out how to know quality care when we see it, or if we did,
to make sure Medicare is receiving it.''
   The Department of Health and Human Services, of which HCFA is a
part, was quoted in the report as agreeing with all or most of the
GAO's recommendations.
   The report said the agency opposes creation of a new federal
entity to develop quality assurance methods but would consider
improvements in internal coordination.
</TEXT>
