<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder Sentence,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Gets Maximum for Wife Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who pursued his estranged wife
for two years, then shot her 13 times and stuffed her body in an
oven, was sentenced Wednesday to 28{ years to life in prison.
   A jury found Michael Linton, 32, of Yonkers guilty in February
of the murder in February 1987 of Yvonne Renee Linton in her
Yonkers apartment. He was also convicted of attempted assault on a
friend of Mrs. Linton who was in the apartment moments before the
killing.
   Linton entered his wife's apartment from the fire escape and
attacked her and the friend as she spoke to her mother on the phone.
   She shouted, ``Michael, you're a murderer!'' her mother said.
   Their three children were asleep when he came in and did not see
him.
   State Supreme Court Justice Nicholas Colabella imposed a 25-year
to life term for murder and a 3{- to seven-year term for the
attempted assault conviction _ both the maximum _ and ordered that
they be served consecutively.
   Linton says he is innocent and will appeal.
   The murder occurred one day before Linton was due in court to
answer a charge that he had violated a judge's order of protection
barring him from contacting his wife, who was divorcing him.
   According to prosecutor Jeanine Ferris Pirro, Linton pursued his
wife for two years from North Carolina to Yonkers, repeatedly
threatening her.
   The couple's 11-year-old son, Michael Jr., testified that his
father had repeatedly said he would ``hunt down'' his wife and kill
her for leaving him.
</TEXT>
