<HEAD>4,000 Strike in Kosovo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 4,000 construction workers
demanding higher wages were on strike Wednesday in southern
Yugoslavia, the Tanjug news agency reported.
   The strikes began Tuesday when 1,000 workers stopped work in
Pristina, capital of the southern region of Kosovo. The workers
were demanding pay raises of 100 percent. Most make about $50 a
month.
   Izet Sheku, trade union president in Pristina, informed the
strikers about an economic recovery program of their construction
company. Tanjug said most workers greeted the news with applause,
but a few taunted Sheku that ``you promised us a lot before but
nothing was realized.''
   The workers protested excessive bureaucracy and organization in
the company without any decision taken on whether to continue the
strike, Tanjug said. The agency said the number of workers on
strike in and around Pristina, capital of Yugoslavia's poorest
region, rose to 4,000 Wednesday.
   About 2,000 textile workers of a textile plant in Djakovica,
another Kosovo town, went on strike a week ago demanding higher
pays before they were accomodated.
   In 1987, according to official estimates, there were more than
1,570 strikes in Yugoslavia involving some 365,000 workers.
</TEXT>
