<HEAD>List of Some of the Most Familiar</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Berlin Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Berlin is credited in reference works as
composing about 1,000 songs. The first published was ``Marie from
Sunny Italy'' in 1907 and the last was ``An Old Fashioned
Wedding,'' written for the 1966 revival of ``Annie Get Your Gun.''
   In between, were such tunes as these:
   ``A Pretty Girl Is Like a Melody,'' ``Alexander's Ragtime
Band,'' ``All Alone,'' ``Always,'' ``Be Careful, It's My Heart,''
``Blue Skies,'' ``Cheek to Cheek,'' ``Doin' What Comes Naturally,''
``Easter Parade,'' ``God Bless America,'' ``Heat Wave,'' ``How Deep
Is the Ocean?'' ``I Left My Heart at the Stage Door Canteen,''
``Isn't This a Lovely Day?'' ``I've Got My Love to Keep Me Warm,''
``Let's Face the Music and Dance,'' ``Let's Have Another Cup of
Coffee,'' ``Marie,'' ``Oh How I Hate To Get Up in the Morning,''
``Play a Simple Melody,'' ``Puttin' on the Ritz,'' ``Remember,''
``Say It Isn't So,'' ``Say It With Music,'' ``The Song is Ended,''
``There's No Business Like Show Business,'' ``They Say That Falling
in Love Is Wonderful,'' ``This Is the Army, Mr. Jones,'' ``Top Hat,
White Tie and Tails,'' ``What'll I Do,'' ``White Christmas,'' ``You
Can't Get a Man With a Gun.''
   Berlin composed music for these shows:
   ``Ziegfeld Follies'' of 1911, 1919, 1920 and 1927; ``Watch Your
Step,'' 1914; ``Stop! Look! Listen!'' 1915; ``The Century Girl,''
1916; ``The Cohan Revue of 1918''; ``Yip Yip Yaphank,'' 1918; ``The
Canary,'' 1918; ``Music Box Revues'' of 1921, 1922, 1923 and 1924;
``The Cocoanuts,'' 1925; ``Face the Music,'' 1932; ``As Thousands
Cheer,'' 1933; ``Louisiana Purchase,'' 1933; ``This Is the Army,''
1942; ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' 1946; ``Miss Liberty,'' 1949; ``Call
Me Madam,'' 1950; ``Mr. President,'' 1962.
   Movie versions of ``Louisiana Purchase,'' ``Annie Get Your Gun''
and ``Call Me Madam'' appeared in 1941, 1950 and 1953,
respectively. Other movies for which Berlin wrote the music
included:
   ``Top Hat,'' 1935; ``Follow the Fleet,'' 1936; ``On the
Avenue,'' 1937; ``Alexander's Ragtime Band,'' 1938; ``Care Free,''
1938; ``Second Fiddle,'' 1939; ``Holiday Inn,'' 1942; ``This Is the
Army,'' 1943; ``Blue Skies,'' 1946; ``Easter Parade,'' 1948;
``Annie Get Your Gun,'' 1950; ``Call Me Madam, 1953; ``White
Christmas,'' 1954; ``There's No Business Like Show Business,'' 1954.
</TEXT>
