<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CPSC-Fireworks     05-11 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CPSC-Fireworks,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Suspends Fireworks Exports After U.S. Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 26 million defective or mislabeled
fireworks have been seized in a federal crackdown that reportedly
has led China to suspend export production of firecrackers.
   More than 100,000 cartons of Chinese fireworks awaiting shipment
were recalled and production of fireworks intended for export to
the United States was halted in April, until quality control can be
improved, sources familiar with the Chinese fireworks industry said
Wednesday.
   The sources spoke on condition they not be identified.
   Zheng Wanchen of the Chinese Embassy in Washington said he had
no information on the report. Wilson W. Mao, head of the importing
company Hop Kee Pyrotechnics Ltd. in Monterey Park, Calif., was out
of town and not available for comment, his office said.
   But officials of the Consumer Product Safety Commission
comfirmed that more than $2 million worth of imported fireworks has
been seized in recent weeks in a joint operation with the U.S.
Customs Service.
   That operation concentrated on imported products arriving at
customs offices in San Francisco, Cleveland, Chicago, Philadelphia,
Baltimore and Charleston, S.C.. the safety commission reported.
   Mislabeling and overloaded fireworks were the most common
problems cited by the agency, which seized more than 15 million
``Thunder Bomb'' firecrackers containing between 72 milligrams and
84 milligrams of powder. Federal law limits firecrackers to 50
milligrams.
   The crackdown doesn't mean there will be no Fourth of July
fireworks, agency officials added. In San Francisco, for example,
some two-thirds of the imported products passed inspection and were
allowed into the country.
   The effort does represent a shift in emphasis from inspecting
retail dealers to trying to stop problems before they are widely
distribued, according to Safety Commission Chairman Terrence M.
Scanlon.
   ``We have taken enforcement of U.S. government safety standards
from the roadside to the dockside in an effort to be more
effective,'' Scanlon said Tuesday in a statement in Cleveland where
he announced ``Midwest Thunder,'' the joint Customs-CPSC operation
in that area.
   The effort combining the work of the two federal agencies will
give taxpayers ``more bang'' for the dollar, said John Mackey, an
aide to Scanlon.
   Officials predicted the effort would lead to the availability
this year of safer firecrackers.
   In 1987 more than 9,000 Americans were injured by fireworks
seriously enough to require hospital treatment, the safty agency
said.
   Seized fireworks can be returned to commerce and sold if the
problem is repaired, such as improving the labeling and warnings,
according to officials. Products that cannot be fixed are
destroyed, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
