<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugLord     05-11 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Lord,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Drug Czar Arrested in NYPD-FBI Raid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man arrested for allegedly running a
multimillion-dollar cocaine operation adopted the lifestyle of a
cocaine kingpin played by Al Pacino in the movie ``Scarface,''
authorities said.
   Thomas Mickens, 24, was taken into custody Tuesday at his
$760,000 house on Long Island by police and FBI agents, Police
Commissioner Benjamin Ward said.
   A silver Rolls-Royce worth $121,000 was parked in the garage at
the Dix Hills house, Ward said. Mickens bought as many as 19 luxury
cars with drug profits, police said.
   Mickens apparently also used neighborhood businesses he owned to
launder money from his cocaine operations in the city and in
Atlantic City, N.J., authorities said.
   Mickens used the name Tony Montana, Pacino's character in the
1983 movie, authorities said.
   ``His favorite movie was `Scarface,''' said Capt. Charles Mattes
of the Queens narcotics squad. ``He tried to model his existence
after that character.''
   Mickens allegedly employed nearly 100 street-level dealers and
pushers in a 2-year-old heroin and cocaine network based in the
borough of Queens but also flourished in Harlem and in Atlantic
City, according to a criminal complaint obtained by U.S. Attorney
Andrew J. Maloney.
   Two locations in Queens and homes in Miami and Atlantic City
were searched. Authorities also seized a bar, a grocery store and a
sporting goods store, all named ``Tony Montana'' and owned by
Mickens.
   Only a small amount of drugs was found during Tuesday's arrests,
Mattes said. Authorities, he added, were mostly looking for records
and documents that would describe Mickens' organization and perhaps
lead to more arrests.
   ``We believe taking this organization down dismantles a major
flow of narcotics into this area,'' Ward said. Mattes described
Mickens' operation as a ``multimillion-dollar organization'' but he
refused to say exactly how much money it made.
   Mickens was not linked to the drug-related violence that led to
the death of police Officer Edward Byrne, who was gunned down Feb.
26 while protecting the home of a witness, Ward said.
   Mickens faces federal charges of conspiracy and possession and
distribution of narcotics. He is being held at the Metropolitan
Correctional Center, pending a bail hearing Thursday, said Charles
Rose, an assistant U.S. attorney in the Eastern District.
   Six other men, believed to be lieutenants in Mickens'
organization, were also picked up Tuesday. All were charged with
conspiracy and possession and distribution of narcotics.
</TEXT>
