<1ST_LINE>u w AM-JedsReunion 1stLd-Writethru a0797 05-11 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jeds Reunion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0797,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allied Soldiers Reminisce Over Life Behind Enemy Lines</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with French Jeds arriving, INSERTS two grafs after
5th graf bgng ``This week.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aging American, British and French comrades
who harbor the often agonizing memories of one of World War II's
most heroic missions gathered Wednesday for probably their last
full reunion, 44 years after they were parachuted behind enemy
lines.
   ``It took some of them this long to find each other, and they
won't let go,'' said Daphne Friele, who was an 18-year-old
secretary in the British intelligence office that trained 279
Americans, Britons and Frenchmen for a mission code-named
``Jedburgh.''
   Records of the operation remained top secret until 1985,
although many of those taking part have told their dramatic stories
of sabotaging German forces and supporting the European resistance.
The specially trained soldiers were dropped in teams of three with
a radio _ scattered across France, Belgium and The Netherlands _ in
advance of the June 6, 1944 Normandy landings.
   Their code name, Mrs. Friele said, comes from the name of a
Scottish town where the term ``Jedburgh justice'' was the rule for
dealing with sheep rustlers: ``hang them first and question them
afterwards.''
   This week, 51 American, 26 French and 18 British survivors of
the Jedburgh unit will meet with President Reagan, receive honors
at the French and British embassies and visit the CIA headquarters
where one of their members, William E. Colby, was director in the
mid-1970s.
   The final group of French veterans arrived Wednesday to shouts
of greetings from their fellow British and American soldiers at
Dulles International Airport.
   French Gen. Roland de Mecquenem of St. Julien Le Concelles said
his memories of the resistance are ``neither sad nor gay. We
experienced the happiness of fulfilling a duty.''
   Mrs. Friele _ she later married an American ``Jed'' who died in
the Korean War and, after the Jeds first reunion in France four
years ago, married another one _ said she has been able to track
down all but two of the original American soldiers in the
operation. For them she has only names and scant detail: Arthur
Gruen and Ian Forbes.
   ``I was 18 and very impressionable, so these people have always
been my heroes, and they always will be,'' said Mrs. Friele, 62,
who has lived in the United States since the war. Her second
husband, Berent E. Friele Jr., 65, of Redding, Conn., like many of
the American Jeds, was also sent into China to aid resistance
against the Japanese.
   Mrs. Friele said life after the war has been difficult for some
of the men because of the intensity of their experiences dodging
enemy forces.
   She said the reunion in France and one in 1985 of American Jeds
have given the men a chance to share experiences, often unpleasant,
that they had rarely talked about. Many had not seen each other
since they were trained in England, she said.
   ``Things that angered them just spilled out,'' she said.
   ``Some couldn't readjust. They became alcoholics and went
through terrible experiences,'' she said.
   But she said many have done very well in the military and
elsewhere. In addition to Colby, former Jeds include retired Army
Maj. Gen. John Singlaub, who has organized a controversial
worldwide effort to support resistance groups against communism,
and internationally known yachtsman Hod Fuller, a retired Marine
general.
   The late columnist Stewart Alsop was a Jed.
   Paul Cyr, 66, of Centreville, Va., said he only found out after
the war that the headquarters of British Special Operations thought
some of their messages were coming from the German Gestapo and so
did not respond to requests for assistance, including arms drops.
   Cyr, who was sent behind enemy lines twice in Europe and later
in China, said his biggest problem was communications.
   ``It could take all day to get the radio into the sidepockets of
a bike and get out into the countryside to send a simple message,''
he said. In France, he said, the mostly French-speaking Americans
operated in villages and towns with Germans all around them.
   The Jeds tell the story of one American who didn't speak French
and injured his back during the jump. He had to spend time in a
German hospital, speaking very little, before a mission was flown
in to rescue him.
   Cyr said he has some horrible memories, including holing up on a
farm with 300 resistance fighters and ending up with only 15
survivors after Germans were led to the scene by a Frenchman.
   Retired Col. Frank Mills of Fairfax, Va., who worked with the
Allied forces in Europe and with the Americans who went to China
but was not a Jed himself, is writing a book about the missions.
   Since the documents were declassified, Mills has spent three
years going through hundreds of boxes stored in the National
Archives.
   He said that despite the obvious danger of the missions, only a
handful of the Jeds were killed.
   ``They were guerrillas. They had to design operations that would
keep them alive,'' he said.
</TEXT>
