<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Paraguay     05-11 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Paraguay,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Cancels Meeting Between Pope And Opposition Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner canceled a meeting between Pope John Paul II and
civilian leaders, including opposition politicians, but a church
group pledged Wednesday to try to hold the meeting anyway.
   The Permanent Episcopal Council said it would search for another
site if the government prevented use of a sports stadium operated
by the Education and Culture Ministry.
   John Paul is scheduled to arrive Monday in Paraguay on the last
stop of his four-nation pilgrimage to South America. The meeting
with about 350 civilian leaders was scheduled Tuesday, May 19.
   The session in Paraguay had been billed as a ``meeting of the
pope with the constructors of society.'' It was intended to bring
the pontiff into contact with a broad mix of civilians, including
peasants, lawyers, religious leader and members of opposition
parties not recognized by the government.
   The invitation of opposition leaders prompted government
criticism. An editorial Sunday in Patria, the daily newspaper of
President Stroessner's ruling Colorado Party, described the meeting
as a ``corrupt assembly.''
   Patria reported Tuesday that government officials, citing
``security reasons,'' notified the pope's local envoy on Monday
that the meeting had been canceled.
   Tensions between the church and government have escalated in the
last year. The church hierarchy has increasingly criticized
Stroessner, in absolute power since 1954, and other government
leaders. It has accused them of repeated civil rights violations.
</TEXT>
