<2ND_LINE>AM-Dead Marriage,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marriage After Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lim Hong Juat and Saw Bee Hong
were married, but both have been dead for many years.
   It all began a few weeks ago, when 78-year-old Foo Ah Heoh,
Lim's mother, was tormented by a recurring dream of her son, who
died 16 years ago at the age of 25.
   In the dream, Lim urged his mother to marry him to a certain
Miss Saw.
   Foo learned that there was a Saw Bee Hong who once lived nearby.
   She went to see Saw's family, who told her that Saw had died in
an accident 15 years ago, when she was 12. But the family said it
had no objections to the marriage.
   On Tuesday, a Chinese temple priest joined in marriage
3-foot-tall paper effigies of the couple.
   Eighty friends and relatives attended the ceremony in the city
of Penang, about 180 miles northwest of Kuala Lumpur, the National
News Agency Bernama reported Wednesday.
   At the wedding, which cost $1,600, the dead newlyweds were
showered with gifts, including a house, a car, a video-cassette
recorder and bedroom furniture _ all made of paper.
