<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Rally,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nancy Reagan Leads Fourth Annual National Rally Against Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 11,000 people cheered first lady
Nancy Reagan as she took the stage at the fourth annual national
``Just Say No'' Walk Against Drugs Rally on Wednesday.
   Initially flanked by two school children, drug-sniffing police
dogs, Snoopy, Yogi Bear and Ronald McDonald, Mrs. Reagan told the
children how proud she was of them.
   ``Saying no to drugs is the biggest decision your can make in
your lives right now,'' she said during the ceremony on the Mall
near the Washington Monument. ``You've made a commitment against
drugs; that is an adult decision and you deserve the adult respect.
   ``And I want you to know that you have my fullest respect, not
to mention affection,'' she said.
   As the honorary chairman of the Just Say No Foundation, Mrs.
Reagan told the crowd of a campaign to get more young people to
pledge to fight drugs when the new school year starts this fall.
   ``I hope you will join in this drive to renew the pledge against
drugs and to get new people to just say no,'' she said.
   Mrs. Reagan's remarks were the highlight of the program hosted
by Tempestt Bledsoe of NBC-TV's ``The Cosby Show'' and Sonny
Melendrez of The Disney Channel's ``You and Me Kid.''
   Among the featured performers was LaToya Jackson, the
international spokeswoman for the ``Just Say No'' movement and
board member of the foundation.
   Ms. Jackson, the sister of superstar Michael Jackson, sang her
``Just Say No'' song while on stage with members of the Halau Hula
Olana's champion hula ensemble from Oahu, Hawaii.
   Most of the children in the program and in the audience were
members of the 15,000 Just Say No Clubs active in schools and young
people's organizations across the nation.
   The clubs are an outgrowth of a commitment Mrs. Reagan made to a
group of school children in Oakland, Calif., in 1984. Since 1986,
the second week of May has been observed as ``Just Say No'' Week,
including local and national walks and rallies on the same day.
</TEXT>
