<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Housing     05-11 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cranston Wants Housing Bill To Be Part of Fall Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation calling for a new national housing
policy should be ready this summer in time to be a major focus of
the presidential and congressional campaigns, Sen. Alan Cranston
said Wednesday.
   The California Democrat, who is chairman of the Senate housing
subcommittee, said he wants all of the presidential and
congressional candidates to make a commitment to the housing
program he has been working on with some of the nation's leading
housing experts for the past 10 months.
   ``We want to have an impact during the campaign so that housing
is discussed not just in general terms with all candidates claiming
to be `friends of housing,''' Cranston said in remarks to a meeting
of the California Association of Realtors.
   He said commitments are necessary ``so they will be more likely
to adopt the policy framework that supporters of housing have
developed.''
   Meanwhile, representatives of the poor urged the House housing
subcommittee to approve legislation to provide for the construction
of 5 million new public housing units and to modernize 1 million
public housing units over a 10-year period.
   Rick Tingling-Clemmons, representing the National Tenants
Organization, urged Congress to appropriate emergency money ``to
begin the immediate restoration, renovation and repair of all
existing public housing units.''
   He said the tenants' organization also wants Congress to pass
the so-called Jesse Gray Housing Act, named for the 1969 founder of
the tenants organization, to provide for additional public housing.
   Cranston, the Senate's second-ranking Democrat, said he hopes to
have the Senate Banking Committee, which oversees housing
legislation, approve his legislation by Aug. 15 when Congress
recesses for the summer.
   ``We will move it as far as possible through Congress this
year,'' he told the realtors, ``but I suspect we will have to wait
for a new administration to enact it.''
   He said major pieces of the bill should be ready to be announced
in June and should be introduced in the Senate and House in July.
   ``We should set clear, realistic goals that can be accomplished,
say, by the year 2000,'' Cranston said. ``Even if the initial steps
must be smaller than many would like, we can show that they are the
right steps and that they are part of a sustainable strategy.''
</TEXT>
