<HEAD>Spence Taken Off Respirator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., who underwent a
double lung transplant last weekend, was removed from a respirator
Wednesday and ``is making steady progress,'' officials said.
   ``There are no signs of rejection as yet,'' said Barbara Austin,
a spokeswoman at the University of Mississippi Medical Center.
``His lungs are oxygenating well and there is a good possibility he
may be removed from the intensive care unit on Thursday.''
   The rare operation was performed Friday night, and Spence
continues to take drugs to ward off rejection of the new organs,
which came from an 18-year-old motorcycle accident victim from
Texas, hospital officials said.
   A lung specialist determined Spence suffered from a severe form
of non-hereditary emphysema, Austin said.
   ``The congressman is in good spirits _ very upbeat,'' she said.
``He was asking for hot soup early Wednesday.''
