<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     05-11 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer, Five Instructors Charged in Recruit's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The officer in charge of the Navy rescue
swimmer school and five instructors face military charges in a
recruit's death at Pensacola Naval Air Station, the Navy said.
   Lee William Mirecki, 19, died March 2 shortly after he was
pulled from a pool at Naval Aviation Schools Command.
   Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, the school's top officer, was charged
with dereliction of duty, Rear Adm. David R. Morris, chief of Naval
Air Training in Corpus Christi, Texas, said in a statement Tuesday.
   Petty Officers Richard E. Blevins, David J. Smith, Michael W.
Combe, Frankie E. Deaton and John W. Zelenock were charged with
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy to commit battery.
   Mirecki died after swimming exercises in the rescue school
program that trains Navy air crew personnel for search and rescue
missions.
   Initially, the Navy said Mirecki died of natural causes. But
Mirecki's classmates contacted news media and his family to say he
was treated unusually harshly the day he died.
   Mirecki's sister, Lyn Johansen, said recruits told her Mirecki
was having trouble performing a difficult exercise known as
``sharks and daisies,'' in which instructors jump on top of
students in the water to test their rescue abilities.
   ``The others were told to get out, line up by the pool with
their backs to the water, sing the National Anthem and do exercises
while they dealt with Lee individually,'' she said.
   The recruits said Mirecki called for help, got out of the pool
once, asked instructors to allow him to drop the class but was
pulled back into the pool.
   ``After their exercises, they turned around to see Lee's limp,
blue body being pulled from the water,'' Mrs. Johansen said she was
told.
   Rescue workers began cardiopulmonary resuscitation, she said.
   Morris will appoint an investigating officer to determine
whether the evidence warrants referring the charges to a
court-martial or dropping them.
   If convicted, Torchia faces a maximum penalty of punitive
dismissal from the Navy and three months' confinement; the
instructors face a maximum penalty of dismissal and three years'
confinement.
</TEXT>
