<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-VotingBarriers     05-11 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Voting Barriers,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Poor, Minorities Disenfranchised By Voting Barriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discriminatory voter registration procedures
are disenfranchising the poor, minority and disabled citizens
throughout the country, directors of a private study said Wednesday.
   Among the practices are arbitrary registration hours,
inconvenient registration locations, ``mysterious purging of voters
without notice, denial of registration before an election,'' said a
statement from Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who is the author of
legislation to correct such practices.
   The Citizens Commission on Civil Rights in hearings in New York,
Atlanta and Phoenix in 1984 and 1985 ``documented numerous examples
of discrimintory practices,'' the group said.
   The commission also reviewed the registration systems in each
state and the historical voting and registration practices. The
report said in most states, local officials have ``wide
discretion'' in setting times, places and conditions for people to
register to vote.
   ``This discretion is often is exercised in ways which establish
barriers to registration and voting,'' said the report.
   The restrictive practices ``have a disproportionately adverse
effect on low-income, minority and disabled citizens,'' the report
said. It cited the following examples:
   _ Limited registration sites affect poor people who don't own
cars.
   _ Limited hours for registration affect working people who can't
get away from their jobs.
   _ Many registration sites are inaccessible to the disabled.
   _ Failure to provide bilingual assistance affects low-income
citizens and non-English speaking minorities.
   The Voting Rights Act of 1965 has eliminated the most blatant
discrimination practices, but ``remnants of the old systems of
disenfranchisement persist,'' the report said.
   Among the specific problems are refusal by local officials to
designate sites in black commuinities for mobile registration
units; requirement of excessive identification from black
applicants; ``undue scrutiny'' of Hispanics and Asian-Americans to
determine their citizenship; sites ``that require extraordinarily
long trips'' and dual registration requirements for tribal and
state elections for Native Americans.
   The commission recommended legislation to permit registration by
mail, election-day registration, and a congressional investigation
into denial of the right to vote for homeless people.
   Cranston's bill, pending in Senate committee, and a companion
House bill by Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., generally parallels those
recommendations.
   The commission is sending a copy of its report to Congress, the
White House and the presidential candidates, seeking support for
its proposals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-UnionAds     05-11 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Union Ads,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO Ad Campaign Aimed at Updating Union Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO on Wednesday said a new $13
million broadcast advertising campaign was designed to show that
unions, like their workers, are interested in fairness, justice and
life outside the job.
   The ads, which all end with a chorus singing ``America works
best when we say union yes,'' have begun appearing on the
television networks and in 13 local markets. The 30-second spots
are expected to reach more than nine out of 10 of all American
homes at least four times.
   Radio spots will be aired as well, including one that urges
listeners to ask Congress to override President Reagan's expected
veto of the trade legislation. Unions have been pushing a provision
of the bill requiring mandatory notice of plant closings for large
companies.
   At a closed-circuit TV news conference to the 13 cities where
the TV ads will be shown, AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said
``the labor movement has a long, well-documented record of fighting
for the rights and the standard of living of working Americans. But
in spite of that, there are still many Americans who have serious
misconceptions about what unions do and about whether or not they
are necessary in today's work place.''
   ``The goal of `Union Yes,''' he said, ``is to talk directly with
American workers about the value of unions in the work place today.
One of the best ways to do that now is through television.''
   Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of America,
told reporters in Washington that the ads ``fill a need to let the
population at large know what the trade union movement stands for.''
   He said many Americans have ``a stereotype of unions and union
members. They see a heavyset fellow smoking a cigar and wearing a
$500 suit.''
   One commercial focuses on women, with a woman saying unions have
ensured fairness in promotions. Another, obviously pregnant, woman
says that because of unions she will be able to take time off to
have her baby and come back to a job.
   The first phase of the ad campaign runs through mid-June. The
second phase picks up on Labor Day in September. The campaign,
which is paid for with union dues, is expected to last two years.
   The ads will star actors Jack Lemmon, Tyne Daly and Howard
Hesseman.
   Local TV ads will run during May and June in New York, Los
Angeles, Chicago, Philadelphia, San Francisco, Boston, Detroit,
Cleveland, Pittsburgh, Washington, Atlanta, Nashville, Tenn., and
Orlando, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
