<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     05-11 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Communist Party to Debate New Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist officials under pressure to
resolve the country's rising economic and political turmoil said
Wednesday that a party conference will grapple next week with
changes in national leadership.
   Premier Karoly Grosz has said the meeting could lead to
departure of party leader Janos Kadar.
   Critics of the 75-year-old leader, who has headed the party
since 1956 when the Kremlin put down an anti-Soviet revolt, blame
him for Hungary's economic problems and for resisting reform.
   A communique published Wednesday in the state-run media after a
one-day meeting of the Communist Party's Central Committee said it
is ``necessary to renew the party's leading bodies.'' It proposed
that a conference next week elect a new Committee. Its more than
100 members make key policy decisions for the party.
   Wednesday's statement said the Central Committee on Tuesday
approved a draft policy document for debate at the conference.
   The original document was written by Kadar, but the communique
did not make clear whether changes had been made to incorporate
complaints from critics inside and outside the party that it did
not go far enough with reform.
   In the version published last month, the Communist Party
accepted blame for the country's economic woes and offered some
political reforms, such as multicandidate elections and limited
terms in party office.
   But critics said it stopped far short of allowing genuine
political pluralism, an issue hotly debated among the nation's
880,000 Communists and in the state-run media for the past year.
   Austerity measures imposed to curb a gross foreign debt of $17
billion have resulted in inflation of more than 15 percent this
year and prompted widespread grumbling from citizens and the
official trade unions about the government program.
   The communique on Wednesday said leaders at Tuesday's meeting
also debated personnel changes and formed a special committee to
deal with such matters at the three-day conference opening May 20.
But it did not reveal who made the report on personnel matters or
say who will be on the committee.
   Western diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
they expected some changes in membership of the Central Committee
at next week's conference. They described Tuesday's decisions as a
modest step forward in dealing with the mounting political and
economic crisis.
   Communist party leaders, including Kadar and Grosz, have said in
recent months they would like the party to retreat from day-to-day
adminstrative duties and concentrate on ideological and political
leadership of the country.
   Grosz has also declared readiness for dialogue with any
Hungarian who is not opposed to socialism and Budapest's alliance
with the Soviet Union.
   Grosz, a leading contender to succeed Kadar as party chief, has
said the political future of the party leader may be up for debate
at next week's conference.
   ``In the event that some 1,000 delegates attending the
conference decide that personnel changes are necessary, and if
these changes include the person of Janos Kadar, he will accept the
decision,'' Grosz told reporters while in Britain last week.
   Kadar has said he would step down if asked, but he has shown
little sign of wanting to do so.
   Hungarians will watch closely to see whether outspoken reformers
move up or down in party rankings when the conference ends with
another Central Committee meeting May 22.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
