<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Takeovers-Pensions     05-11 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Takeovers-Pensions,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Department To Monitor Pressures On Pension Fund Managers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department launched an effort
Wednesday to ensure that pension fund managers who control a
growing percentage of the nation's corporate stock are free from
improper pressures in takeover battles.
   Over the next several months, department investigators will be
monitoring how selected investment managers vote on takeover
defenses and other issues that affect the value of stock, according
to David M. Walker, assistant secretary of labor.
   The department's Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration
issued guidelines in February saying pension fund investment
managers should keep the interests of the members of the fund in
mind when voting proxies for shares in their care. The enforcement
project is intended to see if the guidelines are being followed.
   ``We're not trying to come out pro-corporate management or pro
any other party. The important thing is that pension funds not be
viewed as tools or pawns of corporate management or any other
party,'' Walker said.
   There has been growing concern in recent years that investment
managers have been subject to pressure from parties trying to block
takeovers, such as corporate managers or union leaders, who have
the ability to add to or take away from a fund manager's business.
   ``We want to make sure there's not undue influence, improper
influence, that would adversely affect the economic interests of
the plan,'' Walker said.
   If the enforcement project turns up violations, investment
managers could be subject to civil enforcement proceedings, Walker
said, adding, ``If the plan suffers an economic loss ... then there
is personal liability.''
   Walker said he did not know how much abuse exists. However, a
survey released in September by the Employee Benefit Research
Institute, a Washington-based, non-partisan research organization,
showed that 65 percent of pension fund investment managers reported
being pressured at least once in voting on corporate takeovers.
   ``The stakes are high in this area for a lot of parties. There's
a great potential for abuse and we hear a lot of assertions. ...
We're trying to do a little bit of preventive medicine ... before
abuse becomes widespread,'' Walker said.
   The question of improper influence over fund managers has become
more important as more companies call on shareholders to adopt
poison pills and other measures designed to thwart corporate
raiders.
   Pension funds controlled 24 percent of the nation's stock last
year, up from 19 percent in 1980 and 10 percent in 1970. But, the
percentages are significantly higher for stocks traded on the New
York Stock Exchange, Walker said, and pension funds own 60 percent
of some companies, he said.
   The department estimates by the year 2000, pension funds are
likely to control half the stock in all U.S. companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
