<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Myrtle Beach may have been rated the
East Coast's tackiest tourist spot, but the owner of a miniature
golf course sporting pink flamingo and gorilla statues says such
attractions represent good, clean fun.
   The book, ``The Worst of Everything,'' also rates Los Angeles
the tackiest vacation spot in the West and gives Panama City, Fla.,
that distinction for the Gulf Coast.
   Al Tirrell, owner of Jungle Golf, called the tacky label ``the
most outrageous lies I've ever heard.''
   ``It's a family beach. We're newer, we're cleaner, Tirrell said.
   Vacationer Charlie Jolley, of Mars Hill, N.C., was sympathetic.
``I'd much rather see the plain beach, but you don't come here
expecting it all to be coconut palms,'' Jolley said Tuesday.
   The book's author, Don Lessem, asked authorities in dozens of
fields for their opinions on the worst.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LUTHERVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school principal paid off
an unusual bet with pupils by donning a tuxedo and bow-tie and
eating a lunch of pizza and cola atop the school's sun-drenched
roof.
   Below, on the school grounds of Lutherville-Timonium Elementary
School, 500 pupils shouted triumphantly, ``Eat, eat, eat.''
   The scene Tuesday was an odd victory celebration for the
students, who were challenged at the beginning of the school year
by principal Fred Brown to read 1 million pages by the end of the
school year.
   The prospect of seeing him eat lunch on the roof of the school
was the reward.
   ``We're not sure whether it (Brown's offer) was a flip remark,''
said librarian Doris Glotzbach. ``But we picked up on it and
wouldn't let it go.''
   There were doubts about whether the students could get through
enough books to reach the goal, but the chance of putting Brown on
the roof apparently proved incentive enough.
   ``It did the job as far as motivating students to read,'' said
fifth-grade teacher Dennis Kimmel. ``They were carrying around
books with them all the time.''
</TEXT>
