<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RattlesRecall     05-11 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rattles Recall,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Baby Rattles, One Puzzle Game Recalled Over Choking Hazard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission
announced Wednesday the recall of two brands of baby rattles and a
puzzle game because they present a choking hazard to infants.
   The commission said Li Peng Enterprises Inc. of Los Angeles
withdrew its Rainbow Bell rattle, and Toys-R-Us of Rochelle Park,
N.J., withdrew its Crib Pals Shake and Twist Baby Rattle and its
Colorforms Story Book Puzzle.
   The Rainbow rattles, item CT-8013, are plastic with a handle
made of what appears to be beads at one end and four bell-shaped
noise makers in a circle at the other end.
   The commission said it did not know of any injuries caused by
the rattles, but said they posed a choking hazard because the
handle is small enough to enter a child's mouth and can reach the
back of the throat.
   About 86,400 were sold between June 1987 and August 1987 for
$2.85.
   The Crib Pals Shake and Twist Baby Rattles, No. 098132, are 5{
inches by 1} inches and have a ball containing liquid and six
colored pellets. The commission said the rattle can break during
use and the pieces present a potential choking hazard, although no
injuries or deaths have been reported. Approximately 24,000 were
sold from March 1986 to December 1987 through Toys-R-Us stores for
$1.48.
   The Colorforms No. 150 Story Book Puzzles have five wooden
pieces and come in two models, the Pinky Brite Bear and the Rosy
Brite Bear. Some pieces are small enough to present a choking
hazard, the commission said, although no injuries had been reported.
   About 12,000 puzzles were sold from September 1986 to December
1987 through Toys-R-Us for $5.97.
</TEXT>
