<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Kansas     05-11 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Kansas,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaign Challenges Delegate Split in Kansas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT TRUELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of Jesse Jackson say the
Democratic presidential candidate was shortchanged in delegates he
received at Kansas district conventions.
   Jackson backers filed a formal challenge to the delegate
selection process last week, as state party officials prepared for
a state Democratic committee meeting on Saturday to choose the last
of Kansas' delegates to the Democratic National Convention in July
in Atlanta.
   Supporters say Jackson should have been allocated 12 national
delegates instead of the seven he received, based on the results of
county caucuses March 19.
   They also say Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis should have 10
delegates instead of 12, and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. should have two
instead of five. The number of uncommitted delegates would remain
at two under the challenge.
   A total of 26 national delegates was selected April 22 at
congressional district conventions.
   Jackson supporters also complain that the way delegates are
chosen in Kansas is confusing and unduly complicated.
   ``It's an unfair process,'' said Charles Meek, state coordinator
for the Jackson campaign. ``When you say `caucus' to the average
person, they say, `What do you mean?' All we're asking for is what
is fair.''
   ``We're still formulating an answer to the challenge,'' said Joe
Scranton, executive director of the Kansas Democratic Party. ``We
don't know what that answer will be yet.''
   The state party has until May 24 to rule on the Jackson
challenge.
   Delegates are selected to the national convention based on a
process that started with 117 local caucuses, which chose the
people who vote at the district conventions.
   The district conventions then selected 26 national delegates
from the five congressional districts. The third and final step is
the selection of 13 delegates at the state committee meeting. Those
delegates will be chosen based on the results of the district
conventions, with seven going to Dukakis and three each to Jackson
and Gore.
   Bill Beachy, former state party executive director who is acting
as a consultant to the Jackson campaign in the challenge, said the
26 national delegates selected at the district conventions should
accurately reflect the results of the local caucuses under a party
rule.
   That rule was not followed, he said.
   Candidates must receive at least 15 percent of the caucus votes
before they can receive any delegates, according to the rules.
Beachy says people were allowed to re-group at the district
conventions and previously uncommitted delegates threw in with
either Dukakis or Gore.
   Although Gore did not break the 15 percent threshold in the
local caucuses in three congressional districts, he received one
delegate from each of those districts after picking up uncommitted
delegates at the district conventions.
   ``They shouldn't be allowed to re-group after the caucuses,''
Beachy said. ``The caucuses set what the (delegate) allocations
should be.''
   Scranton acknowledged there is a difference of opinion in
interpretation of party rules.
   He also joined Jackson supporters in their complaints about the
complicated process.
   ``Anyone who has tried to administer this, from the county
selection on up to the national selection, is painfully aware of
how complicated it is,'' Scranton said.
</TEXT>
