<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NakedProsecutor     05-11 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Naked Prosecutor,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Half-Clothed' Prosecutor Cleared of Car Chase Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor who police said was naked
from the waist down when they pulled her car over after a
high-speed chase was cleared of trying to outrun the officers.
   Former Assistant State Attorney Jan Bamping, 32, who resigned
her post after publicity about the incident, was cleared Tuesday of
fleeing to elude an officer, the only criminal charge against her.
She pleaded guilty to two non-criminal traffic charges and was
fined $400.
   ``I have paid for this more than I ever should have, I think,''
she said after Tuesday's hearing.
   On March 20, Bradenton Beach police said they spotted Ms.
Bamping _ accompanied by prosecutor Jerry Blevins, who also later
resigned _ pass improperly, and tried to pull her over.
   The officers claimed she fled at up to 90 mph, then turned
belligerent when police caught up with her and asked her why she
was semi-nude.
   They accused her of threatening them by using the name of
Manatee County Judge Walter Talley and showing her state attorney
badge.
   Ms. Bamping denied Tuesday that she was partly naked. She said
she was wearing a knee-length shirt at the time.
   ``I was not partially clothed. I was not fleeing. I was polite.
I never used Judge Talley's name. I did not threaten them,'' she
said.
   She was cleared of the misdemeanor flight charge in part because
the officers never mentioned a high-speed chase in taped radio
conversations and did not request assistance, as is usual in such
cases.
   Her former boss, State Attorney Frank Schaub, refused to discuss
the case in detail, but said Tuesday ``I cannot reappoint her.''
   Ms. Bamping said she plans to stay in Florida.
</TEXT>
