<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MatchingFunds     05-11 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Matching Funds,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FEC Certifies Another $1.7 Million For Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission on Wednesday
certified another $1.7 million in federal matching funds to
presidential candidates.
   That brings to $54.5 million the total that has been passed out
so far to 15 candidates, most of whom are now out of the race.
   After a candidate drops out, the individual may still receive
matching funds to cover debts and winding down costs.
   To be eligible for matching funds a candiate must raise $100,000
privately in sums of $250 or less across 20 states. The Federal
Treasury thereafter matches each contribution of $250 or less.
   The amounts approved Wednesday followed by the total the
candidates have received are:
   Bruce Babbitt, Democrat, $49,325, $985,319.
   Vice President George Bush, Republican, $0.0, $8 million.
   Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., $0.0, $7.2 million.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, Democrat, $583,678, $7.4
million.
   Pete du Pont, Republican, $0.0, $2.5 million.
   Lenora B. Fulani, independent, $65,862, $446,359.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., $0.0, $2.7 million.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., $270,847, $3.2 million.
   Alexander Haig, Republican, $18,667, $514,294.
   Gary Hart, Democrat, $0.0, $1.1 million.
   Jesse Jackson, Democrat, $513,292, $3.3 million.
   Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., $0.0, $5 million.
   Lyndon LaRouche, Democrat, $0.0, $607,460.
   Pat Robertson, Republican, $0.0, $8.6 million.
