<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IndianChildren     05-11 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indian Children,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hodel Attacks `Pure Racism' in Bill on Indian Adoption and Custody
Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel on
Wednesday attacked a bill to amend Indian adoption and child
custody laws, saying it contains provisions that smack of ``pure
racism.''
   Hodel wrote Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, chairman of the
Select Committee on Indian Affairs, that he was ``extremely
alarmed'' about some portions of the bill.
   Assistant Interior Secretary Ross Swimmer, a former principal
chief of the Cherokee Nation who is in charge of Indian affairs,
asked the committee to hold up action on the bill until the
department could propose a substitute.
   Hodel said one provision of the bill gives parents no right to
object to a tribe's attempt to transfer custody or adoption cases
from state to tribal court unless the objection is ``consistent
with the best interests of the child as an Indian.''
   ``The provision ignores all other aspects of the child's status
as a human being. That, in my view, is pure racism,'' Hodel said.
   Current law permits tribes to claim jurisdiction in adoption and
custody cases only for children of enrolled members, but the bill
would extend that jurisdiction to children whose ``parents and
other ancestors of the child may have had no connection with the
tribe, perhaps for years or even generations,'' Hodel said.
   In his testimony at a hearing of the committee, Swimmer said,
``We do not believe that Indian parents and their children should
have to return to the reservation of their tribe, which is often in
another state, for a court proceeding concerning the child.''
   ``We strongly oppose the expansion of the definition of Indian
child and recommend that the definition should not only contain a
membership requirement but also that the domicile of the
birthparent or parents is in Indian country,'' Swimmer said.
   If the family does not live in Indian country _ on a reservation
_ then state courts should have jurisdiction, following certain
guidelines of federal law for placement of children in foster homes
and adoptions ``unless the best interest of the child requires a
different placement,'' Swimmer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
