<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZeroTolerance     05-11 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zero Tolerance,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Still Detains Second Yacht Seized for Drugs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Includes information from AM-BRF--Avianca Seizure, a0828.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second luxury yacht seized for carrying tiny
amounts of drugs remained in U.S. Customs custody Wednesday, as the
crackdown under the new ``zero tolerance'' policy continued.
   And a jetliner owned by Colombia's Avianca Airlines was seized
Wednesday following the investigation that began when cocaine was
found aboard it.
   The seizures come a day after the $2.5 million Ark Royal was
allowed to sail away following payment of a fine.
   The $600,000 Ms. Mindy, a boat used to entertain customers of
North Miami's Cigarette Racing Team, was boarded Monday as it
returned from the Bahamas and docked in Port Salerno.
   A search by Customs agents turned up cocaine residue on a dollar
bill and traces of marijuana in a plastic bag.
   ``It's simply being detained and checked right now for
narcotics, and a determination will be made later'' whether to
confiscate the ship, Customs spokesman Michael Sheehan said
Wednesday.
   Neither the ship's captain, Lewis Shaver, nor his unidentified
first mate, who were the only people aboard the boat registered out
of Orange Beach, Ala., were charged with drug possession.
   Sheehan said the plane's seizure also was ``consistent with zero
tolerance.''
   The new, tough policy allows the confiscation of a boat, plane
or other conveyance if it carries any amount of drugs, no matter
how small.
   The plane's seizure was based on a 35.8-pound cocaine shipment
found March 27, Sheehan said, adding that the delay was to allow
for a full investigation.
   Avianca has a right to appeal the process by petitioning the
government for release of the plane, Sheehan said.
   Since October 1986 Customs has made 10 seizures aboard Avianca
planes, many of them in flower shipments, for a total of 1,000
pounds of cocaine.
   The Ark Royal, seized under the get-tough rule, was held for
three days after the Coast Guard found some marijuana seeds and
stems in a trash can and a drawer Saturday.
   But the 133-foot vessel, complete with hot tubs and a grand
piano, was released Tuesday afternoon when Michael Rogerson,
president of the California-based company that owns the boat, paid
a $1,600 fine.
   Fewer than 10 percent of vessels seized by the government are
ever returned to owners. The Ark Royal was in that minority because
its owner moved swiftly and filed a convincing petition, Customs
officials said.
</TEXT>
