<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0787,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uprising Leaders Call For More Protests</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with Palestinian death, other dvpts</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underground leaders in the occupied lands urged
Palestinians on Wednesday to ``burn the earth with fire and anger''
in continued rebellion.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the uprising has the same
goals as Palestinian ``terror organizations,'' and declared that
``terror must be met by force.''
   Doctors at Ramallah Hospital in the West Bank said a 19-year-old
Arab died of gunshot wounds suffered in a clash with Israeli
soldiers last month in a village near Bethlehem.
   An army spokesman said reports of the death were being
investigated. It would bring to at least 186 the number of
Palestinians killed in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip since Palestinian riots began Dec. 8.
   Instructions for more Arab strikes, boycotts and other
resistance appeared in a new underground leaflet. It was
distributed as soldiers rounded up at least 11 journalists and
other community leaders in overnight raids.
   ``Let's burn the earth with fire and anger under the feet of the
occupation,'' the leaflet said. ``Painful blows should be inflicted
against the occupation soldiers and policemen and the
collaborators.''
   The bulletin was the 16th from the United Leadership of the
Uprising in five months of rebellion among the 1.5 million
Palestinians in the occupied territories, which Israel captured
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war.
   It said the leadership ``calls for a complete boycott of the
Zionists and asks the people to ready themselves for civil
disobedience by storing food in houses, enough for at least a
month.''
   Police spokesman Alex Lapidoth in Jerusalem said more than 2,000
extra officers were ordered deployed in the Holy City from Thursday
through early next week.
   He said they were needed to handle anticipated Arab protests
this weekend at the end of the Moslem feast of Ramadan and on
Sunday, Jerusalem Day, when Israelis celebrate the 21st anniversary
of city's reunification.
   The leaflet ordered demonstrations on Friday the Moslem sabbath,
a ``day of anger'' and general strike Sunday and a march by
teachers to protest the closing of Palestinian schools.
   Rabin told a meeting of B'nai B'rith leaders from around the
world the uprising has ``the same political goals ... that the
Palestinian terror organizations try to achieve by terror and
atrocities.''
   ``Terror must be met by force,'' he said. ``Any giving in to
violence will invite more violence, terror and the increasing
danger of war.''
   He defended the use of force to put down the revolt, saying
soldiers and police acted within the limits of Israeli law.
   ``I know that you have seen television day and night, all the
stories of confrontation between civilians and the military,'' he
said. ``I will not deny it. This is what we have to do.''
   In the West Bank village of Qabatiyeh, 47 Palestinians were
charged with manslaughter in the lynching death of an Arab man
accused of collaborating with Israeli authorities, Israel radio
reported.
   Mohammed Id Sakanda was dragged from his home and hanged from an
electricity pole in February.
   Israeli soldiers closed the main vegetable market in Hebron and
used loudspeakers to order merchants there and in other towns to
keep their shops closed in the morning, when leaders of the
uprising have told them to open.
   A struggle between the army and Palestinian leadership over when
stores will close and open has continued for months.
</TEXT>
