<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AssassinationPlot     05-11 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Assassination Plot,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uncover Plot To Assassinate Cisneros</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Libertarian congressional
candidate was accused of trying to hire a ``patriotic'' assassin to
kill Mayor Henry Cisneros ``to make a statement,'' authorities said
Wednesday.
   Parker E. Abell, 74, a tax protester who claims to be head of a
political extremist group called the American Patriots, was held
without bail in the Bexar County Jail on charges of solicitation of
capital murder.
   Abell, who was under surveillance for about a month, was
arrested Tuesday after agreeing to pay an undercover officer $5,000
to kill Cisneros, District Attorney Fred Rodriguez said.
   ``He was doing it to make a statement. He wanted to get
publicity,'' Rodriguez said. ``It wasn't a spur-of-the-moment
thing. It was thought out. He is firm in his convictions and
somehow or another he wanted a hitman with the same resolve, the
same philsophy.
   ``He just didn't want anybody. He wanted a patriot to carry out
the execution,'' said Rodriguez, who met with the mayor Wednesday
to discuss the threat.
   Cisneros, 40, a four-term mayor and former president of the
National League of Cities, said he was not getting additional
protection and joked that he was insulted he was worth only $5,000.
   ``I'm going about the business of San Antonio and this is not
going to dissuade me,'' Cisneros said.
   Abell, a resident of Natalia, 18 miles east of San Antonio,
mentioned other possible targets, including State Comptroller Bob
Bullock, before deciding on Cisneros, the prosecutor said.
   ``Bullock's name was mentioned ... but for whatever reason,
Bullock being out of town, not enough name ID, he settled on Henry
Cisneros,'' Rodriguez said.
   Officers arrested Abell at a supermarket pay phone. In his car
were a .22-caliber rifle and ``execution warrants'' issued by the
``Sovereign Court of the People,'' police said.
   The warrants contained blanks for names of public officials to
be assassinated.
   ``The above-named traitor or traitors are to be executed on
sight,'' read the warrants. ``Each accused has given public proof
of guilt beyond reasonable doubt that he or she is a traitor to the
people of the United States and the United States Constitution.''
   Rodriguez said the investigation began about a month ago after
Internal Revenue Service officials contacted his office, saying an
IRS undercover agent had talked to Abell, who wanted to assassinate
a public official.
   An undercover officer later talked to Abell on the telephone
several times and in person for the first time Tuesday, Rodriguez
said.
   Abell was a Libertarian candidate for the 23rd Congressional
District seat in 1982. More recently, he and several members of his
group picketed the courthouse to protest the grand jury system,
officials said.
   ``He said his group was small to avoid dissension among the
troops,'' said Assistant District Attorney Skip Atwell, head of the
special crimes unit.
   Gary Johnson, secretary of the Libertarian Party of Texas, said
Abell's affiliation with the party ended in 1985.
   ``Our philosophy is to live and let live and, politically, we
would like to see as little government as possible,'' Johnson said,
``but we don't want to do this through violent means.''
</TEXT>
