<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-11 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain In Texas, Hail in Florida, Maryland and Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms dumped rain in Texas and pelted Florida, Maryland
and Pennsylvania with hail Wednesday, while rain dampened much of
New York and New England.
   Sunny skies prevailed from the south Atlantic and Gulf Coast
states across the Ohio, Mississippi and Tennessee valleys to
portions of the northern and central Plains. Skies were also sunny
from the Rockies to the West Coast.
   Up to 2 inches of rain fell in parts of southwest Texas, causing
some local flooding. A severe thunderstorm watch was in effect for
a large part of southern Texas.
   The storms produced hail between Waldo and Green Cove Springs in
northern Florida and pea- to marble-size hail in central Maryland
and eastern Pennsylvania.
   Rain was widespread from eastern New York to most of New
England. The only section of New England to escape rain was
northern Maine.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 1.38 inches at San Angelo, Texas; 0.49 inch at Midland,
Texas; 0.47 inch at Bridgheport, Conn., and 0.46 inch at Hartford,
Conn.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 43 degrees at Grand
Marais, Minn., to 104 at Thermal, Calif. The nation's morning low
was 16 at Gunnison, Colo.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern and eastern Texas to southern Mississippi; scattered
showers over the Great Lakes, northern New York and northern
Vermont; rain over parts of Washington and Oregon, and sunshine
over most of the remainder of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 70s and 80s across
most of the nation, with readings in the 60s in New England and New
York, in the 50s and 60s from Michigan to eastern Minnesota, and in
the 90s to near 105 in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
