<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Robertson 1stLd-Writethru a0874 05-11 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0874,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson To Drop Out Of Presidential Race, Likely to Return to
CBN</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with Robertson campaign saying he
suspending campaign, SUBS 6 grafs for 5th graf pvs, bgng: The
former</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson announced Wednesday that he
would halt his Republican presidential race next week, and said in
a newspaper inerview that he will likely return to his financially
ailing Christian Broadcasting Network.
   Barbara Gattullo, a spokeswoman for Americans for Robertson,
said the decision to return to CBN is ``not set in stone, but the
important thing is whether or not he returns to CBN, he will
continue to be involved in politics.''
   She said Robertson would file papers shortly with the Federal
Election Commission for a new political action committee _
Americans for the Republic.
   Robertson himself, speaking to reporters outside the White
House, endorsed Vice President George Bush, who already had the GOP
nomination well in hand.
   The former television evangelist said he would formally withdraw
from the race Monday.
   ``I will be making that official on Monday, as a candidate,
because the race now is over and the people that I wanted to bring
through the process are pretty much home now in relation to their
races,'' he responded when asked if he were withdrawing.
   But an aide, Richard Pinsky, later described Robertson's planned
move as a suspension, rather than a withdrawal.
   Asked whether he would be releasing his delegates, Robertson
responded: ``Well, of course, I will be releasing them.''
   ``Many of them were not really bound to me because in the
caucuses, it has to do with their own preferences. However, the
procedures go on the first ballot, we want to make sure that
there's a unanimous vote for George Bush,'' Robertson told
reporters.
   Pinsky later said Robertson would release the delegates, but not
immediately.
   Meanwhile, in an interview published in The Virginian-Pilot &
The Ledger-Star of Norfolk, Robertson said he likely would return
to the Christian Broadcasting Network, which he founded nearly 30
years ago, as chief executive officer, a job his son now holds.
   ``I don't have a comment to make,'' said CBN spokesman Benton
Miller. ``None of the staff or I ... have been provided any
information by him at this point concerning what his future plans
are.''
   Since 1967 Robertson had co-anchored the ``700 Club'' program
that is the heart of the network in terms of viewership and fund
raising. He left the program in 1986 to organize his presidential
campaign, and in September 1987 resigned both as the network's
chief executive officer and as a pastor in the Southern Baptist
church to run for office.
   The network quickly reported a big drop in revenue and began
laying off personnel. At the time, spokesmen refused to blame
Robertson's political ambitions for the shortfall.
   In March, CBN announced it faced a deficit of $500,000 for the
month, and sent out pleas for more donations.
   ``I did not realize that my personal presence on the `700 Club'
was as important as it is to the audience,'' Robertson told the
newspaper.
   His return was seen as both a political and economic necessity
by several experts.
   ``He needs to shore up his base,'' said one, Larry Sabato, a
University of Virginia political scientist and longtime Robertson
watcher. ``This campaign in the later stages has been injurious to
that base. Such severe setbacks as he has suffered have shaken even
his staunchest supporters.''
   Robertson, who has spent over $22 million on his campaign, has
but 46 delegates to the national convention, while Bush has more
than 1,300. Robertson finished third to Bush and Sen. Bob Dole in
most of the early primaries.
   Ms. Gattullo said the new political action committee will raise
money and train conservative Christians who want to become involved
in the political process. The staff of Americans for Robertson
would switch to the new PAC, keeping the same offices in Virginia,
she said.
   The new PAC has a purpose similar in some ways to Robertson's
now-defunct Freedom Council, which had tax-exempt status before it
folded in 1986 after Americans for Robertson was incorporated.
Critics challenged the council as being merely a front for
Robertson's then-undeclared campaign, and it is being investigated
along with CBN and Americans for Robertson by the Internal Revenue
Service.
   Unlike the council, Americans for the Republic will actively
support candidates, Ms. Gattullo said.
</TEXT>
