<1ST_LINE>b w AM-AlohaPilots 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aloha Pilots, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0813,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aloha Pilots Describe In-Flight Ordeal With Gaping Hole in
Fuselage</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout to UPDATE with FAA tape recording</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilots of Aloha Flight 243 knew they had
problems as they tried to land their plane with a large section of
its cabin wall and ceiling torn away, but for a time they thought
their predicament was even worse, it was revealed Wednesday.
   According to a tape of radio communications from the crippled
Boeing 737, the pilots were certain as they approached the airport
on the island of Maui that the nose landing gear had failed to
deploy.
   This would have made landing the severely damaged aircraft
especially dangerous, according to aviation experts.
   ``Be advised we have no nose gear. We are landing without a nose
gear,'' co-pilot Madeline ``Mimi'' Tompkins told the Maui airport
tower in a strained but controlled voice as Capt. Robert
Schornstheimer struggled to keep the aircraft aloft.
   ``We'll need all the (emergency) equipment you got,'' she
continued, although giving little hint as to how serious Flight
243's predicament really was last April 28 in the skies above
Hawaii.
   Only seconds before the plane landed on the runway did the
controller tell the pilots the landing gear actually was deployed.
They possibly had been misled by a false instrument reading.
   The tape was played Wednesday by the Federal Aviation
Administration, the same day that Schornstheimer and Tompkins were
honored by the Air Line Pilots Association for their heroics. They
met with Vice President George Bush on Tuesday.
   Schornstheimer told the pilots group that training and teamwork
allowed him and Ms. Tompkins ``to stay calm and fly the airplane''
as they rapidly descended from 24,000 feet to a safe landing with a
20-foot section of the cabin exposed to the sky, one engine out and
another engine damaged by flying debris.
   A flight attendant was swept to her death during the flight.
   The two pilots were presented the Superior Airmanship Award from
the 40,000-member pilots union for landing the plane safely without
any additional casualties.
   The FAA tape provided little hint of the drama that was
unfolding aboard the aircraft. The plane was just approaching the
south coast of Maui when the first word of trouble aboard the plane
reached the control tower.
   ``Maui tower, Aloah 243. We're inbound for a landing,'' Ms.
Tompkins advised matter of factly.
   After providing the plane's position, she added, ``We are
unpressurized, declaring an emergency.''
   The tower directed another plane away from the runway and
advised that Flight 243 had a clear, straight approach and
emergency vehicles would be waiting.
   While Schornstheimer flew the plane, Ms. Tompkins handled the
radio. While they must have been aware of the huge missing section
of the cabin wall and ceiling, they never suggested the extent of
the plane's damage to the control tower during the 10 minute and 18
second descent and landing.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar suggested that the controller had no
need to know the information and the crew probably was busy
otherwise.
   Ms. Tompkins at one point advised there were injuries on board.
How many?
   ``We have no idea. We cannot communicate with our flight
attendants,'' she replied, the strain in her voice now showing.
   Muffled noise could be heard in the background as the wind
whipped through the cockpit _ its door torn off by the rapid
depressurization. The pilots later explained they had to resort to
hand signals to communicate.
   As Schornstheimer struggled to keep the plane flying on a direct
path to the Maui airport, Ms. Tompkins advised that the cockpit
instruments indicated the nose landing gear had not deployed.
   Two minutes later there came good news.
   ``Just for your information, the gear appears down. The gear
appears down,'' the tower informed Flight 243 seconds before it
landed.
   ``Aloha 243, just shut it down where you are. Everything's fine.
... The fire trucks are on the way,'' the controller then said.
   During the ALPA ceremony, Schornstheimer said, ``What seemed
like a short time to Mimi and I because of our busy cockpit duties
must have seemed like an eternity to our passengers and flight
attendants.''
   Ms. Tompkins praised the captain, an 11-year veteran of Aloha.
   ``Bob analyzed the situation confronting us and he reacted,''
she said. ``All of his decisions were the right ones.''
   Despite the experience, she said she was eager to return to the
cockpit: ``I`m looking forward to going back to Hawaii and flying
again.''
</TEXT>
