<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseSpending 3rdLd-Writethru a0931 05-11 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0931,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House OKs Pentagon Spending Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To update with Senate vote on breaching SALT II limits,
INSERTS new 7th graf, ``The Senate''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House cast aside President Reagan's
objections Wednesday and passed a Defense Department budget bill
that restricts his arms control policies and Star Wars programs.
   The 252-172 decision in the Democratic-controlled chamber went
largely along party lines.
   The bill will eventually be sent to a conference committee to be
reconciled with the different Pentagon budget measure now on the
Senate floor.
   The Senate, meanwhile, voted Wednesday for a $4.55 billion Star
Wars budget, narrowly rejecting a move to cut deeply into Reagan's
cherished anti-missile research program.
   The House bill authorizes the Pentagon to spend $299.5 billion
in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, the same total as the Senate
plan and the amount Reagan approved last December in an agreement
with congressional leaders aimed at reducing federal budget
deficits. The current budget is about $299 billion.
   But the House added a ban on any Star Wars tests that violate
the so-called ``narrow'' interpretation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile treaty, and also voted against buying any nuclear weapons
that violate the numerical limits in the unratified 1979 SALT II
nuclear arms treaty.
   The Senate, by a 51-45 margin, voted Wednesday afternoon to kill
a provision in that chamber's bill that would also ban weapons
beyond the SALT II limits.
   The House also added a directive telling Reagan to order the
military into the fight against illegal drug smuggling. The Senate
is likely to consider a similar proposal.
   Reagan opposes both arms restrictions and is also unhappy with
the $3.5 billion approved by the House for the Strategic Defense
Initiative, as Star Wars is formally known.
   Reagan had wanted $4.8 billion for Star Wars next year, compared
with the current SDI budget of $3.9 billion.
   In a letter to the House, Reagan said he was ``deeply
disappointed'' by the chamber's actions and said the restrictions
``would seriously undermine our position in negotiations with the
Soviet Union and (would) hold back the progress of the Strategic
Defense Initiative.''
   Reagan said he wants progress in nuclear arms control, but
added, ``We cannot do it alone. It is time for the House to step up
to these responsibilities and pass a defense authorization bill
that will strengthen our security.''
   But Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said, ``I don't believe the president has any reason to
be upset. I think it's a good bill. We gave the president a lot of
what he wanted.''
   Hours before the final House vote, the Senate voted 50-48
against a deep reduction in Star Wars.
   The Senate defeated a proposal by Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La.,
to reduce the SDI budget to about $3.8 billion and devote the extra
$750 million to the space shuttle and a space station.
   Johnston's loss was similar to his defeats in each of the past
two years, when he failed by a single vote to slash the SDI budget.
Last year, Vice President George Bush cast the tie-breaking vote in
his role as the Senate's presiding officer.
   Congress has consistently scaled back Reagan's annual requests
for sharp increases in spending for the 5-year-old program SDI
program.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has said he would recommend
a Reagan veto of the entire Pentagon budget bill unless Congress
votes enough money for Star Wars.
   Johnston argued that ``it's going to be very, very difficult to
get that space station going unless we give it some more money. ...
What's the higher priority here, the space station and the shuttle
or SDI? The space station has a lot of defense implications. ...
Dollars are scarce.''
   But Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said Johnston's proposal ``would be
very detrimental to the defense budget.''
   Originally, Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., simply proposed
reducing the proposed SDI budget from $4.6 billion to $3.9 billion,
but that lost on a 66-29 vote.
   While the House measure restricts Reagan's arms control policies
and Star Wars, it granted Reagan's request for spending for a vast
variety of weapons.
   That total includes 180 F-16 jet fighter planes, 84 F-A-18 jets,
42 F-15 jets, a dozen F-14 jets, three new Navy destroyers, two
more attack submarines, one Trident missile-firing sub, the first
of the new ``Seawolf'' class subs and 611 M-1 tanks.
</TEXT>
