<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0804 05-11 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0804,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Battle of Rival Shiites kills 33 in Sixth Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs with new cease-fire announcement, updated
death toll; picks up 5th pvs `About 60' with some editing near end
of story to conform and tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shiite Moslem militias fought with
artillery and tanks Wednesday, the sixth day of their battle for
supremacy in south Beirut's battered sprawl of tin-roofed huts and
jerry-built apartment houses.
   Police said 33 people were killed and 160 wounded, bringing
total casualties to 187 dead and 532 wounded.
   The battle raged unchecked for eight hours. Heavy fighting
continued after a truce Syrian and Iranian mediators called for
10:30 a.m. between the mainstream Amal militia, backed by Syria,
and pro-Iranian Hezbollah.
   Another truce was announced Wednesday night, the third in two
days, and the Iranian Embassy said Presidents Hafez Assad of Syria
and Aly Khamenei of Iran were forming a four-man committee to
enforce a ``final cease-fire.''
   An embassy statement said Assad and Khamenei reached agreement
by telephone on a cease-fire to begin at 11 p.m. (4 p.m. EDT) and
deployment of truce observers. Another lull in the fighting
occurred after the truce deadline.
   About 60 percent of the 250,000 inhabitants of the Shiite slums
have fled. Those remaining huddled in basements and bomb shelters.
   Witnesses reported fires burning out of control, snipers
shooting from rooftops at moving vehicles, ambulances under attack
as they tried to pick wounded from the streets.
   Hospitals appealed for blood donations. The Sahel hospital,
closest to the battle zone, told rescuers through Moslem-run Voice
of Nation radio to take victims elsewhere because ``we can't cope
with the flood of casualties.''
   AP photographer Ali Mohammed, in the Ghobeiri neighborhood,
heard a woman shout through the shellfire: ``There is a wounded man
here! He is dying! Help us, please! Take us out of here!''
   No one could reach the building.
   The factional war reflects a contest between Syria and Iran for
influence with the 1.2 million Shiites, Lebanon's largest sect. Its
focus is a 16-square-mile enclave next to the Beirut airport in
which most of the 18 foreigners missing in Lebanon are believed
held.
   Their captors in most cases are thought to be extremists linked
to the radical Hezbollah. There has been no word on the fate of the
captives, who include nine Americans.
   Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, Syria's military intelligence chief in
Lebanon, said: ``If the bloodletting continues, we will have no
other option but to respond to the pleas of the population and end
their ordeal.'' His statement was broadcast before the latest truce.
   Syria has 25,000 soldiers in Lebanon and, after 13 years of
civil war, was the nation's undisputed power broker until Iran
began challenging its influence.
   Syria sent 7,500 of the soldiers into Moslem west Beirut in
February 1987 to stop a factional battle primarily involving Amal
and Walid Jumblatt's Druse militia. The Syrians drove Hezbollah
from some west Beirut strongholds but has not entered the southern
slums.
   Salim Hoss, Lebanon's acting prime minister, accused militia
leaders of ``providing criminals with the means of killing and
destruction that burn a safe area.''
   ``We hold the leaders responsible for all the crimes committed
against humanity in south Beirut and urge them to order a
cease-fire before it is too late,'' he said in a statement.
   A slum resident, in a telephone call to the Voice of the Nation,
said: ``They are destroying our homes. They are killing our
children. They (militias) claim they want to protect us, but we
need to be protected from them.
   ``They've done worse than Israel did to us'' in the 1982
invasion, he said. ``We don't have water, power or food and we
don't know where to go.''
   A police spokesman said Amal forces led by tanks had dislodged
Hezbollah fighters from several areas on the western edge of the
slum, abutting the airport, and Hezbollah overran the main Amal
base east of the airport highway.
   Police said Amal brought 2,500 fighters from south Lebanon
during the Tuesday truce to reinforce its 4,000 men in south
Beirut. Hezbollah's fighting strength in the area is estimated at
3,000.
</TEXT>
