<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CrashProbe     05-11 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Probe,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Asked To Probe Rash Of Crashes Involving Attack Bombers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy officials said Wednesday they are weighing a
request from two Washington state congressmen to investigate a
string of six crashes of the A-6 attack bomber that killed 10
people in the last year and a half.
   At least four of the crashes occurred during training runs and
all involved bombers from the Whidbey Island Naval Air Station
north of Seattle.
   Reps. Norm Dicks and Al Swift, both Democrats, signed a letter
Monday asking Navy Secretary William Ball to investigate, said
George Behan, a spokesman for Dicks.
   Ball is reviewing the request, Navy spokeswoman Lt. Kippy Burns
said in Washington, D.C.
   The latest crash took place May 5, about 100 miles south of
Seattle, when a $32 million A-6E Intruder on a night mission
hurtled into the Cascade Mountains at 400 mph to 500 mph, killing
the pilot and bombardier-navigator.
   Less than a month earlier, a crash on the same training route
claimed two lives.
   Since 1980, 27 Whidbey pilots and crew members have died in 25
crashes of the A-6 and its cousin, the EA-6B, said Mariana Graham,
base spokeswoman.
   Dicks, a member of the House Appropriations defense
subcommittee, has asked the staff to look into the crashes to
determine whether congressional action is needed to alter the
training of pilots or correct problems with the aircraft.
   ``After six times, I think it's time to find out about what's
going on up there'' at Whidbey Island Naval Air Station, Dicks
said. The base is on Puget Sound's Whidbey Island, about 60 miles
north of Seattle.
   ``That's too many lives, too many planes,'' Dicks said.
   The training mission in last week's crash involves heading out
over the Pacific at 20,000 feet, then dropping to 500 feet as the
aircraft circles and heads inland, up and over the mountains toward
a bombing range.
</TEXT>
