<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 2nd Add, a0959-a0965,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MIAMI: the government.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Noriega's aides have told opposition leaders that the general
envisions stepping down on Aug. 12, the fifth anniversary of his
accession as commander of the defense forces.
   U.S. officials have said in recent days that they were trying to
negotiate an arrangement under which Noriega would leave Panama
immediately after his resignation and then return after 1990
presidential elections. It could not be confirmed independently
Wednesday night that agreement was reached on this point.
   Previously the administration had agreed not to extradite
Noriega on the drug charges if he went into political exile.
   Another issue under negotiation was the status of five to seven
close associates of Noriega in the defenseforces. The
administration has been seeking their resignation along with that
of Noriega, but the outcome of the discussion on this issue was
unclear.
