<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HarvardDemonstration     05-11 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvard Demonstration,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students End Occupation of Harvard Law School Dean's Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50 Harvard Law School students,
most of them black, ended an overnight ``study-in'' Wednesday,
saying the dean had agreed to some of their demands for recruiting
more minority professors.
   ``We feel we were very successful over the last 24 hours,'' said
Robert Wilkins, president of the Black Law School Association,
which staged the protest in the outer office of Law School Dean
James Vorenberg.
   The students had demanded that additional black professors be
hired and that Vorenberg, who is retiring, be replaced by a black
professor. They remained at Vorenberg's office overnight.
   Wilkins said the dean agreed to seven of 12 demands, including
establishment of a fellowship to encourage blacks to teach at
Harvard; a policy statement expressing commitment to diversity in
hiring, and a broader role for students in searching for and hiring
minority faculty.
   Vorenberg did not immediately return telephone calls for comment.
   Vorenberg said he could not agree to demands to hire a tenured
black female professor by 1989 or to increase the number of tenured
faculty by 20 positions and filling them with professors from
diverse backgrounds, Wilkins said.
   Vorenberg also said he had no ability to fulfill the students'
demand that he be replaced by Derrick Bell, a black professor at
the law school, the student leader said.
   Harvard Law School has 61 tenured positions, two held by blacks.
Three black assistant professors, who do not have teunure, are on
the staff.
</TEXT>
