<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CapitolBombing 2ndLd-Writethru a0940 05-11 1276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Capitol Bombing, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0940,1270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Charged With Bombing Capitol, Other Buildings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with background on defendants, more
details, CORRECTS date of Israeli Aircraft bombing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven members of a radical leftist group that
used ``armed propaganda'' to protest government policies are
charged with setting off bombs in the U.S. Capitol and seven other
locations, the Justice Department said Wednesday.
   The seven defendants are charged with conspiring to set off a
bomb that blew a hole in a wall outside the U.S. Senate chamber on
Nov. 7, 1983, and damaged five paintings, U.S. Attorney Jay B.
Stephens said in a statement.
   The Capitol bomb also blew doors off the hinges outside the
office of Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., then the Senate minority
leader and now majority leader.
   Explosives were also detonated at three Washington-area military
installations and four locations in New York City between 1983 and
1985, including the FBI office on Staten Island and the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association office as part of the group's campaign of
``armed propaganda,'' Stephens said.
   The bombings damaged the buildings but did not injure anyone.
   The indictment was unsealed in U.S. District Court on the same
day that one of the defendants, Marilyn Buck, 40, was convicted in
New York of murder, armed robbery and racketeering in two 1981
armored truck robberies that resulted in the deaths of two guards
and two Nyack, N.Y policemen.
   Ms. Buck drove a getaway car in the unsuccessful robbery of a
Brink's armored truck carrying $1.6 million in Nanuet, N.Y. on Oct.
20, 1981.
   Linda Sue Evans, 41, one of the seven named in the April 20
indictment, is serving a sentence for harboring Ms. Buck when she
was a fugitive wanted for the Brinks heist. Evans also was
sentenced last year to 40 years imprisonment for illegally buying
guns in New Orleans in 1983.
   Federal authorities said they waited to unseal the five-count
indictment until Ms. Buck's trial had ended in federal court in
Manhattan.
   All but one of the defendants named in the five-count indictment
unsealed Wednesday are in custody on other charges, federal
officials said. Elizabeth Duke, the seventh defendant, is a
fugitive, officials said.
   Duke fled while awaiting trial on similar charges.
   The indictment identified the defendants as members of a group
that variously called itself the Revolutionary Fighting Group, the
Armed Resistance Unit and the Red Guerrilla Resistance.
   The Armed Resistance Unit claimed responsibility for the Capitol
bombing to protest the U.S. invasion of Grenada and involvement of
Marines in Lebanon.
   Other defendants named were: Laura Whitehorn, Susan Rosenberg,
Timothy Blunk and Alan Berkman.
   Besides the Capitol bombing, the group is charged with setting
off a bomb outside the National War College at Fort McNair here on
April 26, 1983, the Washington Navy Yard Computer Center on Aug.
18, 1983 and the Washington Navy Yard Officers Club on April 20,
1984.
   Bombs were also placed at the Federal Building on Staten Island,
N.Y., on Jan. 28, 1983; the Israeli Aircraft Industries building in
New York on April 5, 1984; and the South African consulate in New
York on Sept. 26, 1984. The bombing of the New York Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association occurred on Feb. 23, 1985.
   The indictment charged the defendants with conspiracy, malicious
damage of U.S. property and aiding and abetting.
   As part of the conspiracy, the indictment charged, the group
conducted surveillances of other potential bombing targets
including: the Old Executive Office Building next to the White
House; the Washington office of the American Israel Public Affairs
Committee; the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md.; and the Army's
Aberdeen Proving Ground in Aberdeen, Md.
   Explosives and weapons, including dynamite, water gel, and other
material were stored in a Cherry Hill, N.J. storage bin and in a
garage in Doylestown, Pa., the indictment said.
   The blast in the U.S. Capitol occurred at about midnight and
blew a hole in the wall across a corridor from the Senate chamber.
The FBI concluded that three or four pounds of dynamite with a
dual-release timer was placed beneath a bench in an alcove in the
corridor outside the Senate chamber.
   It caused numerous cracks in the walls and the ornate ceiling of
the corridor but did not leave any lasting structural damage to the
Capitol.
   The indictment did not identify which members of the conspiracy
set off the bomb in the Capitol.
   After the bombing, a communique was mailed to National Public
Radio in Washington and a local public radio station, WAMU, that
said: ``We purposely aimed our attack at the institutions of
imperialist rule rather than at individual members of the ruling
class. We did not choose to kill any of them this time. But their
lives are not sacred,'' the indictment said.
   Credit was also claimed in communiques or calls to news
organizations for the other bombings to dramatize the group's
political goals, the indictment said.
   In his statement, Stephens said the defendants were charged with
being part of ``a secret organization which described itself as `a
communist politico-military organization' and which operated under
the names Revolutionary Fighting Group, Armed Resistance Unit and
the Red Guerrilla Resistance.''
   To protest government foreign and domestic policies, the members
of the group ``would plan and carry out acts of violence, which
they called `armed propaganda,' including the bombing of various
government and private buildings and property.''
   The indictment charged that the members of the group used
multiple aliases derived from the names of babies who died in the
late 1940s and early 1950s to obtain false passports, driver's
licenses as well as to get jobs, buy firearms and impersonate
police officers.
   The group armed itsef with Uzi submachine guns, shotguns,
handguns, silencers and such accessories as bulletproof body armor.
   Berkman and Blunk used a bogus search warrant to stage a Sept.
2, 1984 armed robbery of a Cromwell, Conn., supermarket, the
indictment said.
   Other potential targets said to be subjects of surveillance were
the Cuban American National Foundation and the law offices of
Smathers, Symington and Herlong, both in Washington. Summit
Aviation in Middletown, Del., was also the subject of surveillance
and training exercises for the bombing missions, the indictment
charged.
   Whitehorn, Evans and Buck were charged with conspiracy, while
all seven defendants were charged with malicious destruction of
property in connection with the bombings of the Capitol and the
three Washington military facilities.
   ``Let this be a warning to those who seek to influence the
policies of the United States government through violence and
terrorism that we will seek unrelentingly to bring them to
justice,'' Stephens said in his statement.
   ``Those who attack our sacred institutions of government and
seek to destroy the symbols of our democratic system ultimately
will have to pay the price.''
   Rosenberg, 32, and Blunk, 30, both of New York City, were
sentenced to 58 years imprisonment for possession of 600 pounds of
weapons and explosives seized during their arrest Nov. 29, 1985 in
Cherry Hill, N.J. They were arrested while placing the explosives
into a rented storage bin.
   Berkman, a physician, was sentenced to 10 years in prison last
year by a Philadelphia federal judge for possesion of explosives,
weapons and false identity cards.
   Whitehorn's was convicted of making false identity cards and
possessing firearms.
   Buck, meanwhile, faces a maximum life sentence for her
participation in the two Brink's robbberies in 1981. She and Mutulu
Shakur were also convicted of murder in death of a Brink's guard
killed during a June, 1981 armored truck robbery in the Bronx.
   The robberies were part of a string of attempted robberies and
robberies in New York and Connecticut.
</TEXT>
