<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CableTV 1stLd-Writethru a0897 05-11 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cable TV, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0897,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Film Industry Wants More Controls on Cable TV `Monopoly'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, ``Before cable...,'' to clarify attribution.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Motion Picture
Association of America urged Congress on Wednesday to rein in some
of the cable television industry's power to control the
entertainment marketplace.
   But leaders of the cable TV industry dismissed the movie
industry's concerns and rejected charges that cable TV has become
an unregulated monopoly.
   At a hearing marked by a few lively exchanges, MPAA President
Jack Valenti sparred with Ted Turner, president of Turner
Broadcasting System, and John Malone, president of
Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's largest cable company.
   ``Cable is no longer a babe in swaddling clothes,'' Valenti told
members of the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on
telecommunications, which is looking into the effects of cable
deregulation.
   Cable TV, he said, has grown into a multibillion-dollar industry
dominated by several large companies.
   ``Consumers are held hostage by their cable system. They have no
alternative. They can either commit suicide or go bowling,'' said
Valenti, who represents the major Hollywood studios and independent
producers.
   Malone and Turner defended their industry, saying it has brought
more than 50 basic channels and more than a dozen pay channels to
television viewers in more than half the country.
   ``Before cable, we had the three big networks and they dominated
what people saw. Now there are the three networks and more than 50
cable channels,'' Turner said.
   More than 80 percent of America's TV households can receive
cable, and about 52 percent of all households subscribe. The steady
increase in cable subscribership and in the amount of
cable-exclusive programming has cut into the audience of the
broadcast networks and the receipts of movie theaters.
   Edward O. Fritts, president of the National Association of
Broadcasters, said ``the cable industry has become the mouse that
roared,'' able to raise rates at will and decide what broadcast
signals to carry.
   Fritts urged Congress to pass a law requiring cable companies to
carry local broadcast signals and prohibit cable companies from
showing any syndicated program for which a local broadcaster has
purchased exclusive rights.
   As cable's clout has grown, it has been winning contracts away
from the broadcast networks to carry more and more major sports
events, and Rep. Dennis Eckart, D-Ohio, wondered whether in the
future average sports fans will have to subscribe to cable to watch
their home teams play.
   Malone suggested that while Congress could pass a law to protect
broadcast coverage of sports events, it would be more prudent to
``wait to see what the free market does.''
   Malone disputed Valenti's claim that cable TV is a monopoly. For
movies, he said, consumers can go to the theater, rent video
cassettes or watch them on the broadcast networks.
   Malone also defended the investment his company and other large
cable companies have made in industry programming ventures, saying
that without this investment many of these channels would have gone
out of business. He
   cable companies helped shore up The Discovery Channel and
Turner's enterprise.
   Valenti, however, said such investments give cable companies
incentive to carry on their systems the services in which they have
an equity stake, denying viewers other programming choices.
   ``These monopolies can decide what the consumer is going to
see,'' Valenti said.
</TEXT>
