<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CyanideTrial     05-11 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Trial,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Misconduct Probed in Cyanide Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors who convicted a woman of killing two
people with cyanide-laced Excedrin capsules will return to court
Friday for a hearing on allegations of jury tampering, a judge
ruled Wednesday.
   U.S. District Judge William Dwyer granted a request to question
the 12 jurors by defense attorney Thomas Hillier II, who cited an
anonymous telephone call allegedly received by a juror during
deliberations.
   The jury Monday convicted Stella Nickell, 44, of killing her
husband, Bruce Nickell, 52, and Susan Katherine Snow, 40. Both had
swallowed Extra-Strength Excedrin capsules containing cyanide in
1986.
   Dwyer said the court by law must look into any allegations of
jury tampering, but he emphasized that in ordering the hearing, he
was ``not suggesting in the slightest any misconduct by any juror.''
   He invited Hillier and Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida to
submit questions to him. Dwyer said he would question jurors
himself under oath.
   Laurel Holliday, a juror, had told the judge before the verdict
that a female caller told her Mrs. Nickell had failed a lie
detector test, information that had not been allowed as evidence in
the three-week trial.
   The judge let Ms. Holliday stay on the jury after she said the
call would not influence her. Hillier concurred with that decision
at the time.
   Ms. Maida on Wednesday argued against the need for questioning,
saying any inference of misconduct was ``pure speculation.''
   Mrs. Nickell faces a maximum penalty of life in prison at
sentencing June 17.
</TEXT>
