<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CannesFestival     05-11 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cannes Festival,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cannes Film Festival Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FIONA GLEIZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 41st Cannes Film Festival opened
Wednesday evening with a gentle rain falling on a parade of
beautiful people.
   French actress Sandrine Bonnaire declared the start of the
two-week movie gala.
   This year's festival, which runs through May 23, is billed as a
quieter affair than last year's 40th anniversary extravaganza, but
enough big names were on hand to satisfy the star-spotters gathered
on the famous seaside promenade La Croisette.
   Actress Nastassja Kinski, dressed in rose taffeta, drew cries of
admiration upon her arrival.
   She is one of the nine members of the festival jury, which is
headed this year by veteran Italian director Ettore Scola.
   Ms. Bonnaire pronounced the festival open from the Palais des
Festivals, known as ``the cake'' for its layered structure.
   But the stars in everyone's minds were the dolphins, the stars
of ``Le Grand Bleu,'' the naturalist movie selected for the opening
night celebrations.
   French director Luc Besson kept his film under close wraps and
Wednesday night was its first public showing.
   ``Le Grand Bleu'' stars American actress Rosanna Arquette, who
played alongside Madonna in ``Desperately Seeking Susan.''
   Her co-star is Jean-Marc Barr who plays the French diver Jacques
Mayol, who dives without oxygen bottles.
   Much of the 2{-hour film was shot underwater, using cameras
designed especially for the film.
   ``Le Grand Bleu'' is not in the official competition. The first
of the 21 films competing for the Golden Palm award will be shown
Thursday.
   ``L'Oeuvre au Noir'' _ The Work in Black _ is directed by
Belgian Andre Delvaux, son of surrealist painter Paul Delvaux.
   Based on the novel of the same name, written by the late
Marguerite Yourcenar, the film is set in Flanders and Italy in the
16th century, with Zenon, an alchemist doctor as the main character.
   The background is one of religious upheaval and inquisitions.
   In an effort to encourage new talent in the cinema, the festival
jury has selected a number of films by young directors.
   ``A World Apart,'' a story of apartheid in South Africa, is the
first film made under the direction of Chris Menges from Britain.
   Menges made his name in the cinema as a director of photography,
working with leading directors such as Roland Joffe on the movie
``Mission.''
   China's emerging film industry is represented by the film,
``King of Children.'' This is the first time a Chinese film has
been included in the official selection at Cannes.
   Another Far Eastern film selected by the jury, is Kiju Yoshida's
``Onimaru,'' from Japan.
   The film promises a new regard on the novel ``Wuthering
Heights'' by the English romanticist, Emily Bronte.
   ``Three Sisters'' by German director Margarethe von Trotta, is
billed as a modern adaptation of the Anton Chekov play. The three
sisters are played by Fanny Ardant, Greta Scacchi and Valeria
Golino.
   Fifteen countries are represente in the official competition.
</TEXT>
