<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     05-11 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire In Siege Of Sikh Temple; Negotiations Begin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces and Sikh militants ceased
fire Wednesday as negotiations began to end the three-day siege of
Sikhism's holiest shrine, police and witnesses said.
   Up to 12 people were killed during the siege that started Monday
after Sikh militants began firing from the Golden Temple complex at
police posts on nearby rooftops.
   Elsewhere in Punjab state, five people were killed in attacks
late Tuesday night and early Wednesday, the United News of India
reported.
   The head Sikh priest, Jasbir Singh Rode, held inconclusive talks
with senior police officials late Wednesday as 2,500 paramilitary
troops around the 400-year-old temple and an estimated 100 Sikh
militants inside stopped firing.
   ``We have many options,'' Punjab Gov. S.S. Ray told a news
conference, referring to the talks. He did not elaborate.
   Militant Sikhs have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland since 1982.
   Although a majority in Punjab, Sikhs comprise only 2 percent of
India's total population of 800 million people. The Sikhs claim
they are discriminated against by Hindus, who make up 82 percent of
the nationwide population.
   An Associated Press correspondent allowed inside the shrine saw
the decomposing bodies of three men and one woman. Sikh militants
said the four were shot by security men firing from rooftops.
   Militants holding automatic weapons huddled behind marble
pillars and vowed to carry on their resistance.
   ``We will continue to die but we shall never be destroyed,''
said Sikh militant Nirvair Singh.
   Young Sikhs, most yet to sprout a beard, were seen carrying
automatic weapons and chanting ``Sikhs will rule!''
   Earlier plans to lift a curfew in most of Amritsar's old walled
city failed, police officer Singh said.
   The curfew was ordered Monday when Sikh extremists began firing
from the temple complex at rooftop police posts.
   A.A. Siddiqui, deputy inspector general of police, said at least
10 people have died and 10 have been injured since violence began
Monday.
   But Sikh militants inside the shrine said at least 12 people
have died.
   Three people were killed early Wednesday in a heavy exchange of
fire between extremists in the temple complex and security forces.
   In New Delhi, P. Chidambaram, minister of state for home
affairs, told Parliament Wednesday ``other forces'' were being
moved to Amritsar, the United News of India reported. He did not
elaborate.
   The Home Ministry is responsible for internal security.
   The army was sent into the Golden Temple complex in June 1984 to
drive Sikh extremists from the shrine. Later that year, Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi was assassinated by two of her Sikh
bodyguards in revenge.
   Reports said Wednesday that police cut off electricity and water
to the temple. Amritsar city officials said lines were down but
said militants had cut them.
   Government spokesman J.F. Brar said extremists cut electrical
lines Tuesday night to make sure no lights inside the shrine would
illuminate their positions. He said this also cut the water supply,
as electricity is needed to operate the system's pumps.
   More than 800 pilgrims were evacuated from the complex Tuesday
to keep them out of the crossfire.
   The complex covers an area equivalent to more than five city
blocks. The temple is located in the center of a pool.
</TEXT>
