<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0944 05-11 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0944,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Finally Gets Reagan Endorsement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: UPDATES in top 10 grafs with speech delivered, color; picks
up 9th graf pvs, bgng: Earlier, as</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan gave George Bush's
presidential bid his long-awaited endorsement Wednesday night,
saying ``I intend to campaign as as hard as I can'' for his vice
president.
   Reagan's endorsement, delivered at a $1,500-a-plate Republican
fund-raising dinner, came hours after Bush won the support of his
only remaining presidential rival, Pat Robertson.
   Although the president's backing was never in doubt, Reagan as
titular head of the party remained officially neutral while the GOP
race was contested, even though Bush clinched the nomination two
weeks ago.
   Reagan told his audience of 3,000 Republicans: ``I intend to
campaign as hard as I can. My candidate is a former member of
Congress, ambassador to China, ambassador to the United Nations,
Director of the CIA and national chairman of the Republican party.''
   ``I'm going to work as hard as I can to make Vice President
George Bush the next president of the United States.''
   In endorsing Bush, Reagan said he was breaking ``a silence I've
maintained for some time with regard to the presidential
candidates.''
   The president's terse endorsment came at the end of a speech in
which he cited the accomplishments of his adminstration. He
mentioned Bush three times, and on one of those occasions referred
to him as ``George Bosh.''
   ``Eight years ago, George Bush and I said to the American
people, `the time is now.' It still is. The story of America is one
of people who have made their dreams come true, by realizing that
the time for action is always now,'' Reagan said.
   At the end of Reagan's speech, Bush joined him at the podium and
the two held clasped hands aloft as hundreds of balloons were
released from the ceiling.
   Bush, who spoke before Reagan, praised the president, saying:
``You began a great national renewal. What an inspiration you have
been to all of us _ your simple humanity, your decency, your
strength.''
   Earlier, as Bush waved from a second-floor balconey in the Old
Executive Office Building, Robertson told reporters on the White
House drive below that he had given his endorsement to the vice
president during a private session.
   ``I will be making that official on Monday ... because the race
is pretty much over,'' Robertson said.
   The former television minister has won only 46 delegates in the
Republican primary and caucus competition. He said he was waiting
until Monday so his supporters would have a shot at winning
additional national convention seats at GOP caucuses this weekend
in Arizona and Virginia.
   ``I didn't ask anything for myself. I spoke about education and
the need to bring the 1984 platform into line with the realities of
1988,'' Robertson said. ``We definitely had a meeting of the minds
on the platform.''
   Robertson said he told Bush he would work to get his supporters
to back him.
   In a prelude to his formal endorsement, Reagan made his
intentions known at a meeting of GOP congressional leaders in the
Cabinet Room earlier Wednesday. The Republican leaders applauded
when Reagan and Bush entered the room.
   Vanquished Republican presidential hopeful Sen. Bob Dole, who
attended the session, later had some advice for Bush which he
shared with reporters.
   Dole said Bush would ``have to build on the Reagan record, build
on the Reagan constituency, try to hold it if you can. But sooner
or later, you're going to be out there running as _ it's going to
be the Bush campaign, the Bush agenda, the Bush vision for the
future. And I think that will develop in time. I think he can do
it.''
   On more specific advice on what Bush would have to do in the
coming months to get elected, Dole said, ``I think I'll leave that
to Bush. He did enough _ he took care of me all right.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater called the president's
endorsement of Bush ``the warmest of political embraces.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan would campaign for Bush even before the
Republican convention in August.
   ``I'm sure once we return from the summit (in Moscow May 29-June
2) there will be a number of events this summer,'' Fitzwater said.
   Reagan's blessing comes two weeks after the Pennsylvania primary
in which Bush won sufficient Republican convention delegates to
lock up the party nomination.
</TEXT>
