<HEAD>Witnesses Identify Defendant in Multiple-Murder case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with last witness, state
resting, picking up 11th graf `Vicky, I'm...'; DELETES last 2 grafs
to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness testified Wednesday that a man
accused in 16 slayings spoke of settling scores a month before a
shooting rampage that left two dead.
   ``He said he had a few people in town he'd like to get even
with,'' Paul Epperson, a bakery route salesman, said before the
prosecution rested its case against R. Gene Simmons.
   Simmons is charged with capital murder, attempted capital murder
and kidnapping during a 45-minute shooting rampage Dec. 28 in
Russellville.
   Police said Simmons used two .22-caliber revolvers that day to
kill Kathy Kendrick, 24, who friends say once rejected Simmons'
amorous attention, and James Chaffin, 33, who apparently was a
chance victim.
   Police said Simmons had a grudge against most of the people he
is accused of shooting. Others were wounded that day as four
Russellville businesses were terrorized by a pistol-wielding
intruder.
   After Simmons surrendered, police found the bodies of 14
relatives, including his wife, his children and grandchildren, at
his home near Dover. Police said they were killed during the
Christmas holidays. Simmons is to be tried July 18 in their deaths.
   Epperson said Simmons made the comments about getting even
during conversation at the convenience store where Simmons worked.
   ``Rusty Taylor was the only name he called,'' Epperson said,
referring to one of the four people Simmons is accused of wounding.
   Defense attorney Robert E. Irwin said the defense would have
only two or three witnesses. The defense opens its case Thursday.
   Earlier Wednesday, Joyce Butts, assisted to and from the witness
box by her husband, identified Simmons in the courtroom and said
they had a bad encounter once when both worked at a freight company
after she admonished him to do a better job. ``He got angry,'' she
said. ``He screamed, he shouted across the office that he didn't
get paid enough.''
   Mrs. Butts said the shooting resulted in nightmares. ``I see
things, scary,'' she said. ``I hear things. I see people. They
don't have faces. They're after me.''
   Vicky Jackson, who the prosecution says was taken hostage after
Mrs. Butts was shot at the freight company, recalled saying to
Simmons, ``Gene, please don't shoot me, please don't shoot me.''
   Ms. Jackson said she was cowering when Simmons, holding a gun to
her right temple, took her by the right arm and told her to get up.
   ``Vicky, I'm not going to hurt you,'' Ms. Jackson said Simmons
told her, ``I came to kill Joyce. I got everybody that hurt me. I'm
not going to hurt you.''
   Ms. Jackson said Simmons put down one of the two pistols, but he
kept the other one pointed at her and would not let her leave. She
added: ``Because he said he didn't want the police barreling in
there or barging in there. ... I guess he thought they wouldn't
shoot him if they had me there.''
   He refused to give her the other gun, she said.
</TEXT>
