<HEAD>Panama Denies Reports of Deal with Noriega</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf pvs ``He continued:...'' with
government news agency report of Reagan contact with Noriega. Pick
up 6th graf pvs, ``The source...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government denied Wednesday that
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega had agreed to step down as armed forces
commander and leave the country in return for dismissal of charges
against him in U.S. federal court.
   An administration source in Washington said the Reagan
administration had offered to drop drug-smuggling and
money-laundering charges against Noriega in return for the
general's retirement and exile.
   Boris Moreno, director of the government's National Information
System, or SNI, told The Associated Press: ``In Panama there have
been simple conversations on diverse subjects. There has been no
agreement about anything.
   ``Upon being informed of the existence of such reports, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega told SNI categorically, ``The sovereignty of
Panama is not negotiable and is indeclinable,'' Moreno said.
   He continued: ``Such reports only come from sources interested
in sidetracking the conversations and in aggravating the existing
situation. These reports form part of the confusion and
confrontation provoked by certain elements of the Washington
establishment.''
   The official news agency Panapress on Wednesday said that
``President Reagan entered in direct contact with General
Noriega.'' The agency did not elaborate.
   Moreno, when asked if that meant Reagan spoke by telephone with
Noriega, said he did not know.
   The source in Washington, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said that under the proposed deal Noriega would step down, probably
in August, and he would stay out of Panama until after the next
presidential elections there.
   The U.S. government has called for Noriega's ouster since he was
indicted in federal court in Florida in February. The Reagan
administration has imposed a variety of economic sanctions on
Panama in recent months to try to hasten the departure of Noriega,
who is considered the power behind Panama's government.
   Raymond Takiff, one of Noriega's four U.S. lawyers, told the AP
in Miami that he was unaware of the alleged deal. Takiff and lawyer
Frank Rubino met with Noriega Tuesday in Panama City.
   Rubino had told the AP in Panama on Tuesday: ``At the moment
there are no plans for his (Noriega's) retirement.''
   Terence Kneebone, the U.S. Embassy spokesman in Panama City,
said he had no knowledge of the alleged deal.
   Asked if State Department envoy Michael Kozak met in Panama on
Wednesday with the general or his representatives, Kneebone said,
``No comment.'' The Reagan administration has sent Kozak to Panama
in recent weeks to talk with Noriega.
</TEXT>
