   The United Methodist Publishing House
has developed a policy on AIDS in the workplace, saying the disease
is not spread by casual contact and protecting the jobs and privacy
of any employes who have it.
   If ``unable to perform their normal job duties because of their
illness,'' workers with AIDS would be given disability leaves, the
policy says. Employees who refuse to work alongside people with
AIDS could go on unpaid leaves or apply for other publishing house
jobs.
   The policy is ``to protect the rights of all our employees,''
says Stephen C. Tippens, a vice president, who adds that so far, no
cases of AIDS have been reported among the agency's 1,300 employes.
