<2ND_LINE>AM-Spelling Dwelling, Adv 17,0382</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, May 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Aaron Spelling Builds Home That Dwarfs Neighborhood Mansions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Megamansions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television producer Aaron Spelling, who
created lavish prime-time fantasies Americans love, is building an
opulent real estate fantasy his neighbors hate.
   In this real-life drama with soap-opera overtones, the
56,500-square-foot Holmby Hills mansion has already been
immortalized in satirical song in ``An Ode to Spelling's Dwelling''
and is called ``The Mental Institution'' by a neighbor who says
only a crazy person would build it.
   Spelling, whose TV shows include ``Dynasty,'' ``Hotel'' and
``Fantasy Island,'' is himself tight-lipped about the $12 million
home mushrooming on the six-acre parcel he bought for $10 million,
said his publicist, Warren Cowan.
   The Spelling property was once anchored by the
10,000-square-foot Bing Crosby house and included two other homes,
all torn down for the new mansion.
   The French chateau-style structure, which will house Spelling,
wife Candy and two children, dwarfs other sizeable mansions in the
area. It is longer than a football field and has a roofline 51 feet
from the ground. Tons of natural limestone shipped from Italy will
cover the exterior.
   Inside will be a bowling alley, a screening room, a gymnasium,
garages for eight cars, a tennis court, an entire floor of closets
tucked between the soaring first and second floors and, of course,
a swimming pool.
   ``Aaron Spelling is not a superstar in this neighborhood, and
I'm not excited about the visibility of this wealth,'' said one
neighbor, J.P. Guerin. ``Yet, you have to look at this with a
certain amount of humor. If you don't laugh at it, you'll cry.''
   Composer John Perry of Ojai, Calif., said he was staggered by
published reports of Spelling's lavish home, so he knocked out a
calypso-style rap song with these lyrics:
   ``See Candy's jewels, see Aaron's money,
   ``Aaron doesn't think being picked on is funny.
   ``See Candy's clothes, see Aaron's pad,
   ``See Aaron and Candy's castle, make the neighbors mad.
   ``But they're livin' in splendor high above the crowds,
   ``60,000 square feet of heaven.
   ``That's Spelling's dwelling, I said Spelling's Dwelling...''
 
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, May 17</NOTE>
