<TEXT>
   A report from a private consultant hired
by Union Carbide Corp. says sabotage by a disgruntled employee, not
negligence, caused a deadly gas leak at the company's Bhopal,
India, plant about four years ago.
   Arthur D. Little Inc.'s report, released Tuesday, supports
previous assertions by Carbide about how the disaster occurred and
refutes the Indian government's negligence theory as ``physically
impossible'' given the plant's design.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers soon will be harvesting a winter wheat
crop estimated at 1.62 billion bushels, up 4 percent from last
year's production, the Agriculture Department says.
   The first forecast of the season, released Tuesday and based on
May 1 surveys, compared with a 1987 winter wheat output of 1.56
billion bushels. The average yield was estimated at 40.7 bushels
per harvested acre, up from last year's 39.8 bushels per acre.
   Farmers are expected to have about 39.8 million acres for
harvest this year, up 1 percent from 39.3 million in 1987, the
government reported.
