<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-11 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices remain in what analysts call
a sluggish, directionless phase, partly because of nervousness
about OPEC's scheduled meeting next month over production cuts.
   Crude oil futures were mostly higher, gasoline futures generally
declined and heating oil was mixed Tuesday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   The June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, settled down 8 cents at $17.46 per barrel. Most other
contract months showed small gains.
   Traders said the weakness in June crude reflected a continued
surplus of West Texas Intermediate and other light crude grades in
the spot market for immediate purchase.
   June contracts for unleaded regular gasoline edged up 0.03 cent
to close at 51.62 cents a gallon, but most other months fell. June
heating oil gained 0.07 cent to 47.74 cents a gallon. Shorter-term
contracts for heating oil rose while longer-term contracts slipped.
   Dealers said the market's jitters about OPEC's scheduled June 8
meeting had subdued trading volume.
   The 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
scheduled the meeting after failing to reach agreement on cutting
production in conjunction with non-OPEC producers at meeting last
month in Vienna, Austria.
   ``There's talk about that (meeting) ... it's like an excuse not
to trade,'' said John Azarow, senior energy trader for Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
</TEXT>
