<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Earns-FarmCredit     05-11 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Farm Credit,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Credit System Reports $165 Million Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Farm Credit System has posted its third
consecutive quarterly profit, a $165 million net in its first
fiscal quarter that reversed its loss of $155 million a year
earlier.
   The profit reported Tuesday was due entirely to a $160 million
reduction in the reserve for loan losses and a $10 million net gain
on other property owned.
   The system's net interest income of $146 million _ the
difference between interest income and interest expense _ fell
short of its other expenses of $151 million. A year earlier, the
system had net interest income of $149 million, less than the $164
million in other expenses.
   The Farm Credit System has been able to reduce its loan-loss
reserves because borrowers are considered better able to repay
their loans.
   ``The improvement in the agricultural economy experienced in the
latter half of 1987 continued into the first quarter of 1988,''
Alan D. Fass, president and chief executive of the Federal Farm
Credit Banks Funding Corp., said in a news release.
   Fass announced the Farm Credit System's profit jointly with H.
Brent Beesley, president and chief executive of the Farm Credit
Corporation of America.
   The Farm Credit System consists of 37 borrower-owned banks and
associations serving the rural economy. Congress put it on a more
secure footing last year by authorizing the issuance of up to $4
billion in government-backed, low-interest loans.
   The 1987 legislation, by increasing confidence in the Farm
Credit System, made it possible to narrow the interest-rate spreads
on Farm Credit debt obligations over U.S. Treasury securities.
   Fass said the first-quarter net interest income was boosted by
special factors, and may be lower in the rest of 1988.
   The allowance for loan losses as of March 31 was $2.744 billion,
down from $2.951 billion at the end of 1987 and $3.532 billion as
of March 31, 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
