<DOCNO> AP880511-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ProgramTrading Bjt   05-11 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Program Trading, Bjt,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brokerage Halt of Program Trading: Progress or Public Relations
Ploy?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Program Trading-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broad move by five big brokers to limit
computerized stock trading has won enthusiastic endorsement from
critics who claim the strategy has caused unwarranted price
convulsions and alienated many investors.
   But some question the effectiveness of the halt on index
arbitrage program trading, because four of the firms will continug
using the strategy for their clients' investments.
   Kidder Peabody & Co., Morgan Stanley & Co., PaineWebber Inc. and
Salomon Brothers Inc. on Tuesday announced limitations on program
trading for their own accounts only, while Bear Stearns & Co. said
it had imposed a total suspension.
   The moves marked the most aggressive voluntary steps yet to calm
an outcry over the strategy, which has been blamed for destructive
volatility in the stock market before and since the October crash.
   ``It is necessary for all to work toward the goal of restoring
confidence in and guaranteeing the vibrancy of the marketplace,''
John Gutfreund, chairman and chief executive of Salomon, said in a
statement that also reflected a view expressed by the other firms.
   ``Any action taken by member firms to tone volatility and
increase investor confidence should be applauded,'' said Richard
Torrenzano, spokesman for the New York Stock Exchange, which also
has taken steps to limit program trading. ``I think it's meaningful
and a step in the right direction.''
   Wall Street sources said the firms have been under enormous
pressure from stock exchanges, customers, lawmakers, and even their
own salespeople, for coordinated action to control the computerized
practice, which involves the massive purchase and sale of stock
index futures and the underlying stocks on which they are based.
   Although their action won't mean an end to program trading, some
traders said it should help limit the volatility because the
brokerages had used the technique much more frequently than their
customers did.
   ``We welcome their decision, of course,'' said Anthony A.
LaCroix, chairman, president and chief executive of Advest Inc., a
Hartford, Conn.-based securities firm that has urged tough
restrictions on program trading. ``We think it's a right one for
the capital markets in the long run, and will encourage individuals
to come back to the market.''
   Nevertheless, experts say proprietary program trading by these
brokerages has accounted for only about 20 percent of the total
volume of trades attributed to the strategy. Some critics said this
leaves plenty of room for more uncertainty.
   ``Liquidity in our financial markets has dried up, and this may
be the first sight of rain we've seen in a long time,'' said Rep.
Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the finance subcommittee of
the House Energy and Commerce Committee in reaction to the
suspensions. ``However, with customers still in the index arbitrage
business, the question remains if intra-day volatility will
increase or decrease.''
   Capital Guardian Trust Co. Chairman Robert G. Kirby, a member of
the presidential panel that investigated the stock crash, said the
big brokers probably had determined that bad publicity over the
technique didn't outweigh the profits they derived from it.
   ``These guys decided that life's too short,'' Kirby said. ``I
think they get the blame for all the volatility in the marketplace,
but all the volatility is going to go on, because of their
customers.''
   Most index arbitrage program trading is done on behalf of
institutional clients, such as pension funds and banks, who see the
strategy as one of the few moneymakers in a market that has
languished since the October crash.
   At the same time, program trading has frightened billions of
investor dollars out of the market because it can swing prices
violently without regard to a stock's real value. The result has
been a severe drop in trading volume and stock underwritings.
   Some said the actions Tuesday reflected a growing belief in the
securities industry that lawmakers would take steps aimed at
restoring investor confidence unless brokerage firms could reform
themselves.
   ``What's really developed is a tremendous fear by the Wall
Street commmunity that legislators may take significant action that
might be an over-reaction,'' said Jack Barbanel, a futures expert
at the Gruntal & Co. investment firm in New York.
   Goldman Sachs & Co., Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., Merrill Lynch
& Co. and First Boston Co. had previously announced suspensions of
index arbitrage program trading for their own accounts. But only
Goldman's was considered significant because the firm was among the
biggest users of the technique.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ProgramTrading-Glance     05-11 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Program Trading-Glance,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Program Trading, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Program trading is a catch-all term for a range
of computerized trading strategies that most often refers to index
arbitrage, which involves the rapid purchase and sale of stocks and
stock-index futures.
   In this strategy, traders attempt to profit on discrepancies
between the price of the actual stocks traded in New York and the
value of indexes based on them, such as the Standard & Poor's 500,
traded in Chicago.
   When the stocks trade at a significant discount to the index
futures, traders sell the futures and buy the stocks. Conversely,
when the index futures sell at a big enough discount from the
underlying stocks, traders sell the stocks and buy the index
futures.
   The speed at which these transactions are executed is crucial to
the program trading strategy because the price discrepancies
between stocks and stock-index futures are temporary during the
course of a trading session.
   Big brokerages use powerful computer programs that track these
discrepancies and instantly set off buy or sell programs when
conditions are deemed profitable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OrangePeeler Bjt   05-11 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Orange Peeler, Bjt,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Andy Rooney's ``Magic'' Comments Spark Wave Of Orders For Gadget</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOULON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-odd years of personal promotion failed
to make Wilbur Blank's orange-peeling invention a success, but a
few seconds of exposure on CBS' ``60 Minutes'' have sparked a
deluge of orders for the gadget.
   Commentator Andy Rooney's glowing comments and brief
demonstration of the device in a show broadcast several weeks ago
prompted an unprecedented wave of demand for the Quik Orange Peel,
which Blank has been selling in its current form for about eight
years.
   ``This has been mind-boggling,'' Blank's wife Jane said in an
interview from the couple's home in this west-central Illinois
town. ``We had no idea he was going to say anything about the
orange peel. You can't believe the reaction.''
   Rooney demonstrated the peeler _ which had been lying in his
desk for three years _ during a commentary on gadgets he gets in
the mail.
   ``This is one of the best things I ever got,'' Rooney said.
``It's changed my life.
   ``It really is magic. You can amaze your friends with this.''
   In the past two weeks, Blank and his Wil-Le Products Co. have
received dozens of mail and phone orders for the peeler, which he
sells in groups of five for $6.
   ``Last week, we sent out about 500 or 600 orders,'' Blank said.
``We're getting more every day.''
   Blank nearly had given up on ever selling the public on his
invention, which he developed in California while working as a
welder before World War II.
   ``I was fresh off the farm, and I got out to California and
found I loved oranges but hated to peel them,'' he said. ``That's
when I came up with my orange peeler.''
   The original model, made of stainless steel wire, looked more
like a bottle opener than an orange peeler. Blank's patent
application was rejected and for four decades tried unsuccessfully
to market the device.
   He showed his peeler to Fred Wadley at I.V. Die Co. in Peoria
about eight years ago, and Wadley fashioned one from
brightly-colored orange plastic.
   Wadley has produced about 30,000 peelers since then, but says
sales must soar before the product can be declared a commercial
success.
   Rooney isn't sure why he still had the peeler in his desk drawer
three years after Blank sent it to him.
   ``I just saw it in the drawer one day when I was looking for
something, and I decided to give it a try,'' Rooney said in a
telephone interview. ``I really liked it.''
   Rooney said viewers flooded the network with calls and letters
after the ``60 Minutes'' segment.
   ``We always get a lot of mail, but we got more than usual on
this. Letters are still coming in,'' he said.
   Rooney speculated that the benefits of prime-time exposure would
be fleeting, although a planned ``60 Minutes'' follow-up filmed at
the Blanks' home could help.
   Blank sold his blacksmith and welding shop two years ago, but
still runs a mobile home park and other business interests. He
isn't counting on the Quik Orange Peel to make him rich.
   ``I don't want to be a millionaire. I'd have too many people on
my back, then,'' he said. ``I'd be happy with about $90,000. I
could live real comfortably in Toulon on $90,000. Of course, if it
goes above that, I'm not going to turn it down.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USG     05-11 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USG,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showdown at USG Shareholders Meeting Over Hostile Takeover</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain; meeting scheduled to begin at 11
a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle over Desert Partners L.P.'s attempted
hostile takeover of USG Corp. moves to the company's annual meeting
today, where Desert Partners has another chance to appeal to
shareholders for support.
   Directly at stake are six seats on USG's 15-member board of
directors.
   Desert Partners has nominated its own a slate of candidates for
the seats, rivaling USG's own slate, and is waging a hostile $2.2
billion buyout offer for the building products company as well.
   Most shareholders already have voted their choices by mail,
although those voting by mail may change their votes at the meeting.
   Election results were not expected today. Federal regulations
allow USG 10 days to tally the votes and announce the winners, said
USG spokeswoman Randi Killian.
   An election victory by the hostile bidder would not translate
into immediate control of USG by Desert Partners, a partnership led
by oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E. Brown of Midland, Tex.
   But a Desert Partners victory would indicate shareholder
approval of the group's demand that USG drop its ``poison pill''
takeover defense, a major impediment to the proposed acquisition.
   Desert Partners, which owns about 9.9 percent of USG's 51.5
million common shares outstanding, is offering $42 cash a share for
up to 39 million shares. The partnership proposes purchasing the
remaining shares for $42 worth of debt securities and warrants,
bringing the total indicated value of the deal to about $2.2
billion.
   USG has proposed to fight Desert Partners with a defensive
recapitalization, which would be submitted to a shareholder vote on
June 24. USG would borrow $2.2 billion to pay its shareholders $37
a share in cash, debentures with a face value of $5 and a share of
stock in the recapitalized corporation for each of their shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
