<1ST_LINE>d f PM-SouthKorea-Shipbuilding     05-11 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Shipbuilding,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Currency Rise Depresses South Korea Shipbuilding Orders By 41.3
Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's shipbuilding orders have
decreased by 41.3 percent so far this year from the same period in
1987 because of the national currency's appreciation in foreign
exchange, officials said today.
   Orders received so far consist of 626,300 gross tons of export
ships and 800 gross tons of domestic ships, the officials said.
   But the officials also said that despite the sluggish orders,
local shipmakers still have a combined outstanding order of 6
million gross tons, enough to keep them busy until the first half
of next year.
   The value of the South Korean won has risen 7.43 percent against
the U.S. dollar so far this year. A higher won makes South Korean
exports more expensive abroad while lowering the prices of imports.
</TEXT>
