<HEAD>British Airways Wants To Fly Supersonic Plane To Atlanta</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 6th graf to CORRECT name of spokesman to Lampl sted
Lamil; picks up 7th graf pvs bg'ng, That compares ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways wants to fly the supersonic
Concorde to Atlanta as part of its regularly scheduled service.
   ``I can't tell you when because I would then be in the position
of asking permission to do it. It will happen, but you won't know
it because it will drive in quietly,'' British Airways chairman,
Lord John King, told a British American Business Group luncheon
Tuesday.
   ``The plan would be to link (Atlanta) up with the Washington
service,'' King said.
   The tentative plan calls for three Concorde flights a week from
London to Washington to Atlanta. The airline now flies the Concorde
twice daily from London to New York and three times a week from
Miami to Washington to London.
   Atlanta would be a major new gateway for British Airways, King
said. He said he believes Atlanta could support Concorde service.
British Airways has seven of the supersonic planes.
   The Atlanta to London flight, with a stop in Washington,
probably would take about 5{ hours, according to British Airways
spokesman John Lampl. The fare probably would be around $6,000.
   That compares with current non-stop service from Atlanta to
London, an eight-hour flight which costs $677, if tickets are
purchased 21 days in advance.
</TEXT>
