<HEAD>Xerox Cutting 800 Jobs; Hopes To Redeploy Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp. will eliminate 800 managerial
and professional jobs from its U.S. Marketing Group, but expects to
be able to shift displaced employees to other positions in the
group, a company spokesman said.
   The job cuts are being made only in areas that do not have
direct contact with customers, such as public relations, said Xerox
spokesman John Rasor.
   The cutback is part of a companywide effort to reduce expenses
and then invest in areas that directly serve the customer, Rasor
said.
   Workers whose jobs are eliminated will initially fill jobs now
available because of a hiring freeze that has been in effect
throughout the group, which sells and services the company's
copiers.
   A. Barry Rand, the group's president, said Tuesday that layoffs
would be a last resort and that no one who takes another job with
the company will take a pay cut.
   The U.S. Marketing Group, headquartered in Rochester, employs
about 2,600 people here, and about 27,500 throughout the United
States. The cutback will affect 675 jobs in Rochester and 125 at
other locations, Rasor said.
</TEXT>
