<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LTVSale 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LTV Sale, 1st Ld-Writethru,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV Announces Sale Of Warren Works</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with company announcement</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Steel Co. today said it has signed a
contract to sell its steel plant in Warren to the Renco Group Inc.
of New York City.
   Terms of the sale were not disclosed in the company's
announcement.
   Included in the sale is LTV's Republic Drainage Products Co. in
Canton and its six plants, the company said.
   The Cleveland-based LTV Steel said completion of the sale is
targeted for June 30 and is subject to the approval of U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in New York, which has jurisdiction over LTV
Corp.'s reorganization proceedings.
   In 1986, the Dallas-based LTV Corp., parent company of LTV
Steel, filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of the U.S.
Bankruptcy Code.
   LTV announced last November that it wanted to sell or find a
business partner for its Warren plant, which is the largest steel
mill remaining in the Mahoning Valley. The plant has about 2,200
employees.
   LTV described the Renco Group as a privately held concern with
15 diversified manufacturing and distribution operations nationwide.
   All employees at the Warren plant and the Republic Drainage
plants, including management, are expected to be retained, LTV said.
   LTV's coke plant in Warren is not included in the sale and will
continue to be part of LTV Steel, the company said.
   LTV President David H. Hoag said repairs to the Warren blast
furnace will be completed as scheduled later this summer.
   ``We believe this sale of the Warren Works and the drainage
products plants is in the best interest of LTV Steel, the affected
employees and local communities. We urge the employees, their
unions and the communities of the Mahoning Valley to extend their
welcome and cooperation to Renco as it becomes a major employer and
force in the local economy,'' Hoag said in a statement.
   U.S. Rep. James A. Traficant, D-Ohio, said he was informed of
the sales this morning by LTV officials. Traficant represents the
Mahoning Valley area.
   ``The good news is that they will retain all management and
hourly workers,'' said Traficant. ``The questionable news however
is that the group has very limited activity in the steel industry.
However, our local people have turned the plant around and made it
profitable.''
   Hoag said last fall that the sale would fit in with the
company's plans to concentrate its operations and capital
investment primarily in three flat-rolled facilities in Cleveland,
East Chicago, Ind., and Hennepin, Ill.
   The Warren plant has an annual raw steel production capacity of
1.5 million tons, the company said. It produces hot and cold rolled
sheet and strip steel, hot-dipped galvanized sheet steel, silicon
steel and terne plate.
   Republic Drainage buys half of the zinc-coated steel shiopped
out of the Warren Works. Republic Drainage employs 150 people at
plants in Canton; Owego, N.Y.; Charlotte, N.C.; Harrisburg, Pa.;
Bristol, Tenn. and Seneca, S.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0319 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chrysler-Kenosha     05-11 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Kenosha,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler union withdrawing suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers Local 72 is withdrawing
a suit seeking to prevent Chrysler Corp. and the city of Detroit
from using federal money to move subcompact car production from
Kenosha to Detroit, the local's bargaining chief said.
   ``We're going to drop that one,'' Rudy Kuzel said Tuesday.
   ``They (company negotiators) asked for that because of some of
the economics they were compelled to give us. The lawsuit was a
bargaining chip.''
   The union lawsuit filed in February charged that Chrysler and
Detroit were illegally using a federal grant to remodel Chrysler's
Detroit plant for work it planned to move this July from Kenosha.
   Chrysler since has announced it will build the subcompact cars
in Kenosha until the end of the year, when it will stop all auto
assembly and stamping operations at Kenosha.
   Kuzel said Chrysler agreed to increased pension and other
monetary benefits for about 6,500 hourly workers and 8,000 retirees
because it did not want to risk $50 million in federal money it
would have lost had the union suit in U.S. District Court been
successful.
   The contract, which is to cover about 5,500 workers Chrysler
intends to lay off or retire at the end of the year, and about 900
hourly workers it will retain in its engine division, gives workers
severance and retirement options.
   Chrysler also has promised to keep the engine division at
Kenosha open for four years from Sept. 15, when the local contract
becomes effective.
   The portion of the contract that governs those who will be laid
off is a two-year agreement, Kuzel said in outlining the pact
Tuesday for union members who were to vote on it today.
   The contract proposal calls for return of $8,000 to $10,000 owed
each worker under an employee investment plan used to help then
financially-strapped American Motors Corp.
   Kuzel said workers would get the money back over two years but
would not get any interest or bonus payments. That would amount to
a total of about $58 million. Chrysler bought AMC last year.
   Kuzel said Chrysler also added $5 million to a $15 million job
bank fund that will be used to pay full wages to eligible workers
as long as the money lasts.
   The proposal also calls for payments of about $100 a week to
each laid-off worker under the union's supplemental unemployment
benefit fund.
</TEXT>
