<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Saturn-SpringHill Adv16   05-11 0916</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Saturn-Spring Hill, Adv 16,0946</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 16 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Spring Hill Wonders What Its Future Holds</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NS1 of May 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABIGAIL WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every morning for the past seven or
eight years, a half-dozen men have met for coffee and cigarettes at
the oval table in the rear of Spring Hill's only restaurant, Poplar
House.
   The ``Roundtable,'' as the group of contractors and builders is
sometimes called, has watched with skepticism as the sleepy
Southern town prepares for its transformation into a regional
automaking center.
   Spring Hill, population 1,100, is the home of General Motors
Corp.'s multibillion-dollar Saturn plant, which is scheduled to
begin producing cars in 1990.
   But whether the investment is paying adequate dividends for
Spring Hill is a question that still sparks debate over morning
coffee here.
   Saturn is located in a kind of never-never land, on 2,450 acres
that are not taxed by any county, town or state government and that
officially lie in no town.
   ``It is its own empire,'' said James Brewer, a 68-year-old
engineer who has lived in Spring Hill for 40 years and is an
acknowledged leader of the ``Roundtable.''
   Brewer thinks Spring Hill is missing its chances to cash in on
the growth Saturn will bring to the area once its 3,000 employees
begin work.
   He abhors Mayor George Jones' efforts to toughen development
laws, which impose impact fees on new building and make it harder
for developers to erect fast-food restaurants, convenience stores
and the like.
   One regulation that particularly bothers Brewer is a new
ordinance that restricts the size of business signs to 2 feet by 2
feet.
   Everyone agrees they want to ensure their quality of life, but
to Brewer, quality of life includes fast food and the fast
development that has been experienced by other Southern boom towns.
   ``They're not doing anything to encourage people,'' Brewer said
of the town's stance toward developers.
   To the mayor, quality of life comes with controlled growth. For
example, he views the erratic building that has occurred around
Nashville in the past 10 years as incompatible with Spring Hill's
goals. If prepared, Spring Hill can avoid the overburdened roads
and services that frustrate Nashville residents, Jones said.
   GM announced in 1985 that it would build a $5 billion plant in
Spring Hill as a joint venture with the United Auto Workers. The
state, anxious to land the plant, promised to build a $50 million
highway to the town and provide $20 million to train workers the
plant would need.
   Almost all the Saturn employees will be UAW members who were
laid off in other states by GM.
   In return, Saturn agreed to make payments in lieu of taxes to
Maury County, which distributes money to neighboring towns.
   Land speculation cooled somewhat when GM said it would halve its
planned production at the plant to 250,000 cars a year. In fact,
more homes were built in 1980, before Saturn arrived, than in 1987.
But for every fallow field in Spring Hill there is a realtor's sign
advertising its availability, and even the skeptics admit the place
is bound to change as the startup date for Saturn nears.
   Within two years, the town will probably be unrecognizable.
Developers have begun submitting plans to build tracts of homes for
the newcomers. The largest proposal yet, by developer Howell R.
Pettigrew of Arlington, Texas, proposes building about 3,100
multifamily homes and 1,000 single-family homes on 11,000 acres off
the Saturn Parkway over a 20-year period.
   Pettigrew also plans to develop 195 acres for commercial use and
270 acres for industrial use, said Steve Campbell, who is working
on the proposal for Pettigrew.
   ``It's advanced Spring Hill probably 10 to 20 years already,''
Mayor Jones said of Saturn's effect on the town.
   The town has advanced, in Jones' view, by increasing its police
force from two to seven full-time officers, by building a town hall
to grow into and by updating its zoning regulations.
   The $1.2 million town hall, built with money from Saturn, moved
out of its one-room trailer (which was also donated by Saturn) to a
building on a 165-acre complex on a hill off Main Street. Called
``The Town Center at Spring Hill,'' the development eventually will
feature restaurants, stores and multifamily homes.
   Despite such plans, contractor Ray Williams is among those who
believe Spring Hill is chasing away developers by requiring them to
pay impact fees for services.
   ``The only thing I've ever built in Spring Hill is my house and
that'll probably be the only thing I ever build,'' Williams said.
   Williams, like Brewer, believes landowners should be able to do
as they please with their land. Farmers ``don't want people telling
them what to do,'' said Williams.
   Zoning regulations, such as the one governing sign size,
discourage prosperity, he said.
   ``Everybody in the country wants to go to Las Vegas to see those
signs, but who in the hell wants to go to Spring Hill?''
   Spring Hill resident Don Hickman, an engineer with South Central
Bell, is one who views the slow lurch into the future gladly.
   ``In the long term, Spring Hill will be a very attractive place
to live because of the strict zoning laws. We're not faced with the
tenement type projects,'' he said.
   ``We may have some lean years in Spring Hill, but in the long
run it's going to pay off.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 16</NOTE>
