<2ND_LINE>BC-Saturn-Construction, Adv 16,0513</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 16 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Saturn: Top Secret Import Weapon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Saturn-Spring Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABIGAIL WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manufacturing site for the Saturn
car lies between the towns of Spring Hill and Columbia, obscured
from view by a manmade rolling hillside bordered by a bright white
picket fence.
   After Saturn arrived, both towns annexed land as close to the
plant as possible, to take advantage of the housing and commercial
development that will follow the completion of a new parkway to the
plant.
   Despite their neighborly proximity, townspeople know little
about what goes on inside the compound. Saturn officials say the
town wanted them to place the plant out of view, while their
neighbors occasionally grumble that they are being intentionally
shut out.
   But Saturn is intended to be a mystery, a successful top-secret
weapon against import cars. General Motors Corp., which funds
Saturn as a subsidiary rather than a division of the company,
expects the plant to turn a profit immediately, said Laurie Kay, a
spokeswoman for Saturn.
   Almost a fourth of the plant has been completed since
construction began in June 1987. Saturn plans to offer a family of
Saturn cars _ subcompact and compacts _ in 1990 for the 1991 model
year, Ms. Kay said.
   State legislators who visited the sprawling site in March viewed
the half-completed powertrain building where car engines and
transmissions will be built. Construction also has begun on three
other buildings where cars will be assembled and painted before
rolling off the line.
   Part of the plan to make Saturn competitive with imports
involves approaching production work differently, and Saturn
officials _ along with their partners in the venture,
representatives of the United Auto Workers union _ are adopting
management techniques developed by the Japanese, said Ms. Kay.
   Employees will be involved in all aspects of production, from
understanding the cost of supplies to sales, she said.
   They will be on salaries rather than the traditional hourly wage
rates, with 20 percent of their pay based on the performance of the
company, Ms. Kay said.
   Saturn jobs will first be offered to the estimated 300,000 UAW
members who have been laid off around the United States by GM, said
Ms. Kay. About 6,000 people have applied for the 3,000 jobs that
are to be filled by mid-1989.
   The plant is designed to produce 250,000 cars a year initially.
GM plans to increase production, depending on the auto's reception
by car buyers.
   Saturn has begun reviewing about 1,700 applications for a
network of dealerships, which are expected to reach 123 cities by
the end of the first model year.
   Saturn has sent employees to Japan to study Japanese automaking
procedures, as well as to Germany, said Ms. Kay.
   ``We're looking very hard at everything. We're not inventing
everything,'' she said.
   ``We are taking a fresh look at what we do.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 16</NOTE>
