<HEAD>Soybeans Open Sharply Higher; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices opened sharply higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to the Agriculture
Department's latest supply-and-demand estimates. Grain futures were
mixed.
   The soybean market's early gains of as much as 9{ cents a bushel
were expected after the USDA revised downward its estimate of the
U.S. soybean stockpile, predicting stocks would dwindle from 275
million bushels on this Aug. 31 to 145 million bushels a year later.
   The USDA also reduced its estimate for this year's Brazilian
soybean harvest to 17.6 million metric tons from 18 million metric
tons.
   ``This adds to the general feeling or perception that soybean
stocks are shrinking very quickly,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst
in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   The USDA report, issued Tuesday afternoon, was considered
neutral for corn futures, which opened slightly higher, and was
construed as somewhat bearish for wheat.
   The government predicted this year's winter wheat harvest would
be about 4 percent larger than last year's and that prediction
weighed on wheat futures this morning, Spilka said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.01{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to
1 cent higher with May at $1.99} a bushel; oats were \ cent lower
to \ cent higher with May at $1.62 a bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents
to 9{ cents higher with May at $7.14 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower and pork futures were higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .37 cent lower with June at 782.80
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .232 cent lower to .65 cent
higher with May at 79.97 cents a pound; hogs were .17 cent to .53
cent higher with June at 51.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .35 cent to .53 cent higher with May at 51.85 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
