<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     05-11 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0401</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was holding steady at sharply
lower levels at around midday today, weakened by investors' anxiety
about the prospect of higher interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 39.96 points at
1,963.69 at noon EDT, close to its level of an hour earlier but
widened from its initial losses.
   The broader market also showed deep declines. Losing stocks
outstripped advancers by about 6-to-1 on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 1,269 issues losing, only 182 gaining and 372
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board was 103.35 million shares, up from 61.95
million traded by the same time on Tuesday.
   The anxiety about higher interest rates was fueled today by
comments by British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson that
there could be an internationally coordinated boost in rates.
   Lawson, who made the comments in an interview with the Wall
Street Journal's overseas editions that was published today, noted
that a coordinated effort by West Germany, Japan and other leading
nations to hike interest rates ``is certainly possible'' following
the Federal Reserve's increase in short-term rates to curb U.S.
inflation.
   Separately, White House economist Beryl Sprinkel confirmed that
the Fed has nudged up short-term rates in recent weeks. He defended
the move as making sense in the face of a strong economy and recent
growth in the money supply.
   Some observers and market players expect the Fed to raise its
key discount rate, the interest it charges big financial
institutions, possibly this week.
   Market analysts point out that hauntingly similar jitters about
rising interest rates were a big factor behind October's stock
collapse, and those memories are still fresh in the minds of
nervous investors.
   ``The major problem with the stock market has been the rise in
rates,'' said Larry Wachtel, an analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   The NYSE's composite index was down 2.20 at 143.55.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had lost
3.97 at 295.84.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Con Edison was down \
at 42\, Houston Industries had slipped [ to 29~, Gillette had
dropped 1[ to 35|, Gulf States Utilities had declined \ to 5[,
General Electric had lost { at 39 and Philips Petroleum was down \
at 17[.
</TEXT>
