<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-StockMarket-Regan 1stLd-Writethru f0068 05-11 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Market-Regan, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0068,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Regan Calls on Congress to Ban Index Arbitrage Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Program Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 6 grafs with comments by futures exchange officials;
also running on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Treasury Secretary Donald T. Regan
called on Congress today to ban index arbitrage trading, saying the
computer-driven transactions are undermining public confidence in
the stock market.
   ``I don't think it's too extreme to say that overall confidence
in our free market system is threatened by this sort of scandal,''
Regan told the Senate Banking Committee. ``And that's what it is _
a scandal.''
   Regan, former chief executive of Wall Street's Merrill Lynch &
Co., has been the focus of attention recently for a book he has
written on his years as White House chief of staff under President
Reagan. Most attention has been drawn to his revelation that First
Lady Nancy Reagan regularly consulted an astrologer about the
president's schedule.
   Before Regan spoke, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., read Regan's
horoscope to him, which said that he could not ``force colleagues
to be more understanding'' until May 17.
   Regan did not respond, but said later that his testimony ``comes
at an interesting time in terms of my own personal activities.''
   Regan said that program trading is ``fundamentally changing and
endangering the basis on which our economy and stock market have
functioned for generations.''
   He said that although individuals still own most stocks,
institutions in recent years have dominated trading.
   ``If the public feels that the markets are rigged, not only in
favor of the big guy, but also in favor of some unidentified
computer-based trading strategy, then confidence in our markets,
indeed in our system, will plummet,'' Regan said.
   Regan called on the nation's financial markets and the federal
agencies that regulate them to impose their own restrictions on
program trading.
   In index arbitrage, traders use computers to profit from price
discrepancies between the stock and futures markets by
simultaneously buying in one market and selling in the other.
   At the same hearing, Charles R. Schwab, who heads his own
discount brokerage firm, said program trading should be totally
abolished.
   ``The individual investor in this country is angry,'' Schwab
said. ``Most of all, he is angry about Washington's failure to
enact reforms needed to promote greater stability in the securities
markets.''
   Regan and Schwab's comments came a day after five big Wall
Street firms announced they have halted index arbitrage trading for
their own accounts as a means of restoring investor confidence in
the stock market.
   However, Leo Melamed, chairman of the executive committee of the
board of governors of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, defended
index arbitrage today at a breakfast meeting with reporters in
Washington.
   He acknowledged that some individual investors believe program
trading destabilizes the market, but he maintained that index
arbitrage does just the opposite because it ensurse that stock and
futures prices closely track each other.
   ``I'm not going to defend perception,'' he said. ``The reality
is it is not a factor (in the volatility). Index arbitrage was and
is a stabilizing factor.''
   ``I don't believe there's many individual investors who
understand the issue,'' he added.
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange trades the most popular futures
contract, which is based on the Standard and Poor's 500.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Retail     05-11 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Retail,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woolworth, Wal-Mart Report Strong First Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   F.W. Woolworth Co. and Wal-Mart Stores Inc., two bright spots in
a mostly dismal first quarter for the retailing industry, on
Wednesday reported robust increases in their earnings for the
period.
   Woolworth said its net income for the three months ended April
30 totaled $35 million, or 54 cents per share, up nearly 21 percent
from $29 million, or 43 cents per share, in the first three months
of fiscal 1987.
   Sales rose to $1.71 billion from $1.53 billion.
   The first quarter of the retail fiscal year was a disappointment
for many storeowners as consumers continued to spend cautiously.
Woolworth's sales dipped more than 5 percent in April, but the
company fared better than most of the other big retailers in the
first two months of the year.
   Wal-Mart saw no letdown in its business during the quarter.
   The rapidly-expanding discount chain reported earnings of $153.6
million, or 27 cents a share, up nearly 40 percent from $110.4
million, or 19 cents a share, in the first quarter of 1987.
   Sales totaled $4.28 billion, up from $3.21 billion.
   Woolworth is believed to be a possible takeover target for Dart
Group Corp., which recently asked for federal permission to acquire
up to 15 percent of Woolworth stock. Dart has not yet made a bid
for Woolworth.
   Woolworth operates Woolworth general merchandise stores and
specialty retailers including Kinney Shoe, Foot Locker and Lady
Foot Locker.
   Wal-Mart operates more than 1,200 discount stores in 24 states.
</TEXT>
