<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     05-11 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0427</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices dropped on Wall Street today, as
anxiety about the prospect for higher interest rates was heightened
by a rise in the prime lending rate by two major banks.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 44.27 points at
1,959.38 at 2 p.m. EDT, widened from its losses earlier in the
session.
   The broader market also showed deep declines. Losing stocks
outstripped advancers by about 7-to-1 on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 1,375 issues losing, only 200 gaining and 336
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board was 138.82 million shares.
   Citibank and Chase Manhattan Bank boosted their prime rates by a
half percentage point to 9 percent. They were the first increases
in the prime since just before October's stock market collapse.
   Chase was the first big bank to raise the key rate, which is
watched closely because bankers use it as a base rate for loans to
many businesses and for consumer loans, including mortgages.
Chase's move was announced around noon today after Wall Street had
already sustained sharp losses on interest-rate fears.
   ``It tends to reduce confidence in the stock market,'' said Hugh
Johnson, senior vice president of First Albany Corp. in Albany,
N.Y., referring to the increase in the prime rate.
   Higher interest rates, by raising the cost of borrowing, tend to
dampen companies' expansion plans and investments.
   The hike in the prime came against a background of growing
edginess about the outlook for interest rates.
   British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson indicated
earlier today that there could be an internationally coordinated
boost in rates.
   Lawson, who made the comments in an interview with the Wall
Street Journal's overseas editions that was published today, noted
that a coordinated effort by West Germany, Japan and other leading
nations to hike interest rates ``is certainly possible'' following
the Federal Reserve's increase in short-term rates to curb U.S.
inflation.
   Separately, White House economist Beryl Sprinkel confirmed that
the Fed has nudged up short-term rates in recent weeks. He defended
the move as making sense in the face of a strong economy and recent
growth in the money supply.
   Some observers and market players expect the Fed to raise its
key discount rate, the interest it charges big financial
institutions, possibly this week.
   The NYSE's composite index was down 2.59 at 143.16.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had
dropped 4.72 to 295.09.
</TEXT>
