<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Oil     05-11 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Oil,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Royal-Dutch Shell Quarterly Profit Jumps 18.4 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Companies, the world's
biggest oil concern, said Wednesday its net profit rose 18.4
percent in the first quarter from a year ago.
   Royal Dutch-Shell said earnings from its marine, marketing and
chemicals businesses improved but that exploration and production
earnings were down due to the combination of lower crude oil
prices, reduced natural gas sales and the strengthening of sterling
against the dollar.
   It said its net profit increased to 822 million pounds in the
first three months of 1987 from 694 million pounds in the same
period a year ago.
   Using average rates of exchange over the respective quarters,
that worked out to $1.48 billion, vs. $1.07 billion in the first
three months of 1987.
   Special items affecting the latest quarterly earnings were a
gain of 106 million pounds, or $200 million, from the sale of a
Hong Kong property and estimated after-tax inventory losses of 78
million pounds, or $147 million.
   The year-earlier period included inventory gains of 92 million
pounds, or $174 million dollars, Royal Dutch said.
   British companies' accounting method cannot be directly compared
to the method used by American companies, because of differences in
determining the value of inventories.
   Using the American method, Royal Dutch-Shell said, its net
profit spurted 49.5 percent to 900 million pounds, or $1.7 billion,
from 602 million pounds, or $1.14 billion.
   Royal Dutch-Shell, which is based in The Hague, the Netherlands,
and in London, said sales fell 5.2 percent to 13.63 billion pounds,
or $24.9 billion from 14.37 billion pounds.
   In dollars, that worked out to $24.9 billion in the latest
quarter, when the pound was stronger than the dollar, vs. $22.13
billion, in the year-ago period, when it was weaker.
   Royal Dutch Petroleum Co., the Dutch arm, controls 60 percent of
the company. Shell Transport and Trading Co. PLC, the group's
British arm, controls the remaining 40 percent.
   ``The outlook for exploration and production earnings depends on
whether the increases seen in crude oil prices since early March
can be sustained, despite recurring volatility,'' Royal Dutch-Shell
said in a statement.
</TEXT>
