<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-11 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Soar On USDA Data; Grain Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to the
Agriculture Department's latest supply and demand report. Grain
futures retreated slightly.
   The surge in soybean prices was expected after the USDA, in a
report issued Tuesday afternoon, predicted the U.S. soybean
stockpile would dwindle from 275 million bushels this Aug. 31 to
145 million bushels a year later.
   The USDA also reduced its estimate for this year's Brazilian
soybean harvest from 18 million metric tons to 17.6 million metric
tons. A smaller Brazilian harvest could increase world demand for
U.S. soybeans.
   ``This just reaffirms the uptrend in the market and the bullish
attitude of the trade in the soybean complex, particularly in the
beans,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Tuesday's USDA report was seen as neutral for corn futures,
which finished modestly lower in Wednesday's session.
   The government predicted this year's winter wheat harvest would
be about 4 percent larger than last year's and that prediction
weighed on wheat futures Wednesday, Spilka said.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.03 a bushel; corn was 2 cents to
3\ cents lower with May at $1.97\ a bushel; oats were 3\ cents to
3} cents lower with May at 1.58{ a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to
9\ cents higher with May at $7.12 a bushel.
</TEXT>
