<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AmericanMedical     05-11 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Medical,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sale of 37 Hospitals in 10 States Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Medical International Inc.
will sell 37 hospitals in 10 states to an employee group in a
transaction valued at $910 million, the company said Wednesday.
   The announcement follows sale of 15 hospitals and layoffs of
2,000 workers in the last 18 months in an attempt to boost earnings
at the hospital company. It considerably exceeds Chairman Walter L.
Weisman's prediction after the company's annual meeting in January
that between five and 20 hospitals would be sold in the next three
years.
   American Medical said the acute-care hospitals, which among them
have 4,200 beds, would be sold to a new company owned primarily by
an employees' stock ownership plan to be established at the new
company.
   The new company will be headed by Kenneth S. George, present
director of American Medical's Southwest region, and will have
headquarters in Dallas, the company said. American Medical will
retain an interest through an issue of preferred stock in the new
entity, which has not yet been named, said American Medical
spokesman Mick Taylor.
   American Medical is seeking bank loans to finance the planned
$600 million cash portion of the sale, Taylor said.
   The rest of the transaction would bring American Medical $310
million in preferred stock in the new company, assumed debt and
notes, the company said. The proceeds, estimated at $450 million
after taxes and expenses, will be used to pay off debt and buy back
stock.
   The company retains 48 hospitals and five psychiatric hospitals
in the United States and 22 hospitals and three psyciatric
hospitals overseas.
   ``This sale will allow AMI to focus singularly on improving the
earnings per share generated by our remaining asset base,'' Weisman
said.
   The hospitals to be sold are in Texas, California, Oklahoma,
Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Missouri, Arkansas, South Carolina
and Georgia.
   Those hospitals had combined net revenue of $507 million in 1987.
   American Medical, which in March reported second-quarter profit
fell 13.9 percent to $24.1 million, is under pressure from the
holder of 5 percent of its stock to sell marginal operations. For
the first half of its fiscal year, profit rose 11.8 percent, to
$63.3 million, over the year earlier.
</TEXT>
