<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Gulf&Western     05-11 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf & Western,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf & Western Announces New Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf & Western Inc., a major entertainment,
publishing and financial services company, announced another stock
buyback program Wednesday, its third in five years.
   The company said its board authorized the purchase of up to 10
million shares of its common stock in the open market. The plan,
designed to bolster the value of the shares that will remain on the
market, follows the completion of a 24 million-share buyback
adopted in 1985.
   The latest repurchase plan included 5.2 million shares snapped
up in the wake of last October's stock market crash, when scores of
companies bought back their own shares to help stave off further
price declines.
   Martin S. Davis, chairman and chief executive officer, said the
buybacks had enhanced shareholder value ``by giving each
shareholder increased ownership of the company.''
   Since the initial buyback was launched in 1983, about 44 million
shares have been repurchased at an average price of slightly over
$21 a share, the company said. Gulf & Western said it had about 118
million shares of common stock outstanding after adjustment for a
2-for-1 stock split on May 2.
   Analysts said Gulf & Western shares traded strongly on the New
York Stock Exchange in reaction to the announcement, but were
dragged down 37{ cents to $37 by the market's broad decline. The
Dow Jones industrial average dropped nearly 38 points to 1,965.85.
   The company's stock is up significantly from its 52-week low of
$29.75 a share, and analysts credit management for keeping a high
priority on shareholder interests.
   The buyback announcement follows the company's failed attempt to
acquire Western Publishing Group Inc., a children's book publisher
and commercial printer. Mark Manson of the investment firm
Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette Securities said the company's cash flow
was strong enough to accomplish both the buyback and the
acquisition.
   ``It has strong momentum in its entertainment business,
stability in financial services and a mass of cash,'' said Manson.
   Gulf & Western's publishing holdings include Simon & Shuster,
which publishes books for mass circulation, and Prentice-Hall, an
educational and professional publisher. Its entertainment segment
includes Paramount Pictures.
</TEXT>
