<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0539</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices dropped sharply Wednesday in edgy
trading, weakened by fears of higher interest rates that pushed the
Dow Jones industrial average to a three-month low.
   The key index of 30 premier stocks slid 37.80 points to
1,965.85, its lowest closing level since it closed at 1,961.54 on
Feb. 11. Most of the slippage occurred early in the session.
   Losing issues outstripped gainers by about 7-to-1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 1,363 issues declining, 238 advancing and
367 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 176.72 million shares, up from 131.2
million Tuesday.
   Wall Street's fear of higher interest rates were aggravated by
an announcement from big banks that they had raised their key prime
lending rate from 8.5 percent to 9 percent, the first rise since
the October crash.
   Hauntingly similar jitters about rising interest rates were a
big factor behind the crash _ and those memories are still fresh in
the minds of nervous investors.
   In addition, higher interest rates, by raising the cost of
borrowing, tend to dampen companies' expansion plans and
investments.
   ``The major problem with the stock market has been the rise in
rates,'' said Larry Wachtel, an analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   Chase Manhattan Bank was the first big bank to raise the key
rate, which is watched closely because bankers use it as a base
rate for loans to many businesses and for consumer loans, including
some types of mortgages.
   ``It clearly hit a raw nerve ... this market was clearly
vulnerable,'' said Monte Gordon, vice president and director of
research for Dreyfus Corp.
   The hike in the prime came against a background of growing
edginess about the outlook for interest rates.
   British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson reportedly
suggested that there could be an internationally coordinated boost
in rates.
   Lawson, who was quoted in an interview with the Wall Street
Journal's overseas edition Wednesday, noted that a coordinated
effort by West Germany, Japan and other leading nations to hike
interest rates ``is certainly possible'' following the Federal
Reserve's increase in short-term rates to curb U.S. inflation.
   Separately, White House economist Beryl Sprinkel confirmed that
the Fed has nudged up short-term rates in recent weeks.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Con Edison fell { to
42, General Electric lost } at 38}, AT&T was down \ at 26~, IBM
dropped 2[ to 108}, Texaco declined ] to 50[, Woolworth tumbled 1\
to 52}, American Express fell | to 22~ and Exxon eased { to 43|.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 204.86 million shares.
   The NYSE's composite index fell 2.27 to 143.48.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials declined 5.34 to
294.32, and S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 4.31 at 253.31.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index dropped
4.18 to 295.63.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
closed at 369.24, down 6.19.
</TEXT>
