<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GiantGroup     05-11 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Giant Group,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Controlled by Media General Suitor Reports Five-Fold
Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burt Sugarman, the investor engaged
in a contentious takeover battle with Media General Inc., announced
that profits for his cement and game show company increased
five-fold in the first quarter.
   Earnings for Giant Group rose to $741,000, or 16 cents a share,
from $113,000, or 2 cents a share in the first qarter of 1987,
Sugarman announced Wednesday.
   Sales for the quarter ended March 31 were $15.1 million, up from
$14.9 million in the first quarter of 1987.
   Giant owns 24 percent of Barris Industries, producer of the
``Gong Show'' and ``Dating Game'' television shows.
   Sugarman didn't respond to a telephone request for an
explanation of the increase in profits.
   On Tuesday, Media General, the Richmond, Va.,-based newspaper
and television station owner, rejected Sugarman's latest bid of $70
per share for its stock. The offer, an increase over his previous
bid of $61.50 a share, was the latest round in an acrimonious legal
and financial battle over the takeover attempt.
</TEXT>
