<DOCNO> AP880511-0352 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 2153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-UnionAds     05-11 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Union Ads,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO Ad Campaign Aimed at Updating Union Image</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO on Wednesday said a new $13
million broadcast advertising campaign was designed to show that
unions, like their workers, are interested in fairness, justice and
life outside the job.
   The ads, which all end with a chorus singing ``America works
best when we say union yes,'' have begun appearing on the
television networks and in 13 local markets. The 30-second spots
are expected to reach more than nine out of 10 of all American
homes at least four times.
   Radio spots will be aired as well, including one that urges
listeners to ask Congress to override President Reagan's expected
veto of the trade legislation. Unions have been pushing a provision
of the bill requiring mandatory notice of plant closings for large
companies.
   At a closed-circuit TV news conference to the 13 cities where
the TV ads will be shown, AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said
``the labor movement has a long, well-documented record of fighting
for the rights and the standard of living of working Americans. But
in spite of that, there are still many Americans who have serious
misconceptions about what unions do and about whether or not they
are necessary in today's work place.''
   ``The goal of `Union Yes,''' he said, ``is to talk directly with
American workers about the value of unions in the work place today.
One of the best ways to do that now is through television.''
   Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of America,
told reporters in Washington that the ads ``fill a need to let the
population at large know what the trade union movement stands for.''
   He said many Americans have ``a stereotype of unions and union
members. They see a heavyset fellow smoking a cigar and wearing a
$500 suit.''
   One commercial focuses on women, with a woman saying unions have
ensured fairness in promotions. Another, obviously pregnant, woman
says that because of unions she will be able to take time off to
have her baby and come back to a job.
   The first phase of the ad campaign runs through mid-June. The
second phase picks up on Labor Day in September. The campaign,
which is paid for with union dues, is expected to last two years.
   The ads will star actors Jack Lemmon, Tyne Daly and Howard
Hesseman.
   Local TV ads will run during May and June in New York, Los
Angeles, Chicago, Philadelphia, San Francisco, Boston, Detroit,
Cleveland, Pittsburgh, Washington, Atlanta, Nashville, Tenn., and
Orlando, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
